comment: qualitative description of the amount present (or contained) of some type of stuff (e.g., (qualitativeContent(Leaf Chlorophyll veryHighAmountOf)).
label: Qualitative Content
qualitativeContent

comment: (feelsSensationInRegionAtLevel AGT BODYPARTTYPE QUANT) means that the PerceptualAgent AGT feels on its body, in the area specified by BODYPARTTYPE, the quantity of the SensoryQuantity indicated by QUANT. For example, Cyc's knowledge base contains an assertion that the very same part of one's body doesn't feel both hot and cold at the same time. feelsSensationInRegionAtLevel can also be used to state symptoms, e.g., when you're feverish, your head feels hot.
label: Feels Sensation In Region At Level
feelsSensationInRegionAtLevel

comment: (operatingIncomeForPeriodByAccountingCOC ORG MONEY TIME COC) means MONEY is the operating income (EBIT) of ORG during TIME based on the accounting principles allowed by the AccountingCOC COC.
label: Operating Income For Period By Accounting COC
operatingIncomeForPeriodByAccountingCOC

comment:
A ternary instance of InterArgIsaPredicate (q.v.). (interArgEqualsIsa2_1 RELN INDEPENDENT-ARG DEPENDENT-ARG-COL) means that, when INDEPENDENT-ARG appears as the second argument to RELN, a necessary condition for semantic well-formedness is that the first argument must be an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. That is, (RELN ARG1 INDEPENDENT-ARG ...) is semantically well-formed only if ARG1 is an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL.

For an explanation of semantic well-formedness, see CycLExpression_Assertible and its direct specializations. See interArgEqualsIsa for a similar but more general predicate that is quintary, allowing the user to specify the positions of the independent and dependent arguments.
label: Inter Arg Equals Isa 2 1
interArgEqualsIsa2-1

comment: (publicationLocationForStyleAndRendering WORK STYLE RENDERING STRING) means that STRING is the canonical string used to express the publication location for WORK according to STYLE-SPECIFICATION, for rendering using MARKUP-LANGUAGE.
label: Publication Location For Style And Rendering
publicationLocationForStyleAndRendering

comment: (consumptionAmountDuring PT PRODUCT-TYPE THING AMOUNT) means that the NonNegativeScalarInterval AMOUNT is a measure of the amount of instances of the ProductType PRODUCT-TYPE consumed by the instance of PartiallyTangible PT during the temporal extent of the TemporalThing THING. PT might, for example, be a Country, a Business, or a household (CohabitationUnit). THING will often be a calendar time period; but it may also be, for instance, a particular Event. If AMOUNT is a Rate, AMOUNT indicates the average rate of consumption of instances of PRODUCT-TYPE by PT during the temporal extent of THING.
label: Consumption Amount During
consumptionAmountDuring

comment:
An ExistentialQuantifier (q.v.) that corresponds to the standard existential quantifier of predicate calculus. thereExists takes as its arguments an #$ELVariable and an #$ELSentence-Assertible (such that, typically, the former occurs free in the latter). (thereExists VAR SENT) means that there is at least one thing THING such that SENT is true of it. That is, if some given CycL term that denotes THING were substituted for each free occurrence of VAR in SENT, the result would be a true sentence. For example, `(thereExists ?X (mother ?X GeorgeWBush))' means that George W. Bush has a (i.e. at least one) mother; and

(forAll ?PER (implies (isa ?PER Person) (thereExists ?MOM (mother ?MOM ?PER))))

means that every person has a mother. Note that some existential statements can be represented more tersely in CycL using other instances of ExistentialQuantifier, such as thereExistAtMost or thereExistExactly. Also see the #$cyclistNotes for thereExists.
label: There Exists
thereExists

comment: (adoptionTypeOfNormByAgent NORM AGENT ADOPT-TYPE) means that ADOPT-TYPE is the collection of events in which AGENT adopts the norm NORM.
label: Adoption Type Of Norm By Agent
adoptionTypeOfNormByAgent

comment: A variable-arity MetaRelation used for stating that a given PartiallyCommutativeRelation (q.v.) is "commutative" with respect to two or more argument-places, including all argument-places that come after the ordinally highest one that is explicitly specified. (commutativeInArgsAndRest RELN ARGNUM-1 ARGNUM-2 ... ARGNUM-N) means that RELN is commutative in its ARGNUM-1th, ARGNUM-2th, ..., and ARGNUM-Nth arguments-places, along with any of its argument-places whose ordinal positions are greater than the greatest of the ARGNUM-i. Thus RELN admits unrestricted permutation among any of these arguments. More precisely (and assuming without loss of generality that ARGNUM-N is the numerically greatest of the ARGNUM-i): (i) if RELN is a Predicate that holds of a given argument-sequence SEQ, then RELN also holds of any other sequence SEQ-PERMUTE obtainable from SEQ by permuting some or all of SEQ's ARGNUM-1th, ARGNUM-2th, ..., ARGNUM-Nth, and subsequent items (while leaving all of SEQ's other items unchanged). (ii) if RELN is a Function_Denotational that associates a given argument-sequence SEQ with the value VALUE, then RELN also associates any sequence SEQ-PERMUTE (as described above) with VALUE. For example, (commutativeInArgsAndRest commutativeInArgsAndRest 2) has as a consequence that whenever a sentence of the form (commutativeInArgsAndRest RELN 2 3 5) holds, so do the corresponding sentences (commutativeInArgsAndRest RELN 2 5 3), (commutativeInArgsAndRest RELN 3 2 5), and so on. Note that since RELN is an instance of PartiallyCommutativeRelation, it must have at least two argument-places that are commutative with each other and at least one that is _not_ commutative with any other argument-place. See also commutativeInArgs.
label: Commutative In Args And Rest
commutativeInArgsAndRest

comment: A quaternary InterArgRelnPredicate (q.v.). (interArgReln RELN M N BINPRED) means that a ground atomic formula (or "GAF"; see CycLClosedAtomicSentence) or closed non-atomic term (or "NAT"; see CycLClosedNonAtomicTerm) built from RELN is semantically well-formed only if BINPRED holds between the Mth and Nth arguments to RELN (in that order) in the GAF/NAT. That is, a formula (RELN ..ARGM..ARGN..) is semantically well-formed only if (BINPRED ARGM ARGN) holds. For further explanation of semantic well-formedness, see CycLExpression_Assertible and its direct specializations. See also the more specific binary InterArgRelnPredicates, each of which is defined for two particular argument-places of RELN (e.g. interArgReln1_2 and interArgReln4_2).
label: Inter Arg Reln
interArgReln

comment: (softwareParameterSetToValueInSoftwareObject SOFTWARE-PARAMETER VALUE SOFTWARE-OBJECT) means that the value of SOFTWARE-PARAMETER [see softwareParameterValue] is set to the value VALUE at some point during any execution of SOFTWARE-OBJECT (an instance of SoftwareObject). This normally means that the value changes, but it is possible that the value it is set to is its prior value.
label: Software Parameter Set To Value In Software Object
softwareParameterSetToValueInSoftwareObject

comment: (iGPertinentPredForTypeInArg PRED COL N) means that when an InformationGathering IG bears infoGatheredAbout to an instance INST of COL, the sentence resulting from placing INST in arg N of PRED (and filling all other argument positions with distinct free variables) is likely to be pertinent to IG.
label: IG Pertinent Pred For Type In Arg
iGPertinentPredForTypeInArg

comment: Actually, the name should be shouldMeetSpecification, but that's too long. In other words, meetsSpecification won't go away if there is a discrepancy between the thing and what its specification says. If (meetsSpecification O S R), it is usually consistent for O to fill in as R in S.
label: Meets Specification
meetsSpecification

comment:
A RelativeLocationalPredicate that relates tangible objects of the same (specified) type that are located next to or beside each other. (nextToLikeObjects OBJ1 OBJ2 TYPE) means that OBJ1 and OBJ2 are both instances of TYPE, and OBJ1 is spatially next to OBJ2. More precisely: (i) OBJ1 and OBJ2 are both instances of TYPE, (ii) OBJ1 and OBJ2 are near each other, (iii) no other member of TYPE is between OBJ1 and OBJ2, and (iv) no other member of TYPE is both nearer to OBJ1 and in the same general direction from OBJ1 as OBJ2 is, or vice versa.

One person directly in front of another person in a queue, two houses that are next door to each other, adjacent squares on a chessboard, and sequential steps on a raised ladder are all examples of pairs of objects related by nextToLikeObjects. For a specialization of this predicate that is restricted to non-vertical arrangements (and thus does not hold of the ladder steps), see nextToLike_Horizontally.

Note that two things can be related by nextToLikeObjects even though there is an _unlike_ object (i.e. something not an instance of TYPE) between them. For example, two houses might be nextToLikeObjects each other despite the fact that there is a fence, tree, or driveway between them. Note also that when two objects stand in the relation nextToLikeObjects with respect to some collection, it follows that there is some ArrangementOfLikeObjects (q.v.) having at least those two objects as members.
label: Next To Like Objects
nextToLikeObjects

comment: A predicate for indicating the level of toxicity a substance has (under normal circumstances) when it penetrates (e.g. by an arrow or insect stinger) the external surface of some instance of some type of BiologicalLivingObject. (penetrativeToxicityFor SUBSTANCE BLO-TYPE TOX) means that under normal circumstances SUBSTANCE will have a toxicity level of TOX when it penetrates the surface layer of a BiologicalLivingObject BLO via, e.g., a sharp object or body part, where BLO is a typical instance of BLO-TYPE. See also PenetrativeToxinType.
label: Penetrative Toxicity For
penetrativeToxicityFor

comment: (symptomOnsetRateInConditionType SYM AIL RATE) means that when an instance of SYM is a subevent or true symptom of an instance of AIL, it often has an onset rate of RATE.
label: Symptom Onset Rate In Condition Type
symptomOnsetRateInConditionType
Amenable To Be
amenable-ToBe
comment: amenable_ToBe is a deontic operator in Cyc. For each #$ELSentence-Assertible PROP, (amenable_ToBe PROP) means that it is amenable that PROP. amenable_ToBe is the dual of expected_ToBe, i.e., (amenable_ToBe PROP) is equivalent to (not (expected_ToBe (not PROP))).

`(designatedSecondaryResidence OWNER HOME YEAR)' means that HOME meets certain qualifications set by the IRS, that HOME is not OWNER's primaryResidence, and that OWNER has designated HOME as his/her other home the interest on which can be claimed as a tax deduction for YEAR. A taxpayer may own several secondaryResidences which meet the IRS's qualifications, so being a designatedSecondaryResidence can in part be a matter of choice on the part of the taxpayer.
label: Designated Secondary Residence
designatedSecondaryResidence

comment: (strategyOnOutputYieldsCandidateAnswerChoice STRATEGY QUESTION ANSWER) means that the instance of ProblemSolvingStrategy STRATEGY has determined that ANSWER is a likely answer to QUESTION.
label: Strategy On Output Yields Candidate Answer Choice
strategyOnOutputYieldsCandidateAnswerChoice

comment: A QuintaryPredicate used to state exceptions to the applicability of transitiveViaArg assertions. (transitiveViaArgInverse THING FORMULA PRED BINPRED N)) means that the Nth argument position of PRED is "transitive" with respect to BINPRED except when THING (or a constant that stands in the relation BINPRED to THING) occurs as the Nth argument to PRED in a GAF whose arguments are otherwise identical to those of FORMULA. See also transitiveViaArgInverseExceptions.
label: Transitive Via Arg Exceptions
transitiveViaArgExceptions

comment: This predicate can be used to characterize those rules and CycLAssertions that represent in Cyc fundamental laws of chemistry. Additionally, it is a CycInferenceHeuristicPredicate : rules corresponding to fundamental laws of chemistry are to be preferred in inference [this feature should be considered 'experimental' at this time].
label: Chemical Law
chemicalLaw

comment: (userSelectedCoreferentInUDS UDS PEG1 PEG2) is true if PEG2 has been explicitly selected by the CycInterlocutor user as a coreference target for PEG1. This is a special case of viableProposedCoreferentInUDS (q.v.), which implies that user-selected coreferents must not violate semantic or syntactic constraints on anaphoric reference, as applicable to the more general predicate.
label: User Selected Coreferent In UDS
userSelectedCoreferentInUDS

comment: The expression `objectFound_Indefinite (SEARCH SEEKER OBJECT)' means that a LookingForSomething_Indefinite has succeeded, partially or totally. It says that SEEKER, the performedBy in the SEARCH, has come across an OBJECT of the type that was sought (in whatever sense of coming across the SEEKER thinks is required for having found it) and that SEEKER notices that OBJECT satisfies the searchCriterion_Indefinite associated with the search. Since the arg2 of notices is opaque, it is required that the term in the OBJECT place match the way SEEKER conceives of the OBJECT. This is why the arg3 of this predicate is opaque.
label: Object Found Indefinite
objectFound-Indefinite

comment: (inheritedTermSentences TERM GENL FORMULA) states that FORMULA can be deduced to be a true formula about TERM based on the fact that GENL is one of the generalizations of TERM. In other words, although FORMULA is not usually asserted to be true, it is nevertheless an 'inherited' truth based on a more general truth asserted about the more general concept GENL. See also assertedTermSentences and trueSentence.
label: Inherited Term Sentences
inheritedTermSentences
Ambiguous Node
ambiguousNode
comment: (ambiguousNode NODE) means that NODE has more than one viable semantic interpretation.
The Common Lisp format string ARG2 can be applied to the argument list ARG3 to generate pseudo-English for the Cyc Relation ARG1
label: Gen Format
genFormat

comment: Suppose PRED is a BinaryPredicate that is type-level in at least one argument position, and that INST-PRED is an 'instance-level analog' of PRED that is instance-level in at least one argument position in which PRED is type-level. (instantiatesToRuleMacro MACRO PRED INST-PRED) means that if (PRED ARG1COL ARG2COL) is known to be true, (MACRO INST-PRED ARG1COL ARG2COL) is known to be true. For example, suppose we decide that in a certain reasoning context (colorOfType COL COLOR) means that, for every instance INST of COL, (mainColorOfObject INST COLOR), i.e., that (relationAllInstance mainColorOfObject COL COLOR). We would express this by asserting (instantiatesToRuleMacro relationAllInstance colorOfType mainColorOfObject).
label: Instantiates To Rule Macro
instantiatesToRuleMacro

comment: (complementOfIn SUBCOL1 SUBCOL2 COL) means that SUBCOL1 is the complement of SUBCOL2 in COL. I.e. (partitionedInto COL (ThePartition SUBCOL1 SUBCOL2)). Instances of SUBCOL1 are all the instances of COL which are not instances of SUBCOL2, where SUBCOL2 is a specialization of COL. For example, Thing is partitioned into PartiallyTangible and Intangible, therefore (complementOfIn PartiallyTangible Intangible Thing) holds. See also ComplementOfInFn.
label: Complement Of In
complementOfIn

comment:
A quintary instance of InterArgIsaPredicate (q.v.). (interArgIsa RELN INDEP-ARGNUM INDEP-COL DEP-ARGNUM DEP-COL) means that, when an instance of INDEP-COL appears as the INDEP-ARGNUMth argument to RELN, a necessary condition for semantic well-formedness is that the DEP-ARGNUMth argument must be an instance of DEP-COL. That is, if INDEP-INST is an instance of INDEP-COL, then (RELN ... INDEP-INST ...), where INDEP-INST is the INDEP-ARGNUMth (or "independent") argument to RELN, is semantically well-formed only if the DEP-ARGNUMth (or "dependent") argument (which is some item in the sequence <... INDEP-INST ...> other than the INDEP-ARGNUMth) is an instance of DEP-COL.

For example, (interArgIsa performedBy 1 PurposefulAction 2 IntelligentAgent) means that, if ACT is a PurposefulAction, then (performedBy ACT AGENT) is semantically well-formed only if AGENT is an IntelligentAgent.

For an explanation of semantic well-formedness, see CycLExpression_Assertible and its direct specializations. For a more general explanation of independent and dependent arguments in the present sense, see InterArgConstraintPredicate. For similar to but less flexible predicates than interArgIsa, which have already-fixed positions for the independent and dependent arguments, see the ternary interArgIsa1_2 et al.
label: Inter Arg Isa
interArgIsa

comment: (proximityConstraints_Type SIT-TYPE ROLE1 ROLE2 RANGE) means that RANGE is the range of distance that object OBJ can be from the location in which something plays ROLE2 in an instance SIT of Situation SIT-TYPE in order for OBJ to play the role ROLE1 in SIT. For example, (proximityConstraints_Type (KillingByMeansOfFn Hatchet) performedBy organismKilled (Meter .25 30) means that whoever kills with a hatchet must be between a quarter meter and 30 meters from the organism killed; (proximityConstraints_Type (KillingByMeansOfFn Hatchet) deviceUsed organismKilled ActuallyTouching) means that a hatchet must actually touch any organism it kills. Compare this predicate to the instance-level predicate proximityConstraints.
label: Proximity Constraints Type
proximityConstraints-Type

comment: (modifiedForPasswordlessLogin AGENT PROGRAM ACCOUNT COMPUTER) means that AGENT has modified PROGRAM on COMPUTER so that users can login to ACCOUNT via PROGRAM without being prompted for a username or password.
label: Modified For Passwordless Login
modifiedForPasswordlessLogin

Mx4rvWEKXJwpEbGdrcN5Y29ycA: Ke Relation Strengthens Via Arg Inverse
comment: If (keRelationStrengthensViaArg RELATION BINPRED ARGNUM) and (BINPRED WEAK STRONG), then (keStrengtheningSuggestion (RELATION ... WEAK ...) (RELATION ... STRONG ...)). In other words, (keRelationStrengthensViaArg RELATION BINPRED ARGNUM) means that the binary predicate BINPRED can be used to strengthen a sentence with arg0 RELATION (or used inversely to weaken it) by replacement of the ARGNUMth argument. It is not a requirement that all potential replacement sentences be well-formed.
label: Ke Relation Strengthens Via Arg
keRelationStrengthensViaArg

comment: The predicate (textOfTerminalSyntaxSymbol STRING SYMBOL SYSTEM) relates a terminal SyntaxSpecificationSymbol SYMBOL in a StringGrammar SYSTEM to the specific surface string STRING associated with it. For example, in a phrase structure grammar PSG1, DEF-DETERMINER--->''the'' would be represented as (textOfTerminalSyntaxSymbol ''the'' DefiniteDeterminer PSG1). Here DEF-DETERMINER acts as one of the terminalSyntaxSymbols for this grammar (because it stands directly for surface text).
label: Text Of Terminal Syntax Symbol
textOfTerminalSyntaxSymbol
available material
availableMaterial
comment: In Workarounds problems, (availableMaterial OBJ) means that OBJ is available for use as a resource in a solution to the problem. Generally, availableMaterial will be a PhysicalDevice, but engineering companies are also usefully treated this way.

label: Use Reformulation Rule For Cultural Analysis
useReformulationRuleForCulturalAnalysis
comment: (useReformulationRuleForGuidedKnowledgeEntry RULE) tells the GKE that it should use RULE to reformulate formulae during term replacement, so as to produce WFF results without bothering the user.

(orgAllocatesAmountForIn ORG MONEY SITTYPE DATE) means that in DATE, the Organization ORG allocates the funds MONEY for instances of SITTYPE. This is a broad predicate meant to cover a variety of organizations like the US government that sets aside money for the drug war, or the Gates Foundation that allocates money for AIDS research.
Mx4rwLSVCpwpEbGdrcN5Y29ycA: organization had allocated funds for during
organization has allocated funds for during
organization have allocated funds for during
organization will allocate funds for during
organization will have allocated funds for during
label: organization allocating funds for during
orgAllocatesAmountForIn

comment: (few_GenQuantRelnFrom RELN COL THING) is true if few of the instances INST of COL are such that (RELN THING INST) holds.
label: Few Gen Quant Reln From
few-GenQuantRelnFrom
Glf Connectors In Contact In Graph
glfConnectorsInContactInGraph

comment: A ternary instance of InterArgIsaPredicate (q.v.). (interArgIsa2_3 RELN INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL DEPENDENT-ARG-COL) means that, when an instance of INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL appears as the second argument to RELN, a necessary condition for semantic well-formedness is that the third argument must be an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. That is, if INST is an instance of INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL, then (RELN ARG1 INST ARG3 ... ARGN) is semantically well-formed only if ARG3 is an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. For an explanation of semantic well-formedness, see CycLExpression_Assertible and its direct specializations.
label: Inter Arg Isa 2 3
interArgIsa2-3

comment: An instance of InterArgFormatPredicate (q.v.). (interArgFormat3_1 PRED COL FORMAT) means that FORMAT is a Format (q.v.) requirement for the first argument-place of PRED when PRED's third argument is an instance of COL. That is, with respect to a sentence of the form (PRED ARG1 ARG2 ARG3... ARGN) in which ARG3 is an instance of COL, PRED's arg1 position (i.e. the position occupied by the metavariable `ARG1' in the preceding sentence-form) is subject to FORMAT. See Format and its instances for further explanation.
label: Inter Arg Format 3 1
interArgFormat3-1

comment: (collectionRestrictsWhen COL SPEC PRED) means that when INST is an instance of COL and bears a binary relation to some X in PRED (i.e. (PRED INST X) or (PRED X INST) holds) then INST is also an instance of SPEC. Note that SPEC is a spec of COL.
label: Collection Restricts When
collectionRestrictsWhen

comment: (incapacitates SIT AGENT ACT-TYPE) means that SIT causes AGENT to be certainly incapable of doing actions that are instances of ACT-TYPE, i.e., ACT brings it about that the derivedProbability of 'AGENT would be successful at performing an instance of ACT-TYPE if she tried' is zero. Note that incapacitating factors prevent, but preventing factors need not be incapacitating. An example: being locked in a closet incapacitates one to play tennis; being a convicted felon incapacitates one to run for elective offices in most U.S. states. Negative example: an appointment prevents, but doesn't incapacitate, me from meeting you at 3pm.
label: Incapacitates (ternary predicate)
incapacitates

comment: (percentOfWorldProductionOfProduct AGT PRODUCTTYPE REALNUM) says that the amount of PRODUCTTYPE produced by AGT is REALNUM of the total produced anywhere on earth. Assertions with this predicate as the arg0 should be used in a temporally-qualified microtheory (see mtTime) or within the scope of a holdsIn or other temporally-modal predicate. Otherwise, use percentOfWorldProductionOfProductDuring.
label: Percent Of World Production Of Product
percentOfWorldProductionOfProduct

comment: The visual image associated with the image mt ARG1 depicts the object ARG2 in lighting condition ARG3.
label: Mt Image Lighting
mtImageLighting

comment: (pageNumbersOfSubworkForStyleAndRendering WORK STYLE RENDERING STRING) means that STRING is the canonical string used to express the page numbers of WORK according to STYLE-SPECIFICATION, for rendering using MARKUP-LANGUAGE.
label: Page Numbers Of Subwork For Style And Rendering
pageNumbersOfSubworkForStyleAndRendering

comment: (doEnsureInattentivenessToObjectForBriefPeriod AGENT DISTRACTED OBJECT) means that AGENT ensures that DISTRACTED does not pay attention to OBJECT for a brief period of time.
label: Do Ensure Inattentiveness To Object For Brief Period
doEnsureInattentivenessToObjectForBriefPeriod

comment: (pointAtDistanceAndBearingFromThing THING DISTANCE AZIMUTH POINT) means that POINT is the Point which is obtained by translating from THING a fixed distance DISTANCE in the direction of AZIMUTH.
label: Point At Distance And Bearing From Thing
pointAtDistanceAndBearingFromThing

comment: (solubilityValueOfSubstanceType SOLUTE SOLVENT VALUE) means that VALUE is the solubility constant of the substance type SOLUTE in the substance type SOLVENT at 25C temperature. The solubility constant of a substance type SOLUTE is the maximum amount of an instance of SOLUTE that can be dissolved in a given quantity of the type SOLVENT. This constant can be expressed in a variety of inter-reducible ways: here we use mass fraction of solute, a percentage measure: ie., VALUE = m2 / (m1 + m2), where m1 is the mass of solvent and m2 is the mass of solute in a saturated solution. An example: (solubilityValueOfSubstanceType Salt_NaCl (LiquidFn Water) 0.265), meaning that a saturated solution of NaCl at 25C will contain 26.5 grams per 100 grams of water.
label: solubility value of substance type
solubilityValueOfSubstanceType

comment: (assertPriorToInCreationTemplate ASSERTION-1 ASSERTION-2 TEMPLATE) means that when using TEMPLATE to create a new term, the instance of CycLAssertion corresponding to ASSERTION-1 should be asserted prior to asserting the instance of CycLAssertion corresponding to ASSERTION-2.
label: Assert Prior To In Creation Template
assertPriorToInCreationTemplate

comment: An assertion of the form (literalHasNARTInArg LIT NART N) states that the CycLNonAtomicReifiedTerm NART is the value of the Nth argument in the (CycLObjectTypeFn CycLAtomicSentence) LIT.
label: Literal Has NART In Arg
literalHasNARTInArg

comment: (defaultSoftwareParameterValueInSoftwareObject PARAM VAL SOFTWARE) states that, if the value of PARAM is not otherwise specified, it will default to VAL in SOFTWARE.
label: Default Software Parameter Value In Software Object
defaultSoftwareParameterValueInSoftwareObject
Grossly Incomplete With All Args Not Fully Bound
grosslyIncompleteWithAllArgsNotFullyBound
comment:
A unary #$InferenceCompletenessPredicate that can apply to a predicate. (grosslyIncompleteWithAllArgsNotFullyBound PRED) means that the Cyc inference engine will treat as "grossly incomplete" any removal (but not transformation) tactic for a problem with PRED in the arg0 position and with all other argument positions not fully bound.

A good example of a predicate that is grosslyIncompleteWithAllArgsNotFullyBound is spatiallySubsumes_TypeType. Generally, for no two shapes will it ever be asserted that one fits in the other.

Cf. the specialization of this predicate, grosslyIncompleteWithAnyArgsNotFullyBound, as well as grosslyIncompleteWithArgNotFullyBound.

(explosivePowerEquivalent_Type DEV-TYPE1 DEV-TYPE2 NUM) means that a single instance of DEV-TYPE1 has the same explosive force as NUM amount of DEV-TYPE2. This predicate is useful for rating the explosive power of Bombs, etc., in terms of some common measure, such as pounds of TNT or numbers of Bomblet_M77s.
label: Explosive Power Equivalent Type
explosivePowerEquivalent-Type

comment: (changeTypeInProductSupplyFromTo TYPE PRODUCT Q1 Q2) identifies TYPE as the subcollection of ChangeInSupplyOfAGoodOrService such that every instance is a change in the supply in some market of PRODUCT from quantity Q1 to quantity Q2.
label: Change Type In Product Supply From To
changeTypeInProductSupplyFromTo

comment: Used to make clear inappropriate uses of a given constant and the rational for why these are inappropriate. In assertions of the form (examples_Negative CONSTANT EXAMPLE COMMENT), EXAMPLE is english text describing a single example. COMMENT is optional commentary about that example. If you choose not to include the commentary then use the null string as the value for the third argument. Of course, it would not be instructive to assert examples_Negative about patently clear non-exemplars of a constant. E.g. It would be foolish to assert that Frankfurt is an examples_Negative of Dog. Nonetheless, certain exclusion criteria may be more important or ``set in stone'' than others. For example, it may felt that the rationale for a certain exclusion criterion's existence is based on an intuitive guess and may be removed without too much trouble from other facts in kb which depend on this criterion. An assertion with the comment that the affiliated example is a boundary negative can help clue later knowledge enterers to the more negotiable aspects of a terms definition.
label: Examples-Negative
examples-Negative

comment:
A TernaryPredicate and MacroRelation that relates two quoted instances of CycLPropositionalSentence to a Real0_1. Intuitively, (conditionalProbability HYPOTHESIS EVIDENCE N) means that the probability (in the current context) that HYPOTHESIS holds given only the information that EVIDENCE holds is N. Formally, it is shorthand for: 
(equals N
  (QuotientFn
    (ProbabilityFn (and HYPOTHESIS EVIDENCE))
    (ProbabilityFn EVIDENCE)))
For example, 
(conditionalProbability
  (fanOf GeorgeWBush WillieNelson)
  (originallyFromRegion GeorgeWBush Texas_State)
  0.7215)
means that the probability that George W. Bush is a fan of Willie Nelson, given only the information that he (Bush) is originally from Texas, is 0.7215, or 72.15%. Formally, it is shorthand for: 
(equals 0.7215
  (QuotientFn
    (ProbabilityFn
      (and 
        (fanOf GeorgeWBush WillieNelson)
        (originallyFromRegion GeorgeWBush Texas_State)))
    (ProbabilityFn
      (originallyFromRegion GeorgeWBush Texas_State))))
This is the predicate corresponding to ConditionalProbabilityFn. See also conditionalLikelihood.
label: Conditional Probability
conditionalProbability

comment: This predicate relates serial character-string tokens (see CharacterStringToken_Serial) to sequences of subseries into which they can be divided. (concatenateStringTokens STRINGTOKEN SUBSERIES1 ... SUBSERIESN) means that SUBSERIES1 ... SUBSERIES are adjacent segments of STRINGTOKEN (occurring in the order indicated by their respective argument positions) which jointly constitute the whole of STRINGTOKEN. This n-member sequence might or might not exist as part of a longer series (i.e. a superseries of STRINGTOKEN that starts before SUBSERIES1 and/or ends after SUBSERIESN). See also subStringTokens.
label: Concatenate String Tokens
concatenateStringTokens

comment: (typicallyLikesRelationshipFromType AGENT_TYPE REL COLLECTION) means that a typical instance of AGENT_TYPE likes to be in the relationship REL with an instance of COLLECTION [likesRelationshipFromType]. If the relationship is a Role and the Collection is a spec of Event, then likesRoleInEventType applies among the typical instance of AGENT_TYPE, Role, and Event type.
label: Typically Likes Relationship From Type
typicallyLikesRelationshipFromType

comment: (firstRoleInEventType INDIV TYPE ACTOR-SLOT EVENT) means that EVENT is the very first instance of TYPE in which INDIV occupied ACTOR-SLOT. For instance, (firstRoleInEventType #$Foxvog (MakingFn CycLAssertion) performedBy Event001) means that Event001 was the first time that #$Foxvog ever made a Cyc assertion. See also lastRoleInEventType
label: First Role In Event Type
firstRoleInEventType

comment: A predicate relating a collection, such as a specialization of MilitaryAgent or a type of equipment, to the primary military role it is intended to play. For example, (typePrimaryFunction_Military #$PathfinderUnit-MilitarySpecialty #$Reconnaissance-MilitaryFundamental performedBy) means that Pathfinder units are primarily intended to engage in reconnaissance. While such units may have other capabilities, those asserted to be primary are those for which it is most optimized, and are the most probable uses of such units when they appear in military operations.
label: primary military function
typePrimaryFunction-Military

comment: A predicate for storing test cases for PPH-VARIABLE-ISA-CONSTRAINTS in the KB. (pphVariableIsaConstraintTestCase VARIABLE FORMULA COLLECTION) means that calling (PPH-VARIABLE-ISA-CONSTRAINTS VARIABLE FORMULA) in BaseKB should return a list starting with COLLECTION.
label: Pph Variable Isa Constraint Test Case
pphVariableIsaConstraintTestCase

comment: (tourTravelLegTransport TOUR PATH TRAVELINGTYPE) means that the leg of tour represented by PATH will involve a TransportationEventByVehicleType of type TRAVELINGTYPE.
label: Tour Travel Leg Transport
tourTravelLegTransport

comment: (argumentCountType PRED ARG-NUM TYPE) means that the type of the entities being counted in the ARG-NUM position of a CycL sentence headed by PRED is TYPE. For example, (argumentCountType numberOfInhabitants 2 Person) means that the number 2800000 in (numberOfInhabitants CityOfRomeItaly 2800000) is used as a count of 2800000 instances of Person and not, say, of 2800000 instances of Dog. This intention that could not be directly expressed as an argument constraint on the second argument of numberOfInhabitants, which is bound to be a NonNegativeInteger, i.e disjointWith Person.
label: Argument Count Type
argumentCountType
Rdfs: Property
rdfs:Property
comment: rdfs_Property is an imported DAML/XML term equivalent to the Cyc term BinaryPredicate

(interArgIsaGenl RELN INDEPENDENT-ARGNUM INDEPENDENT-COL DEPENDENT-ARGNUM DEPENDENT-COL) means that, when an instance of INDEPENDENT-COL appears as the INDEPENDENT-ARGNUMth argument to RELN, the corresponding DEPENDENT-ARGNUMth argument must be a subcollection of DEPENDENT-COL, or the result is not semantically well-formed.
label: Inter Arg Isa Genl
interArgIsaGenl

comment: This is sort of a specialization of positiveVestedInterest. The agent ARG1 has a positive vested interest in the value of the slot ARG3 on the thing ARG2. For example, hasPositiveInterestIn(#$Guha GuhasBank financialState) means that #$Guha cares about (has a positive vested interest in) the financial health of his bank. He probably doesn't care how old it is or what its name is.
label: Has Positive Interest In
hasPositiveInterestIn

comment: When ACID-OR-BASE is a substance that ionizes in water -- either an acid or a base, (percentOfIonization SAMPLE ACID-OR-BASE PERCENT) holds just in case PERCENT is the percentage of ACID-OR-BASE that is ionized in SAMPLE.
label: percentage of ionization
percentOfIonization

comment:
A TernaryPredicate. Where ACCUSING is an Accusing, ROLE is a BinaryRolePredicate, and EVENT-TYPE is a specialization of Event, (accusedOfRoleInType ACCUSING ROLE EVENT-TYPE) means that the agent playing the role of accused in ACCUSING is accused of playing the role of ROLE in an instance of EVENT-TYPE.

See also the instance-level version of this predicate, accusedOfRoleInEvent.
label: Accused Of Role In Type
accusedOfRoleInType

comment: (predicatesPropertyTypeOfArg PREDICATE ARGNUM TYPE) means that any assertion where PREDICATE is the predicate predicates a TYPE type of property of its ARGNUMth argument.
label: Predicates Property Type Of Arg
predicatesPropertyTypeOfArg

comment: (assertedArg1BinaryPreds_CountMin COL BIN-PRED N) means that there are at least N instances INS of COL for which it has been asserted for some VALUE (not necessarily the same for each) that (BIN-PRED INS VALUE). Note that this predicate is itself notAssertible (q.v.), since it must be computed from the state of the knowledge base.
label: minimum assertion arg1 binary predicate
assertedArg1BinaryPreds-CountMin

comment: `(qualifyingResidenceForTaxDeduction OWNER HOME YEAR)' means that OWNER owns HOME and that HOME passes IRS criteria for OWNER to be able to claim its mortgage interest as a deduction as long as OWNER does not claim this deduction on two other homes. A taxpayer might have more than one secondaryResidence that is a $qualifyingResidenceForTaxDeduction. In such a case, OWNER can designate any of these to be OWNER's designatedSecondaryResidence. Don't confuse this predicate with the similarly named qualifiedResidenceForTaxDeduction. The latter means that HOME is either OWNER's primaryResidence or OWNER's designatedSecondaryResidence for YEAR.
label: Qualifying Residence For Tax Deduction
qualifyingResidenceForTaxDeduction

comment: An assertion of the form (genlSituationTypesWRTRolePlayersOfType_SubSitTypes SITTYPE1 TYPE1 SITTYPE2 TYPE2 SUBSITTYPE ROLE) means that SITTYPE1 is a more specific version of SITTYPE2 in terms of the type of actors which play ROLE in instances of SUBSITTYPE that are subSituations of instances of SITTYPE1. Specifically, it means that in instances of SITTYPE1, the actors of TYPE2 which play ROLE in the subSituations which are instances of SUBSITTYPE will be instances of the more specific type TYPE1.
label: Genl Situation Types WRT Role Players Of Type Sub Sit Types
genlSituationTypesWRTRolePlayersOfType-SubSitTypes

comment: (denotationPlaceholder WORD POS SENSE CONCEPT) indicates that a suitable denotation or denotationRelatedTo for WORD in part-of-speech POS and SENSE would be CONCEPT.
label: Denotation Placeholder
denotationPlaceholder

comment: (dependentMeaning DEP-NODE DEP-MEANING INDEP-NODE INDEP-MEANING) means that the CycL expression DEP-MEANING is a proposed meaning for DEP-NODE that depends on INDEP-MEANING being the meaning for INDEP-NODE. If INDEP-MEANING is excluded as the meaning of INDEP-NODE (cf excludedMeaning), then so is DEP-MEANING as the meaning of DEP-NODE, and conversely if DEP-MEANING is chosen (cf chosenMeaning), then so is INDEP-MEANING. In typical cases INDEP-NODE is a daughter node (cf syntacticDaughters) of DEP-NODE, but this is not assumed definitionally. For instance, the #$CycPhraseStructureParser uses this relation to derive the "denotational" semantics for certain phrases from the lexicon, and in these cases DEP-NODE and INDEP-NODE can be the same node.
label: Dependent Meaning
dependentMeaning

comment: (underspecifiedExpressionOf EXP THING FEATURE) says that EXP, in some abstract or perhaps metaphorical way, is an "expression" by THING of some underspecified "feature" FEATURE of THING. So for example, one might assert (underspecifiedExpressionOf BobSpraypaintingLousCar001 Bob Anger) to mean that Bob's spraypainting Lou's car is an expression of Bob's anger.
label: Underspecified Expression Of
underspecifiedExpressionOf

comment: ARG3 is a non-negative integer indicating the catalogue number of the image ARG1.  ARG2 denotes the catalogue in which the visual image is grouped.
label: Mt Image ID
mtImageID

comment: (obscuresFrom OBJ1 OBJ2 AGENT) means that the PartiallyTangible OBJ1 visually blocks the PerceptualAgent AGENT's view of the PartiallyTangible OBJ2.
label: Obscures From
obscuresFrom

comment: An assertion of the from (hasProjectForGoal AGENT PROJECT GOAL) is used to assert that AGENT, an instance of IntelligentAgent plans PROJECT as the overall task for achieving GOAL. This predicate assumes (hasGoals AGENT GOAL) such that GOAL has independent motivation and is not wholly motivated by a desire to perform some further (although GOAL may be in line with or somehow help achieve other goals).
label: Has Project For Goal
hasProjectForGoal

comment: (ebmtlMeaningOfStringFragment STRING SUBSTRING-SET ASSERTION) means that in the context of example-based machine translation to logic, the combination of strings in SUBSTRING-SET means ASSERTION or expresses the proposition given by ASSERTION, when this combination occurs in STRING.
label: Ebmtl Meaning Of String Fragment
ebmtlMeaningOfStringFragment

comment:
A TernaryPredicate that relates a specialization of Agent_PartiallyTangible to a BinaryRolePredicate to a specialization of Event. (agentTypeTypicallyDislikesRoleInEventType A-TYPE ROLE E-TYPE) means that instances of A-TYPE typically dislike playing ROLE in instances of E-TYPE.

For example, (agentTypeTypicallyDislikesRoleInEventType DomesticCat objectTakenCareOf WalkingAPet) means that instances of DomesticCat typically dislike playing the role of objectTakenCareOf in instances of WalkingAPet -- that is, cats don't like to be taken for walks.
label: Agent Type Typically Dislikes Role In Event Type
agentTypeTypicallyDislikesRoleInEventType

comment: An instance of InterArgFormatPredicate (q.v.). (interArgFormat3_4 PRED COL FORMAT) means that FORMAT is a Format (q.v.) requirement for the fourth argument-place of PRED when PRED's third argument is an instance of COL. That is, with respect to a sentence of the form (PRED ARG1 ARG2 ARG3 ARG4 ... ARGN) in which ARG3 is an instance of COL, PRED's arg4 position (i.e. the position occupied by the metavariable `ARG4' in the preceding sentence-form) is subject to FORMAT. See Format and its instances for further explanation.
label: Inter Arg Format 3 4
interArgFormat3-4

comment: (many_GenQuantRelnFromType RELN COL2 COL1) means that for many instances X of COL1 there is an instance INST of COL2 such that (RELN INST X) holds. "Many" in this sense need not mean "many relative to the total number of instances of COL1 that exist".
label: Many Gen Quant Reln From Type
many-GenQuantRelnFromType

comment: This relation is the 'query' analog of examplePredSentences. It is used to specify, for a given knowledge domain, examples that typify frequently asked questions (FAQs) that users may reasonably be expected to have with regard to that domain.
label: Ke Common Query Example
keCommonQueryExample

comment: An instance of TernaryPredicate. (orthogonalInMt MT COL1 COL2) means that it is true in the Microtheory MT that the Collection COL1 is orthogonal with (i.e. logically independent of) the Collection COL2. More precisely, (orthogonalInMt MT COL1 COL2) means that (1) (orthogonalityCandidates COL1 COL2) is true in MT; and (2) each of the following sentences is such that it is true in some (not necessarily reified) specMt of MT: (a) (thereExists ?THING (isa ?THING (CollectionIntersection2Fn COL1 COL2))); (b) (thereExists ?THING (isa ?THING (CollectionDifferenceFn COL1 COL2))); (c) (thereExists ?THING (isa ?THING (CollectionDifferenceFn COL2 COL1))).
label: Orthogonal In Mt
orthogonalInMt

comment: (subExpressionWithStringAtOffset SUB SUPER STRING INTEGER) means that the instance SUB of LinguisticExpressionPeg is the subexpression of SUPER whose string is STRING and which starts OFFSET characters into the string of SUPER.
label: Sub Expression With String At Offset
subExpressionWithStringAtOffset

comment: (distributionCapacity PT PRODUCT-TYPE RATE) means that the Rate RATE is the greatest possible rate at which instances of the ProductType PRODUCT-TYPE could be distributed to the instance of PartiallyTangible PT. In a general economic context, PT will often be an instance of (GroupFn IntelligentAgent).
label: Distribution Capacity
distributionCapacity

comment: A ternary predicate intended to express the quantity of a ChemicalSubstanceType in a sample of something, (possibly a sample of the same substance) when the quantity is measured in terms of number of basic parts or units. A standard unit used in chemistry is Mole_ChemicalCountUnit. Thus, for instance, (quantityOfSubstanceInSample SAMPLE Salt_NaCl (Mole_ChemicalCountUnit 0.5)) says that SAMPLE is a partially tangible thing containing 0.5 moles of sodium chloride. Cf. quantityOfChemicalObjectInSample.
Mx4rwLSVCpwpEbGdrcN5Y29ycA: quantities of moles of chemical substance in a sample
label: quantity of moles of chemical substance in a sample
quantityOfSubstanceInSample

comment:
A quaternary instance of MetaRelation (q.v.) that is used to state that a relation that is an argument to another relation imposes its own argument constraints on some argument positions of the latter relation. The latter relation "inherits" argument constraints from the relation that is an argument to it.

(inheritsConstraintsViaArg RELN INT-J INT-K INT-L) means that when a Relation SUB-RELN occurs as the INT-Jth argument position of Relation RELN, the argument constraints of the INT-Kth argument position of SUB-RELN apply to the INT-Lth argument position of RELN. The inherited constraints are semantic well-formedness constraints on all expressions in which both RELN occurs as the arg0 term and SUB-RELN occurs as the INT-Jth term.

For example, (inheritsConstraintsViaArg decreasesCausally 3 1 2) means that (decreasesCausally ARG1 ARG2 ARG3) is semantically well-formed only if ARG2 satisfies the semantic well-formedness constraints on the arg1 position of ARG3. So (inheritsConstraintsViaArg decreasesCausally 3 1 2) means that (decreasesCausally ARG1 ARG2 agentPopularity) (for instance) is semantically well-formed only if ARG2 is an instance of IntelligentAgent (since (arg1Isa agentPopularity IntelligentAgent) is true). For an explanation of semantic well-formedness, see CycLExpression_Assertible and its specializations.
label: Inherits Constraints Via Arg
inheritsConstraintsViaArg

comment: (contributesToSpeciesInSample SAMPLE SUBSTANCE ION-TYPE INTERVAL) means that a certain (unspecified) amount of ChemicalSpeciesType SUBSTANCE contributes ScalarInterval INTERVAL amount of IonTypeByChemicalSpecies ION-TYPE to the PartiallyTangible SAMPLE. (contributesToSpeciesInSample SAMPLE SUBSTANCE ION-TYPE INTERVAL) implies that SUBSTANCE is "in" SAMPLE (for the relevant sense of "in", see molarityOfSubstanceInSample). Also, if it is true that (contributesToSpeciesInSample SAMPLE SUBSTANCE ION-TYPE INTERVAL), it is possible for INTERVAL to be "zero" -- i.e, it is possible that SUBSTANCE contributes no amount of ION-TYPE to SAMPLE. However, it is not possible for SUBSTANCE to contribute a "negative amount" of ION-TYPE to SAMPLE.
label: contributing an amount of ions
contributesToSpeciesInSample

comment: (modalFeatureTransfers_Inverse PRED-1 PRED-2 OPERATOR) means that when (PRED-1 ARG1 ARG2) holds, (OPERATOR (PRED-2 ARG2 ARG1)) also holds, where OPERATOR is a modal operator. For example, (modalFeatureTransfers foundingAgent foundsOrganization willAlwaysBe) means that when (foundingAgent ORGANIZATION AGENT) holds, (willAlwaysBe (foundsOrganization AGENT ORGANIZATION)) holds.
label: Modal Feature Transfers Inverse
modalFeatureTransfers-Inverse

comment:
A ternary RuleMacroPredicate (q.v.) that can be used to state that a given binary predicate holds between a specified thing and some instance of a given collection. (relationInstanceOnly PRED THING COL) means that only instances of COL, say INST, are such that (PRED THING INST) holds. It is equivalent to (and can thus be used in effect as shorthand for) the more complex form:

(implies (PRED THING ?INST) (isa ?INST COL)).

For example, `(relationInstanceOnly presidentOfCountry UnitedStatesOfAmerica UnitedStatesPresident)' means that only U.S. presidents are president of the U.S.A.. Cf. relationOnlyInstance, and see the shared #$NoteAboutUseOfRuleMacroPredicates.
label: Relation Instance Only
relationInstanceOnly

comment: This predicate serves to exempt individual assertions or FORT's from inclusion in <font color="#ff0000">#$ProjectBroadsword</font> releases.  One should only use this predicate in cases where the assertion in question would have been included by default.
label: Omit From Project Broadsword
omitFromProjectBroadsword

comment:
A ternary RuleMacroPredicate (q.v.) that can be used to state that a given binary predicate stands in a certain relation to two collections. (relationAllExists BINPRED COL1 COL2) means that for any instance INST1 of COL1, there exists some instance INST2 of COL2 such that (BINPRED INST1 INST2) holds. It is equivalent to (and can thus be used in effect as shorthand for) the more complex form: 

  (implies
    (isa ?INST1 COL1)
    (thereExists ?INST2
      (and
        (isa ?INST2 COL2)
        (BINPRED ?INST1 ?INST2)))).

For example, (relationAllExists temporalBoundsContain CalendarWeek Wednesday) means that every calendar week contains a Wednesday. See also relationExistsAll and #$NoteAboutUseOfRuleMacroPredicates.
label: Relation All Exists
relationAllExists

comment: (programFunctionResult FUNCTION VAR) means that FUNCTION has a variable VAR in its local scope.
label: Program Function Local Variable
programFunctionLocalVariable

comment: An assertion of the form (folderOfResultsFromQuerySearchByAgentWithString FOLDER AGENT STRING) states that the KEInteractionFolder FOLDER stores a set of CycLQuerySpecifications that the system found or generated in response to the IntelligentAgent AGENT's searches (see SearchingForACycLQuery) using the CharacterString STRING. This is the corresponding predicate of the function FolderOfResultsFromQuerySearchByAgentWithStringFn.
label: Folder Of Results From Query Search By Agent With String
folderOfResultsFromQuerySearchByAgentWithString

comment: (salientDifferenceBetween_Inverse COL1 COL2 COL3 BINPRED) means that while COL1 and COL2 contain instances that are similar in many salient respects, they differ in the fact that for every instance, INS1, of COL1 there is an instance of COL3, INS3 such that (BINPRED INS3 INS1). On the other hand, instances of COL2 do not bear the relation BINPRED to any instance of COL3. The differences noted with this predicate should be salient ones, e.g., differences that one familiar with COL1 and COL2 might note if asked to compare and contrast COL1 and COL2. See also the closely related predicates, salientDifferenceBetweenSiblings_Inverse and salientDifferenceBetween.
label: Salient Difference Between Inverse
salientDifferenceBetween-Inverse

comment:
The expression `(transitiveInArgs PRED N M)' means that the Predicate PRED is transitive in its Nth and Mth arguments, if its other arguments are held fixed. Specifically, if the Mth argument in one assertion using PRED is the same as the Nth argument in another assertion using PRED, and all arguments other than the Nth and Mth are the same in the two assertions, then the sentence obtained by replacing the Mth argument in the first assertion with the Mth argument in the second sentence holds.

Thus, for example, if greaterThanOrEqualWRTScalar is ternary and (transitiveInArgs greaterThanOrEqualWRTScalar 1 2), (greaterThanOrEqualWRTScalar VAL1 VAL2 PRED), and (greaterThanOrEqualWRTScalar VAL2 VAL3 PRED) all hold, then (greaterThanOrEqualWRTScalar VAL1 VAL3 PRED) also holds.
label: Transitive In Args
transitiveInArgs
Vulnerability Tech Advisory DOD
vulnerabilityTechAdvisory-DOD
comment: vulnerabilityTechAdvisory_DOD is a unary predicate used to assert that a CycLAssertion expressies information contained in a vulnerability technical advisory on the DOD CERT webpage http://www.cert.mil/iava/index.htm.

The LogicalConnective that represents exclusive-or in CycL. Unlike or, which is a VariableArityRelation, xor takes two arguments, which must be instances of #$ELSentence-Assertible. (xor P Q) means one but not both of P and Q is true. (An EL formula that mentions xor is translated during canonicalization into an equivalent, less compact, formula that mentions or, and, and not).
label: Xor
xor

comment: (assertionDerivedViaReformulation ASST SENT SPEC) means that the CycLAssertion ASST was created by the CycLReformulator, using #$ELSentence-Assertible SENT as the input sentence and SPEC as the reformulation specification. Assertions on assertionDerivedViaReformulation will keep a record of the origins of reformulated assertions.
label: Assertion Derived Via Reformulation
assertionDerivedViaReformulation

comment: (numInstancesOfCollStandInPredToValue_Inverse BIN-PRED COLL THING NUM) holds just in case the number of instances, INS, of COLL such that (BIN-PRED THING INS) is NUM.
label: Num Instances Of Coll Stand In Pred To Value Inverse
numInstancesOfCollStandInPredToValue-Inverse

comment:
A ternary RuleMacroPredicate (q.v.) that can be used to state that a given binary predicate holds between some instance of a given collection and a given thing. (relationExistsInstance BINPRED COL THING) means that there exists an instance INST of COL such that (BINPRED INST THING) holds. This is equivalent to (and can thus be used in effect as shorthand for) the more complex form: 

(thereExists ?INST
  (and
     (isa ?INST COL)
     (PRED ?INST THING))) .

For example, (relationExistsInstance eventOccursAt IllegalDrugActivity Sweden) means that there exists illegal drug activity in Sweden. See also the shared #$NoteAboutUseOfRuleMacroPredicates.
label: Relation Exists Instance
relationExistsInstance

comment: (typeBehaviorCapability COL SIT-TYPE ROLE SCALAR) means that instances of COL are typically capable of playing the role ROLE in situations of type, SITTYPE, at a level of aptitude LEVEL or higher. Note that this does not refer to the average "aptitude" level but the level of aptitude above which nearly all instances (i.e., the default assumption) of the collection will play the role. This is a version of #$typeBehaviorCapable that admits of gradations. Also compare with behaviorCapable and behaviorCapability.
label: Type Behavior Capability
typeBehaviorCapability

comment: (specPredsRelevantToTermSummaryPredWRTInstancesInArg PRED TERM-SUMMARY-PRED TYPE N) means that if a thing THING is an instance of TYPE, then any assertions in which a specialization of PRED occurs in arg 0 and THING occurs as arg N should appear in the fact sheet for THING under the category associated with TERM-SUMMARY-PRED.
label: Spec Preds Relevant To Term Summary Pred WRT Instances In Arg
specPredsRelevantToTermSummaryPredWRTInstancesInArg

comment: (pathBetween PATH X Y) means that the Path_Simple PATH goes between points (or places) X and Y, where X and Y do not 'overlap', and no further. Both X and Y have to be on PATH (see pointOnPath). Note that (pathBetween PATH X Y) is more specific than (pathConnects PATH X Y) because here the PATH cannot extend beyond X and Y. Within a particular PathSystem, a path's end points in the system are unique, and pathBetweenInSystem (q.v.) is restricted to paths and points in the system. When considered without a context of a path system, a path may have several different places at one end, such as Austin and Texas both being at the same end of some path along Highway I-35.
label: path between the specified paths
pathBetween

comment: The predicate productionCapacity states a producer's greatest possible rate of production for a given product. The second argument to productionCapacity must be a ProductType that is a specialization of PartiallyTangibleProduct. The third argument must be a Rate. The producer, the first argument, may be an industry (as in 'The production capacity of the Algerian oil industry is 529 million barrels of petroleum per year'), a given factory (as in 'This plant can produce up to 12,000 tires per day'), or a region ('The maple-syrup production capacity for the state of Maine is 1,000 gallons per month').
label: production capacity
productionCapacity

comment: A TernaryPredicate and specialization of agentMakesProfitInTimeInterval that relates an Agent_Generic to a MonetaryValue to a TimeInterval. (agentMakesProfitInTimeInterval_BeforeInterestAndTax AGENT VALUE INTERVAL) means that AGENT makes VALUE in profits, before interest and taxes, during INTERVAL. For example, (agentMakesProfitInTimeInterval_BeforeInterestAndTax XYZCorp (MillionDollars 10) (YearFn 2000)) means that XYZ Corp. made ten million dollars in profits, before interest and taxes, in 2000.
label: profit before interest and tax
agentMakesProfitInTimeInterval-BeforeInterestAndTax
subPropertyOf: Agent Makes Profit In Time Interval

comment: (revenueForPeriod ORG MONEY TIME) relates the amount of MONEY booked as revenue by ORG during the time period DATE. DATE will typically be a fiscal quarter or year, but could be some other sort of conventionally defined Date.
label: Revenue For Period
revenueForPeriod

comment: (scheduledPaymentFor AMOUNT LOAN FREQUNCY) means that AMOUNT, an instance of MonetaryValue, is the amount due toward the instance of LoanAgreement LOAN at the instance of Frequency. Thus, (scheduledPaymentFor (Dollar-UnitedStates 100) StudentLoan001 Monthly) means that $100 is due every month to pay toward the loan StudentLoan001 until it is PaidInFull.
label: scheduled payment for a loan
scheduledPaymentFor

comment: (decreasesImmediatelyCausally EVENT THING SLOT) means that the value for the predicate SLOT applied to THING (in the first argument position) is lower immediately after (STIF q.v.) EVENT than it was immediately before (STIB q.v.) EVENT. In addition, it means EVENT is the cause of that decrease. See #$NoteAboutQuantityChangePredicates for a map of related predicates.
label: Decreases Immediately Causally
decreasesImmediatelyCausally

comment: A sentence of the form (numberOfCNCTestsMeetingComponentPhraseThreshold RULE RESULTS COUNT THRESHOLD) means that for an implicit #$CandidateNounCompondSearh for RULE with RESULTS, there were COUNT cases tested for which the modifier and head trings met the minimum hit count of THRESHOLD.
label: Number Of CNC Tests Meeting Component Phrase Threshold
numberOfCNCTestsMeetingComponentPhraseThreshold

comment: (supplyCapacityFrom PT1 COL PT2 RATE) means that the Rate RATE is the greatest possible rate at which the instance of PartiallyTangible PT2 could supply instances of the collection COL to the instance of PartiallyTangible PT1. Like the predicate suppliedWith (q.v.), supplyCapacityFrom is very general. In various assertions PT1 might, for instance, be a Cell, a Person, a Business, or a GeographicalRegion; and likewise for PT2. The range of possible supplies is similarly broad.
label: Supply Capacity From
supplyCapacityFrom

comment: (firstPublicationDateForStyleAndRendering WORK STYLE RENDERING STRING) means that STRING is the canonical string used to express of the first publication date for WORK according to STYLE-SPECIFICATION, for rendering using MARKUP-LANGUAGE.
label: First Publication Date For Style And Rendering
firstPublicationDateForStyleAndRendering

comment: This predicate is used by the SKSI code to estimate the cost of querying the fields of a logical schema. More precisely, let SCHEMA denote a logical schema, let LF-1, LF-2, ..., LF-N, denote the logical fields of SCHEMA, and let SELECT_SET and WHERE_SET denote two disjoint subsets of (TheSet LF-1 LF-2 ... LF-N). Then (logicalResultSetCardinality SCHEMA SELECT_SET WHERE_SET NUM) means that NUM is the average cardinality of the result set returned from a query in which the fields in SELECT_SET left unbound and the fields of WHERE_SET are bound.
label: Logical Result Set Cardinality
logicalResultSetCardinality
Has Family Name First
hasFamilyNameFirst
comment: (hasFamilyNameFirst GROUP) indicates that members of the PersonTypeByCulture GROUP generally write their family names first. For example, (hasFamilyNameFirst ChinesePerson) states that Chinese people write their family name first.

label: Needs To Be As Value As
needsToBeAsValueAs

comment: (perCapita PRED GEO_THING MEAN) means that for every resident of (the territory of) GEO_THING, the mean val ue of (PRED RESIDENT VALUE) is MEAN).
label: Per Capita
perCapita

comment: (pcwIdentifiesRolePlayer PCW SIT ROLE) means that PCW identifies some item as playing ROLE in SIT. That is, PCW contains an identifying reference to ITEM (in the sense of the predicate pcwIdentifies, qv.), and also asserts the Proposition that (ROLE SIT ITEM). Note that (pcwIdentifiesRolePlayer PCW SIT ROLE) does not entail (ROLE SIT ITEM), i.e., the identification could be mistaken.
label: Pcw Identifies Role Player
pcwIdentifiesRolePlayer

comment: (resultArgIsaArg FUNCTION N M) means that the result of applying the instance of PredicateDenotingFunction FUNCTION to a series of arguments for which FUNCTION is defined, including COLLECTION in the Mth argument position, will result in an instance PRED of Predicate such that (argIsa PRED N COLLECTION).
label: Result Arg Isa Arg
resultArgIsaArg

comment: (increasesVulnerabilityTo THREAT-OBJ OBJECT HARM-TYPE) means that THREAT-OBJ increases OBJECT's vulnerability to HARM-TYPE. This predicate resembles vulnerableTo, but there is an important difference that must be observed, namely that when using increasesVulnerabilityTo one assumes that certain conditions coming into effect increase vulnerability. Therefore, it should not be used to declare vulnerabilities outright; Cyc should have to conclude that a situation increases an object's vulnerability to some result.
label: Increases Vulnerability To
increasesVulnerabilityTo

comment: (storageLifeInContainerType TYPE DURATION CONTAINER-TYPE) means that, other things being equal, instances of TYPE can be expected to retain their 'intended' capabilities for a period of DURATION when stored in instances of CONTAINER-TYPE.
label: Storage Life In Container Type
storageLifeInContainerType
FAC Tory Pred Topic For Instance In Arg
fACToryPredTopicForInstanceInArg

comment: This SituationTypeRelation expresses a relation that holds between the prescribed substructures of two situations, conditional on one situation being a properSubSituations of the other. (defaultEquivSubSitTypes SIT-TYPE1 SIT-TYPE2 SUBSIT-TYPE1 SUBSIT-TYPE2) means that where SIT1 is an instance of SIT-TYPE1 and SIT2 is an instance of SIT-TYPE2 such that (properSubSituations SIT1 SIT2), any instance of SUBSIT-TYPE2 that is a properSubSituations of SIT2 will be identical with any instance of SUBSIT-TYPE1 that is an properSubSituations of SIT1, barring evidence to the contrary. This is a very strong condition, even for a default, but there are cases for which it is warranted. For example, consider MurderForHire and Murder. It is true that every MurderForHire subsumes a Murder as a properSubSituations. It is also reasonable to assume that any Murder includes a Dying as a #$subEvent. Other things being equal, the default assumption should be that any Dying which is known to occur as a proper subsituation of a Murder is identical with any Dying that is known to occur as a proper subsituation of a MurderForHire of which the Murder is a part: thus, (defaultEquivSubSitTypes MurderForHire Murder Dying Dying).
label: Default Equiv Sub Sit Types
defaultEquivSubSitTypes

comment: If SPACE is a TopologicalSpace with base set BASE and SET is a subset of BASE, then the interior of SET is the set of elements of SET for which SET is a neighborhood. (See neighborhoodOfThingInTopologicalSpace) In CycL, this relation is expressed as (interiorOfSetInTopologicalSpace INTERIOR SET SPACE).
label: Interior Of Set In Topological Space
interiorOfSetInTopologicalSpace

comment: (deciles BINARYPREDICATE TYPE DECILE_STRUCTURE) means that the set of instances of TYPE for which BINARYPREDICATE applies can be broken down into the #$NTupleInterval DECILE_STRUCTURE.
label: Deciles
deciles

comment: hourOfTimeOfDay is the corresponding predicate to the function TimeOfDayFn. An assertion of the form (hourOfTimeOfDay TIMEOFDAY HOUR MINUTE) asserts that the type TIMEOFDAY is composed out of the HourOfDayType HOUR and the MinuteOfHourType MINUTE. So, (hourOfTimeOfDay (TimeOfDayFn TimeOfDay_11PM (MinuteOfHourFn 12)) TimeOfDay_11PM (MinuteOfHourFn 12)) states that (TimeOfDayFn TimeOfDay_11PM (MinuteOfHourFn 12)) is functionally composed out of the HourOfDayType TimeOfDay_11PM and the MinuteOfHourType (MinuteOfHourFn 12). So, it represents the collection of all the CalendarMinutes that are the twelfth minute of the 11th hour of some instance of TimeOfDay_PM.
label: Hour Of Time Of Day
hourOfTimeOfDay

comment: This predicate relates an agent, a goal the agent has, and something the agent needs (in a very broad sense of `needs') in order to achieve or further that goal. The goal is represented by a sentence (i.e. an #$ELSentence-Assertible; see goals). The "something" needed might be either a thing the agent needs directly (such as a physical object or person) or a thing the agent has a need in (close) connection with (such as an object-type or a proposition); see the specializations of needs_Generic for a fuller account. (needsFor AGENT THING GOAL) means that AGENT needs THING (or has a need in connection with THING that s/he must fulfill) in order to achieve her/his GOAL. The sense of `need' relevant here ranges from matters of practical convenience to matters of life and death; see the comment on needs_Generic. See also satisfiesNeed.
label: Needs For
needsFor

comment: (lastSitOfTypeWithRolePlayerBefore SIT SIT-TYPE ROLE PLAYER TEMP-THING) means that (i) SIT is an instance of SIT-TYPE in which PLAYER plays ROLE, and (ii) of all such items, SIT is the last to occur prior to TEMP-THING. We can express that SIT is the most recent situation of the relevant type -- the last to occur prior to the present moment -- by substituting Now for TEMP-THING. For example, we can express that SPEECH is the most recent public speech by GeorgeWBush by writing (lastSitOfTypeWithRolePlayerBefore SPEECH PublicSpeaking senderOfInfo GeorgeWBush Now).
label: Last Sit Of Type With Role Player Before
lastSitOfTypeWithRolePlayerBefore

comment: This is a type level version of the predicate resemblesInQuantity. (typesResembleInQuantity TYPE1 TYPE2 QUANT-TYPE) means that where INST1 and INST2 are any instances drawn, respectively, from TYPE1 and TYPE2, it will be the case that (resemblesInQuantity INST1 INST2 QUANT-TYPE).
label: Types Resemble In Quantity
typesResembleInQuantity

comment: A KBDependentRelation (q.v.) and specialization of trueSentence (q.v.) that is used to state that a given sentence is "known" to be true to the Cyc system. More precisely, (knownSentence SENT) means that SENT is provable by the Cyc inference engine from sentences currently in the Knowledge Base. knownSentence is a non-assertible predicate (see notAssertible). Note that this predicate is not to be confused with assertedSentence, which is used to state that a given sentence is explicitly asserted in the KB.
label: Known Sentence
knownSentence
Completed Sub Situation Type In Situation
completedSubSituationTypeInSituation

comment: A MetaKnowledgePredicate that is used to state a strong pragmatic directive to the CycInferenceEngine. Asserting (knownAntecedentRule RULE) tells the inference engine to automatically generate a removal module to implement RULE; i.e. to solve queries unifying with the consequent of RULE by attempting to prove the substituted antecedent of RULE. When this removal module is used during inference, it attempts to prove the substituted antecedent via removal only (see knownSentence). It does not preclude other uses of RULE in inference.
label: Known Antecedent Rule
knownAntecedentRule

comment: (increasesImmediatelyCausally EVENT THING SLOT) means that the value for the predicate SLOT applied to THING (in the first argument position) is greater immediately after (STIF q.v.) EVENT than it was immediately before (STIB q.v.) EVENT. In addition, it means EVENT is the cause of that increase. For example, (increasesImmediatelyCausally HeatingEvent01 AirMass001 ambientTemperature) means that HeatingEvent01 immediately caused an increase in the ambient temprature of AirMass001.
label: Increases Immediately Causally
increasesImmediatelyCausally

comment: termTemplate_Test relates a class of natural language phrases (e.g. noun phrases) to CycL. In addition to the slot for the Relation (function or pred) that is the focus of the CycL translation, termTemplate-Test also has a test that must succeed for the template to match.
label: Term Template Test
termTemplate-Test

comment:
(notBeforeInSituationType SIT-TYPE SUBSIT-TYPE1 SUBSIT-TYPE2) means that in any instance SIT of SIT-TYPE (a specialization of Situation), if instances SIT1 and SIT2 of SUBSIT-TYPE1 and SUBSIT-TYPE2 occur as subsituations, then SIT1 does not occur before SIT2.

Note that (notBeforeInSituationType SIT-TYPE SUBSIT-TYPE1 SUBSIT-TYPE2) does not imply that instances of SUBSIT-TYPE1 or SUBSIT-TYPE2 occur as subsituations of every instance of SIT-TYPE, since SUBSIT-TYPE1 and SUBSIT-TYPE2 may be merely candidate subsituation types of SIT-TYPE (see candidateProperSubSituationTypes).
label: Not Before In Situation Type
notBeforeInSituationType

comment: (noIDAvailable LF KEYOBJ LTS) means that for the implicit field LF of the schema LTS, on the row identified by the DBKeyObj KEYOBJ, there is no unique ID which can identify the entity binding to the implicit field LF.
label: No ID For Field
noIDForField

comment: This predicate is analogous to schemaIntegrationPredicateForInputExplicitRDSSet, however it relates an instance of IntegratingASetOfKnowledgeSources with a Predicate and the set of implicitly defined RelationshipDefiningSchemas for which the predicate expresses the meaning of the relationship in CycL.
label: Schema Integration Predicate For Input Implicit RDS Set
schemaIntegrationPredicateForInputImplicitRDSSet
subPropertyOf: Schema Integration Predicate For Input RDS Set

comment: (oughtToBe_SubSitTypeRelationToSubSitType SIT SUB-TYPE1 PRED SUB-TYPE2) means that, for any instance SUB-INS1 of SUB-TYPE1 that occurs as a subSituations of SIT, there should be an instance SUB-INS2 of SUB-TYPE2 such that (PRED SUB-INS1 SUB-INS2). Assertions involving this predicate -- which specify what should be the case -- should be made in a normative context, e.g., one that reflects the contents of a particular CodeOfConduct.
label: Ought To Be Sub Sit Type Relation To Sub Sit Type
oughtToBe-SubSitTypeRelationToSubSitType

comment:
A ternary instance of InterArgIsaPredicate (q.v.). (interArgEqualsIsa2_3 RELN INDEPENDENT-ARG DEPENDENT-ARG-COL) means that, when INDEPENDENT-ARG appears as the second argument to RELN, a necessary condition for semantic well-formedness is that the third argument must be an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. That is, (RELN ARG1 INDEPENDENT-ARG ARG3 ...) is semantically well-formed only if ARG3 is an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL.

For an explanation of semantic well-formedness, see CycLExpression_Assertible and its direct specializations. See interArgEqualsIsa for a similar but more general predicate that is quintary, allowing the user to specify the positions of the independent and dependent arguments.
label: Inter Arg Equals Isa 2 3
interArgEqualsIsa2-3

comment: (doEnsureAbsenceFromPlaceOfWork AGENT ABSENTEE PLACE) means that AGENT ensures ABSENTEE is absent from PLACE.
label: Do Ensure Absence From Place Of Work
doEnsureAbsenceFromPlaceOfWork

comment:
A quaternary RuleMacroPredicate (q.v.) that can be used to state that a given binary predicate stands in a certain numerical relation with respect to a given collection and a given thing. (relationExistsMaxInstance BINPRED COL THING N) means that there exists at most N instances (INST(1), ..., INST(N)) of COL that bear the relation PRED to THING such that (PRED INST(i) THING) holds (for 1 <= i <= N). This is equivalent to (and can thus be used in effect as shorthand for) the more complex form:

(thereExistAtMost N ?INST (and (isa ?INST COL) (BINPRED ?INST THING)))) .

For example, `(relationExistsMaxInstance physicalParts Hand MyLeftThumb 1)' means that my left thumb is part of at most one hand. Cf. relationInstanceExistsMax, and see the shared #$NoteAboutUseOfRuleMacroPredicates.
label: Relation Exists Max Instance
relationExistsMaxInstance

comment: (itemsCompared COMPARING ITEM-1 ITEM-2) means that ITEM-1 and ITEM-2 are compared in the instance of Comparing, COMPARING.
label: Items Compared
itemsCompared

comment: (roleCardinalityForSubsituationType SITTYPE SUBSITTYPE ROLE EXTENT) means that for any situation, SIT, that is an instance of SUBSITTYPE and a subsituation of an instance of SITTYPE, if anything plays ROLE in SIT, then the number of things that play ROLE in SIT is within the range EXTENT (that is, the number of things that play ROLE in SIT is between the minimum and the maximum of EXTENT, inclusive--see minQuantValue and maxQuantValue)
label: Role Cardinality For Subsituation Type
roleCardinalityForSubsituationType

comment: (adjSemTrans_Restricted WU SENSE FRAME COL TRANS) means that an adjective form of WU, when modifying a noun that denotes a spec of COL, with sense number SENSE and frame FRAME, means TRANS. For instance, (adjSemTrans_Restricted #$Sterile-TheWord 0 RegularAdjFrame Artifact (dirtinessOfObject :NOUN Sterile)) means that a phrase like 'sterile knife' can be interpreted as meaning (and (isa ?NOUN Knife) (dirtinessOfObject ?NOUN Sterile)), whereas for 'sterile man', this interpretation is not available.
label: Adj Sem Trans Restricted
adjSemTrans-Restricted

comment: A ternary complex action predicate. (doCloseClassDefinition PROGRAMMER FILE CLASS) means that PROGRAMMER appends code to the end of FILE that signifies the end of a declaration of the datatype CLASS.
label: Do Close Class Definition
doCloseClassDefinition

comment: The corresponding predicate of the function HypothesisLevelStrategyForPredAndArgsFn. A sentence of the form (hypothesisLevelStrategyForPredAndArgs STRAT PRED SET-OF-ARGS) states that the ScoringSoftwareStrategy STRAT is the one that rewards the holding of the Predicate PRED between some set of instances of HypotheticalContext and which rewards the hypotheses that fill the argument positions picked out by SET-OF-ARGS, a (SetOfTypeFn PositiveInteger).
label: Hypothesis Level Strategy For Pred And Args
hypothesisLevelStrategyForPredAndArgs

comment: combatForceValueOfUnitTypeWithEchelonSize helps specify quantitatively a default estimate of the cabilities of units of a particular MilitaryUnitSpecialtyType and #$MilitaryEchelon.
label: unit type combat force value
combatForceValueOfUnitTypeWithEchelonSize

comment: (interArgNotIsa3_5 PRED COL1 COL2) means that, when an instance of COL1 appears as the third argument to PRED, the fifth argument in that assertion is constrained to not be an instance of COL2 and vice versa.
label: Inter Arg Not Isa 3 5
interArgNotIsa3-5
Tactical Point From GIS
tacticalPoint-FromGIS
comment: (tacticalPoint_FromGIS TPOINT) means that TPOINT is an instance of TacticalPoint, according to some #$GeographicalInformationSystem to which Cyc has access.
If arg1 (PartiallyTangible or #$PieceOfFreeSpace) has (vis a vis placeHasOdor or objectEmitsOdor) some Odor arg2, tells its magnitude arg3.
label: Has Odor Magnitude
hasOdorMagnitude

comment: An instance of InterArgFormatPredicate (q.v.). (interArgFormat3_5 PRED COL FORMAT) means that FORMAT is a Format (q.v.) requirement for the fifth argument-place of PRED when PRED's third argument is an instance of COL. That is, with respect to a sentence of the form (PRED ARG1 ARG2 ARG3 ARG4 ARG5 ... ARGN) in which ARG3 is an instance of COL, PRED's arg5 position (i.e. the position occupied by the metavariable `ARG5' in the preceding sentence-form) is subject to FORMAT. See Format and its instances for further explanation.
label: Inter Arg Format 3 5
interArgFormat3-5

comment: (softwareParameterValueDomainInSoftwareObject SOFTWARE-PARAMETER SET-OR-COL SOFTWARE) means that the value of SOFTWARE-PARAMETER [see softwareParameterValue] is restricted to being an element/instance of the set/collection SET-OR-COL in SOFTWARE.
label: Software Parameter Value Domain In Software Object
softwareParameterValueDomainInSoftwareObject

comment:
(wordSenseExtension WORD SPEECH-PART-1 DENOTATION SPEECH-PART-2 EXTENSION LIST) means that the use of the word WORD with speech part SPEECH-PART-2 followed by the string picked out by LIST to mean EXTENSION is an extension of the sense of the compoundString associated with LIST and WORD -- in particular the sense with speech part SPEECH-PART-1 and denotation DENOTATION. For example, 
(compoundStringSenseExtension #$Bird-TheWord CountNoun BirdOfPrey MassNoun (MeatFn BirdOfPrey))
means that the use of "bird of prey" as a mass noun to refer to meat from birds of prey is an extension of the count noun sense of "bird of prey" meaning the BirdOfPrey.
label: Compound String Sense Extension
compoundStringSenseExtension

comment: (was_Metric TYPE NUM PROP) means that it was the case NUM `steps' backward that PROP, where the interpretation of `step' is determined by TYPE. For example, (was_Metric CalendarDay 2 `Fritz goes to California') means that Fritz went to California the day before yesterday, (was_Metric CalendarYear 1 `Cyc goes public') means that Cyc went public last year, and (was_Metric Friday 1 `Charles visits his dentist') means that Charles visited his dentist last Friday (the first Friday in the past, w.r.t. today). Note that when asserting (willBe_Metric TYPE NUM PROP) with a time index (see mtTimeIndex) t, one should make sure that t is subsumed by an instance of TYPE if TYPE is a member of CalendarCoveringType. In general, a rule of thumb is to have t be subsumed by (TimeInterval_Excl_Incl_Fn X Y), where X is the first member of TYPE in the past of t, and Y is the first member of TYPE in the future of X. (See other metric tense predicates willBe_Metric, was_Metric_CalendarTime and willBe_Metric_CalendarTime, and plain tense operators was and willBe etc.)
label: Was-Metric
was-Metric

comment: (properNounSemTrans NOUN INT FRAME TRANS) means that the translation of word sense number INT of proper noun NOUN in frame FRAME is TRANS.
label: Proper Noun Sem Trans
properNounSemTrans

comment: (restaurantsMenuItemPrice RESTAURANT FOOD PRICE) means that the Restaurant-Organization, RESTAURANT, offers to sell instances of FOOD at the price PRICE (an instance of MonetaryValue).
label: Restaurants Menu Item Price
restaurantsMenuItemPrice

comment: (ephemeralTerm TERM) states that TERM is a term that only has meaning in this particular copy of the knowledge base. A such, it can be viewed as an ephemeral concept which could likely be forgotten at some future point in time, perhaps by an explicit 'forgetting' process. See also termDependsOn.
label: Ephemeral Term
ephemeralTerm
Highly Relevant Mt
highlyRelevantMt
comment: A CycInferenceHeuristicRelevancePredicate. (highlyRelevantMt MT) means that all assertions in the Microtheory MT should be heuristically considered highly relevant to inferences done in the Microtheory MT-1 in which (highlyRelevantMt MT) is asserted (where MT-1 and MT need not be the same). As a consequence, note that when (highlyRelevantMt MT) is asserted in a Microtheory MT-1, each of the assertions in MT will be a highlyRelevantAssertion (q.v.) for inferences done in MT-1.

If SPACE is a TopologicalSpace with base set BASE and SET is a subset of BASE, then the sets A and B form a separation of SET if and only if the following conditions are met:

(SI) A and B are both non-empty, i.e. different from TheEmptySet.

(SII) SET is the union of A and B.

(SIIIa) The intersection of the closure of A and B is empty.

(SIIIb) The intersection of the closure of B and A is empty.

In CycL, this relation is expressed as (separationOfSetInTopologicalSpace A B SET SPACE).
label: Separation Of Set In Topological Space
separationOfSetInTopologicalSpace

comment: (actsInCapacity_JobCapacity AGT ROLE EVT-TYPE) holds just in case AGT's ROLE in acts of EVT-TYPE is in the capacity of a job.
label: job capacity
actsInCapacity-JobCapacity

comment: An instance of RuleMacroPredicate. (sitTypeEnablesAgentTo SITTYPE AGT EVENTTYPE) says that for every instance SIT of SITTYPE, (sitEnablesAgentTo SIT AGT EVENTTYPE).
label: Sit Type Enables Agent To
sitTypeEnablesAgentTo

comment: An instance of #$CompletenessGroundsPredicate that is used to state, about a collection or predicate whose extent is inferentially complete (see #$InferenceCompletenessPredicate), that the completeness derives mainly from a conventional stipulation, rather than from the nature of the items in the extent themselves, and that the convention is one stipulated by the designers of the Cyc system itself.
