typeBehaviorIncapable

comment: '(causes_SubSitTypeSubSitType SCRIPT SCENE1 SCENE2)' means that in any instantiation of SCRIPT, the subsituation which instantiates SCENE1 is the cause of the subsituation which instantiates SCENE2.
label: Causes Sub Sit Type Sub Sit Type
causes-SubSitTypeSubSitType

comment: A sentence of the form (functionFirstInputUnitOfMeasureForSit FUNCTION UNIT SITT) means that the PhysicalQuantityOrVectorFunction FUNCTION takes as its 'first' input a value that is measured in UNIT, some UnitOfMeasure relative to the PhysicalSituation SIT. The notion of 'first' here is intended only to allow for knowledge about the function to be shared across the predicates such as functionFirstInputValue.
label: Function First Input Unit Of Measure For Sit
functionFirstInputUnitOfMeasureForSit

comment: (sessionHasParameterizedQuerySentenceForDEEP SESSION PARAM-SET SENT) means that during SESSION, SENT must be posted to DEEP, with the parameters listed in PARAM-SET.
label: Session Has Parameterized Query Sentence For DEEP
sessionHasParameterizedQuerySentenceForDEEP
Non Abducible Sentence
nonAbducibleSentence
comment:
An instance of AbductionConstraintConstant (q.v.). (nonAbducibleSentence SENT) means that SENT is provable by the Cyc inference engine without using abduction.

nonAbducibleSentence is primarily used as a means of indicating that certain literals in a rule should never be abduced. Generally, it is used in the pragmatic requirements of rules as a wrapper around literals that already occur in the antecedents of these rules.

For example, consider the following rule: 

  (implies
    (and
      (isa ?METEOR Meteor)
      (primaryObjectMoving ?METEOR ?METEOROID))
    (inputsDestroyed ?METEOR ?METEOROID))
In this rule, if one wanted the '(primaryObjectMoving ?METEOR ?METEOROID)' literal to always be proved only through non-abductive means, one could add this pragmatic requirement as a meta-assertion: 
  (pragmaticRequirement
    (nonAbducibleSentence (primaryObjectMoving ?METEOR ?METEOROID))
  (implies
    (and
      (isa ?METEOR Meteor)
      (primaryObjectMoving ?METEOR ?METEOROID))
    (inputsDestroyed ?METEOR ?METEOROID)))
In this case, if the inference engine were trying to use this rule to prove (inputsDestroyed Event001 Object001) the inference engine would be free to abduce (isa Event001 Meteor) (assuming Meteor is not an instance of NonAbducibleCollection in the context of the proof), but the inference engine could not abduce (primaryObjectMoving Event001 Object001) -- that literal would have to be proven by other means, if at all.

An expression of the form (unaryPolynomialOfDegreeWithCoefficients FUNCTION DEGREE LIST) states that the UnaryPolynomialFunction FUNCTION is of degree DEGREE (that is the highest power to which the variable is raised) and the (ListOfTypeFn RealNumber) where the Nth element of list is the coefficient of the term in function that is raised to the power N-1. For instance, an expression of the form (UnaryPolynomialOfDegreeWithCoefficientsFn 2 (TheList 3 4 1)) could be written out as f(x) = x^2 + 4x + 3. This function abstracts away from the actual choice of variables in the formula.
label: Unary Polynomial Of Degree With Coefficients
unaryPolynomialOfDegreeWithCoefficients

comment: (termsMeetNCRuleSemanticConstraints MODIFIER-DENOT HEAD-DENOT RULE) means that MODIFIER-DENOT and HEAD-DENOT meet the semantic constraints on the modifier and head (respectively) or RULE.
label: Terms Meet NC Rule Semantic Constraints
termsMeetNCRuleSemanticConstraints

comment: assertTemplate_Reln relates a class of natural language assertions (e.g. sentences) to CycL. Unlike assertTemplate, assertTemplate_Reln has a slot for the Relation (function or pred) that is the focus of the CycL translation. For example, (assertTemplate_Reln STemplate objectHasColor ((NPTemplate :subj) "is" "colored" (AdjPTemplate :obj)) (objectHasColor :subj :obj)) would map "Muffet is colored strawberry-blonde" to (objectHasColor Muffet StrawberryBlonde_HairColor), and the template is indexed under Arg2 of objectHasColor.
label: Assert Template Reln
assertTemplate-Reln

comment: It is medically recommended that the BLO with the condition ARG1 (note that it's a particular instance of a condition and not the condition type) play the role ARG3 in some instance of ARG2, in order to ameliorate the condition.

medicallyRecommended

comment: A ternary predicate that relates a given US state to the range of five-digit zip codes available for use in that state. (zipCodeRangeOfState STATE LOWZIP HIGHZIP) means that all the ZipCode_FiveDigits used in STATE are alphabetically between LOWZIP and HIGHZIP inclusive.

(exploitFaultOfProgramOnSystemWithInstrument_ReportIndexed AGENT FAULT PROGRAM SYSTEM THING REP) means that AGENT uses THING to exploit the FAULT of PROGRAM described in REP when PROGRAM is running on SYSTEM.

comment: A KEFacilitationPredicate and RuleMacroPredicate. (keStrongSuggestionPreds_Ins COL BINPRED THING) means that for every known (i.e. Cyc-reified) instance INST of COL, it is strongly suggested that (BINPRED INST THING) is known in the Knowledge Base.
label: Ke Strong Suggestion Preds Ins
keStrongSuggestionPreds-Ins

comment: A meridian of a surface of revolution with respect to an axis of revolution is the intersection of the surface with a plane containing the axis of revolution. (meridianForAxisOfSurfaceOfRevolution MERIDIAN AXIS SURFACE) means that MERIDIAN is a meridian for the axis, AXIS, of the SurfaceOfRevolution, SURFACE. It is necessary to specify the axis in this relation because some surfaces of revolution may be generated by revolving a generatrix about different axes, and a meridian of <SURFACE> with respect to one axis is not a meridian with respect to a different axis. Note also that our use of the term meridian is consistent with the mathematical vocabulary of surface geometry, however it is not consistent with the cartographic use of the term.
label: Meridian For Axis Of Surface Of Revolution
meridianForAxisOfSurfaceOfRevolution

comment: (subEchelonsInOrg SUPERLEVEL SUBLEVEL SCALE) means that the echelon SUBLEVEL is the next strictly 'lower' (not as high as) echelon below SUPERLEVEL in the partially ordered echelon system represented by SCALE, exactly one level lower (immediate successor) than SUPERLEVEL in the same BranchOfMilitaryService.
label: subechelon in an organization
subEchelonsInOrg

comment:
A ternary predicate that is used to describe the spatial orientation of one thing in relation to the another, by specifying an axis of the former that intersects with the latter. (orientationToObject OBJ AXIS THING) means that an intrinsic axis (see objectAxes) of OBJ, AXIS, intersects with THING. Typically, AXIS will be specified using BilateralAxisFn, thus indicating which axis of OBJ's we're talking about. For example, 
(orientationToObject 
    MyHouse 
    (BilateralAxisFn MyHouse LeftSide RightSide) 
    MyGarage)
says that my garage is beside my house. But note that it does not specify which side of my house, the left or the right, the garage is on; for the second and third arguments of BilateralAxisFn commute.

See also facesDirection.
label: direction an object is facing
orientationToObject

comment: (typesDifferInValue COLL1 COLL2 COLL-TYPE) holds just in case instances of COLL1 will differ from instances of COLL2 with respect to COLL-TYPE. For instance, (typesDifferInValue Emerald_Gem Ruby_Gem Color) holds because instances of Emerald_Gem are a different color than instances of Ruby_Gem. So, if Ruby-1 and Emerald-1 are instances of Ruby_Gem and Emerald_Gem, respectively, then (differentInValue Ruby-1 Emerald-1 Color) holds.
label: Types Differ In Value
typesDifferInValue

comment: (argGenlPreds REL N PRED) means that anything given as the Nth argument to the relationship REL must be a specialization of PRED or PRED itself.
label: Arg Genl Preds
argGenlPreds

comment: Predicate used for specifying the contexts in which to ask the antecedent and propagate the instantiated consequent of a rule stored as the InferenceSentenceParameter of a CycLRuleSpecification. (ksRangeInSpecification RuleAntecedentParameter MT-SET SPEC) means that the antecedent of the rule given (via softwareParameterValueInSpecification) as the InferenceSentenceParameter of SPEC should be asked in the microtheoretic union of the elements of MT-SET and its upward closure under genlMt. (ksRangeInSpecification RuleConsequentParameter MT-SET SPEC) means that the set of assertions resulting from instantitating the consequent of the rule given (via softwareParameterValueInSpecification) as the InferenceSentenceParameter of SPEC should all be asserted in each of the microtheories that is an element of MT-SET.
label: Ks Range In Specification
ksRangeInSpecification

comment: (relationAllSpecsExistsSpec PRED COL1 COL2) means that for all subcollection SUBCOL1 of COL1, there exists a subcollection of COL2, say SUBCOL2, such that (PRED SUBCOL1 SUBCOL2) holds. This assumes that PRED is a type level predicate.

relationAllSpecsExistsSpec

comment: A ternary instance of InterArgIsaPredicate (q.v.). (interArgIsa2_5 RELN INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL DEPENDENT-ARG-COL) means that, when an instance of INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL appears as the second argument to RELN, a necessary condition for semantic well-formedness is that the fifth argument must be an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. That is, if INST is an instance of INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL, then (RELN ARG1 INST ARG3 ARG4 ARG5 ... ARGN) is semantically well-formed only if ARG5 is an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. For an explanation of semantic well-formedness, see CycLExpression_Assertible and its direct specializations.
label: Inter Arg Isa 2 5
interArgIsa2-5

comment: (irExpansionCandidate THING-EXPANDED EXPANSION-STRATEGY CANDIDATE) says that CANDIDATE is a proposed candidate for providing IR expansion information for THING-EXPANDED, using EXPANSION-STRATEGY, an instance of IRExpansionStrategy.

comment: (levelOfPhysicalExertion AGNT ACT LEVEL) means that AGNT does ACT with a level of physical exertion LEVEL. E.g., (levelOfPhysicalExertion DonovanBailey RunningMens100MRaceIn1996Olympics veryHighAmountOf).
label: Level Of Physical Exertion
levelOfPhysicalExertion

comment: An assertion of the form (roleInScriptRequires_Pos SITTYPE ROLE QUERY) states that in order for any instance of SomethingExisting to play ROLE in an instance of SITTYPE , then the conditions represented via QUERY, some sub-collection of CycLQuerySpecification, and the InferenceSentenceParameter of the softwareParameterValueInSpecification associated with QUERY must be true concerning the actor who would fill that role. Stictly speaking, these are not logically sufficient conditions, but necessary conditions for being able to fill the role. Thus, they could be labelled 'qualifications.'

roleInScriptRequires-Pos

comment:
A quintary (5-place) RuleMacroPredicate. (actTypeRoleEffectiveForActTypeRole ACT-TYPE-1 ROLE-1 ACT-TYPE-2 ROLE-2 THING) is shorthand for the following rule: 
(implies
  (and
    (subcollectionOfWithRelationTo ACT-TYPE-1 ROLE-1 THING ?SUBCOL-1)
    (subcollectionOfWithRelationTo ACT-TYPE-2 ROLE-2 THING ?SUBCOL-2))
  (effectiveActTypeForActType ?SUBCOL-1 ?SUBCOL-2))
Thus, for example, 
(actTypeRoleEffectiveForActTypeRole PushingSomeone objectActedOn FallingDown primaryObjectMoving Bob)
says, basically, that pushing Bob is a good way to make him fall down.
label: Act Type Role Effective For Act Type Role
actTypeRoleEffectiveForActTypeRole

comment: A sentence of the form (cyclificationOfStringFromParser STRING CYCL PARSER) means that CYCL is one interpretation of STRING according to the Cyclifier and PARSER.
label: Cyclification Of String From Parser
cyclificationOfStringFromParser

comment: (keTestQuestionForTerm TERM FORMULA QUERY-SPEC) says that for TERM, the CycLFormula FORMULA is an interesting question to ask, where the relevant query parameters are determined by the CycLQuerySpecification QUERY-SPEC.

keTestQuestionForTerm

comment:
A ternary instance of InterArgIsaPredicate (q.v.). (interArgEqualsIsa4_1 RELN INDEPENDENT-ARG DEPENDENT-ARG-COL) means that, when INDEPENDENT-ARG appears as the fourth argument to RELN, a necessary condition for semantic well-formedness is that the first argument must be an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. That is, (RELN ARG1 ARG2 ARG3 INDEPENDENT-ARG ...) is semantically well-formed only if ARG1 is an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL.

For an explanation of semantic well-formedness, see CycLExpression_Assertible and its direct specializations. See interArgEqualsIsa for a similar but more general predicate that is quintary, allowing the user to specify the positions of the independent and dependent arguments.
label: Inter Arg Equals Isa 4 1
interArgEqualsIsa4-1

comment: A QueryDedicatedPredicate used for comparing one CycL term with another.
label: Query Basic Comparison On Terms
queryBasicComparisonOnTerms

comment: A ternary instance of InterArgIsaPredicate (q.v.). (interArgIsa4_1 RELN INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL DEPENDENT-ARG-COL) means that, when an instance of INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL appears as the fourth argument to RELN, a necessary condition for semantic well-formedness is that the first argument must be an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. That is, if INST is an instance of INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL, then (RELN ARG1 ARG2 ARG3 INST ... ARGN) is semantically well-formed only if ARG1 is an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. For an explanation of semantic well-formedness, see CycLExpression_Assertible and its direct specializations.
label: Inter Arg Isa 4 1
interArgIsa4-1

comment: A ternary ArgIsaPredicate (q.v.) used to place a specified isa based argument-type constraint on a given VariableArityRelation (q.v.) with respect to any of its argument-places whose ordinal position is greater than or equal to a specified number. (argAndRestIsa RELN N COL) means that, as a necessary condition for semantic well-formedness, anything given as the Nth or greater argument to RELN must be an instance of COL. Thus a closed formula (RELN ARG1..ARG(N)..ARG(N+1)..) is well-formed only if each of ARG(N)..ARG(N+1).. is an instance of COL. See also argsIsa and argAndRestGenl.
label: Arg And Rest Isa
argAndRestIsa

comment:
A ternary predicate that relates a pair of tangible objects, space regions, or spatially-localized events to their mereological product or intersection. (spatialProduct PRODUCT THING1 THING2) means that PRODUCT is the unique SpatialThing (of the same basic type as THING1 and THING2) such that a spatial thing intersects (see spatiallyIntersects) PRODUCT if and only if it intersects with both THING1 and THING2.

Note that "of the same basic type" in the above means that the three relata are either all PartiallyTangibles, all SpaceRegions, or all Event_Localizeds. This restriction is needed in order to ensure the uniqueness of PRODUCT, since a tangible object, a space region, and an event can have the same spatial extent (see cospatial), despite their being distinct things.

See the corresponding function SpatialProductFn. Also see spatialSum and spatialDifference.
label: spatial product
spatialProduct

comment: An assertion of the form (literalHasStringInArg LIT STRING N) states that the SubLString STRING is the value of the Nth argument in the (CycLObjectTypeFn CycLAtomicSentence) LIT.
label: Literal Has String In Arg
literalHasStringInArg
The Cyclist
theCyclist
comment: (theCyclist CYCLIST) specifies the current human CYCLIST logged in in the current image.

This QuaternaryPredicate is used to state that, when certain sorts of inferences take place, argument admittance verification is required for a specified argument-place of a certain predicate, where this predicate and argument-place number are related to some transitive binary predicate via either transitiveViaArg or transitiveViaArgInverse. More precisely, (argAdmittanceTestedDuringTransitiveViaInference TVA-PRED INDEX-PRED TRANS-PRED N) means that when the assertion corresponding to (TVA-PRED INDEX-PRED TRANS-PRED N) is used for unification of some atomic sentence SENTENCE during transitiveViaArg or transitiveViaArgInverse reasoning, argument admittance is verified for the term in SENTENCE that has the position specified by N. The INDEX-PRED predicate (i.e. the 0th-place argument in SENTENCE), its relevant argument-place N, and the transitive predicate, TRANS-PRED, with respect to which the argument admittance verification is to be carried out are all specified by the argAdmittanceTestedDuringTransitiveViaInference assertion. The utility of argAdmittanceTestedDuringTransitiveViaInference is as follows. Suppose (e.g.) that (transitiveViaArg INDEX-PRED TRANS-PRED N) and (INDEX-PRED ... ARGN ...) both hold. In some such cases, any term in the "transitive closure" of ARGN via TRANS-PRED is itself an admissible argument for INDEX-PRED's Nth argument-place. But in certain other cases this is not so, and thus argument admittance testing is needed to determine whether a given member of this transitive closure is admissible in INDEX-PRED's Nth argument-place. argAdmittanceTestedDuringTransitiveViaInference is used to specify cases of the latter sort, where argument admittance testing is required, and thereby enables us to avoid the unnecessary expense of testing all cases.
label: Arg Admittance Tested During Transitive Via Inference
argAdmittanceTestedDuringTransitiveViaInference

comment: This predicate relates instances of set or collection and instances of EquivalenceRelation to the partitioning that results from applying the given equivalence relation to the set or collection. (partitionedIntoViaEquivRelation SETORCOL ER PARTITIONING) means that each element of PARTITIONING is a subset, or subcollection of SETORCOL and any particular element of PARTITIONING contains all the members of SETORCOL that bear the relation ER to each other.
label: Partitioned Into Via Equiv Relation
partitionedIntoViaEquivRelation

comment: (importRateThrough REGION PRODUCT-TYPE PT RATE) means that the GeographicalRegion REGION imports instances of the ProductType PRODUCT-TYPE through the instance of PartiallyTangible PT (on their way from their origin) at the Rate RATE. PT might, in the case of oil imports, for example, be a GeographicalRegion or a Pipeline. Note that since things imported are typically measurable in terms of their monetary value, RATE might in some instances be a MonetaryRate; in others it will be, for example, a rate of volume, mass, or number.
label: Import Rate Through
importRateThrough

comment: `(filedJointReturnWith YEAR PERSON1 PERSON2)' means that PERSON1 and PERSON2 filed joint returns together for YEAR.
label: Filed Joint Return With
filedJointReturnWith

comment: A MetaRelation predicate for stating a quite general sort of argument-type constraint on a specified argument-place of a specified relation, where the constraint is membership (see elementOf) in a given SetOrCollection (q.v.). (argElementOf REL N SETORCOLL) means that semantic well-formedness requires that anything given as the Nth argument to REL be an element of SETORCOLL. (An exception to this is when N is 0: (argElementOf REL 0 SETORCOLL) means that _any_ argument to REL, regardless of argument place, must be an element of SETORCOLL.) argElementOf is useful for stating constraints that are specified with the use of set-theoretical relations such as TheSetOf or TheSet. For cases where a constraint can be specified strictly in terms of membership in a certain Collection, consider the more specialized predicate argIsa.
label: Arg Element Of
argElementOf

comment:
An ArgCardinalityPredicate (q.v.) that can be used to put a "state-of-the-KB" cardinality constraint on a predicate with respect to a given argument-place. Unlike with most argument-constraint predicates, a constraint imposed by assertedArgCardinality is not intended necessarily to reflect the intrinsic nature of the constrained predicate per se, but to limit the number of sentences built from (the CycL term for) the predicate that can coexist as assertions in the Cyc Knowledge Base. Thus a cardinality constraint imposed by assertedArgCardinality can be (and normally is) stricter than the appropriate analogous constraint imposed by argCardinality (q.v.).

(assertedArgCardinality PRED N CARD) means that, at any given time, the KB should contain no more than CARD different assertions of the form (PRED ... ARGNI ...) that are all exactly alike except that they each have a different term ARGNI in their respective Nth argument-positions.

See also argCardinality and interArgCardinality.
label: Asserted Arg Cardinality
assertedArgCardinality

comment: (successiveOrgPositions ORG POS1 POS2) means that in the Organization ORG, an individual who holds POS1 in ORG is expected to hold POS2 at a later date. To put it another way, the expectation is that POS1 and POS2 will be held in temporal succession, though not necessarily in immediate temporal succession.
label: Successive Org Positions
successiveOrgPositions

comment: A predicate that relates an argument-position and a CycL term to a CycL formula in which the term appears (in that position) and a second CycL formula in which has identical arguments to the first in every argument position save the one represented by the integer; substituteArgPositionIn is a QuaternaryPredicate that relates an instance of FormulaArgPosition to an instance of CycLTerm and two instances of CycLFormula. (substituteArgPositionIn POSITION TERM FORMULA-OLD FORMULA-NEW) means that TERM occurs as in POSITION of FORMULA-NEW and that otherwise FORMULA-OLD and FORMULA-NEW are identical.
label: Substitute Arg Position In
substituteArgPositionIn

easilyUnderstoodByHumans

(textualPCWSubSectionOfTypeWithID SUBSECTION PCW PCW-TYPE ID) identifies SUBSECTION as the instance of PCW-TYPE that is a textualPCWSubSections of the TextualPCW PCW, distinguished from--and ordered among--other sub-sections of that type by virtue of the ID string ID-STRING. This is the corresponding predicate to the function TextualPCWSubSectionOfTypeWithIDFn.

textualPCWSubSectionOfTypeWithID

comment: (referencedEditorOfPublication PERSON LITERARYWORK N) means that PERSON is one of the editors of LITERARYWORK, and is the Nth editor credited in references to LITERARYWORK.

referencedEditorOfPublication

label: Packaging Of Type
packagingOfType

comment: (importRateFrom REGION1 PRODUCT-TYPE REGION2 RATE) means that the GeographicalRegion REGION1 imports instances of the ProductType PRODUCT-TYPE from the GeographicalRegion REGION2 at the Rate RATE. Note that since things imported are typically measurable in terms of their monetary value, RATE might in some instances be a MonetaryRate; in others it will be, for example, a rate of volume, mass, or number.
label: Import Rate From
importRateFrom

comment:
A unary #$InferenceCompletenessPredicate and a specialization of grosslyIncompleteWithAllArgsNotFullyBound (q.v.) that can apply to a predicate. (grosslyIncompleteWithAnyArgsNotFullyBound PRED) means that the Cyc inference engine will treat as "grossly incomplete" any removal tactic for a problem with PRED in the arg0 position and with any other argument positions open.

A good example of a predicate that is grosslyIncompleteWithAnyArgsNotFullyBound is spatiallySubsumes_TypeType. Generally, for no two shapes will it ever be asserted that one fits in the other.

Cf. grosslyIncompleteWithArgNotFullyBound.
label: Grossly Incomplete With Any Args Not Fully Bound
grosslyIncompleteWithAnyArgsNotFullyBound
subPropertyOf: Grossly Incomplete With All Args Not Fully Bound

comment: An expression of the form (displaysCycLAsString EVT CYCL STRING) means that during the VisualInformationGeneratingAct EVT, the (quoted) CycLExpression CYCL is represented in the form of the CharacterString STRING.
label: Displays Cyc LAs String
displaysCycLAsString

comment: This predicate expresses the relationship between a wh adverb, a word sense, a subcategorization frame, and a CycL expression used to denote the adverb.
label: Wh Adverb Sem Trans
whAdverbSemTrans

comment:
This predicate can be used to assert that an agent has made a certain essentially subjective assessment or value judgment about a particular individual. (subjectivelyEvaluates AGENT INDIV EVAL) means that the AGENT projects upon INDIV the EvaluativeQuantity (q.v.) EVAL. As the evaluation in question is essentially subjective, the above formula of course does _not_ entail either (i) that INDIV actually has the feature it is subjectively thought to have (or some "objective" counterpart thereof) or (ii) that any other given agent would also attribute EVAL to INDIV. Indeed, outside of contexts explicitly defined so as to represent some particular agent's point of view (e.g. some sentient agent's inner mental world or the world-view espoused by a particular religion), it arguably makes no sense to attribute an EvaluativeQuantity to an individual directly.

For example, (subjectivelyEvaluates Sally SallyLearningToRideABike Easy) says that Sally herself finds/found learning to ride a bike easy; and this might be true regardless of any "objective" ranking of the relative level of difficulty involved in learning to ride a bike, and regardless even of any third-person observer's judgment as to how hard or easy a time Sally had learning to ride. (Of course, assuming Sally is at least minimally self-aware and the observer similarly perceptive, we would expect their respective judgments on this point likely to match fairly well.)

Note that AGENT's basis for the assessment might be largely emotional, logical-inferential (e.g. having a plausible argument), empirical, or some combination of these. Note also that, while there is an almost trivially sense in which _any_ judgment or attribution made by a sentient agent has a subjective (i.e. conscious, inner) aspect or manifestation, subjectivelyEvaluates pertains specifically to EvaluativeQuantity, and thus to what are normally considered value judgments (broadly construed). Hence the use of the expressions "essentially subjective" and "projects upon" in the foregoing to describe the sort of attributions at issue.

For a similar predicate that relates an agent to a state of affairs onto which s/he projects an evaluative attribute, see evaluates_Propositional.
label: Subjectively Evaluates
subjectivelyEvaluates

comment: (preservesRelnInArg FN BIN-PRED N) means that if NAT1 and NAT2 are non-atomic terms generated by means of FN, and (BINPRED ARG1 ARG2) is known to be true, and ARG1 appears as the Nth argument of NAT1 and ARG2 appears as then Nth argument of NAT2, then (BIN-PRED NAT1 NAT2).
label: Preserves Reln In Arg
preservesRelnInArg

comment: An instance of TernaryPredicate that relates an agent and one of his or her actions to one of the motives behind that action. (agentsActionHasMotives AGENT ACTION MOTIVE) identifies MOTIVE as one of the instances of IntentionalMentalState that motivated AGENT to perform (c.f., performedBy) the action (c.f., Action) ACTION. See also motivesForAction.
label: Agents Action Has Motive
agentsActionHasMotive
subPropertyOf: Agent Has Motive For Action Ternary

comment: A sentence of the form (valueOfDuringForQuantity FUNC THING EVENT IN-QUANT OUT-QUANT) states that the property of the Thing THING that is denoted by the PhysicalQuantityOrVectorFunction_SingleInput during the Event EVENT, has a value of OUT-QUANT, some determining Quantity, when the input quanity to FUNC is the Quantity IN-QUANT.
label: Value Of During For Quantity
valueOfDuringForQuantity

comment:
A FirstOrderCollectionPredicate and a specialization of typeIntendedBehaviorCapable (q.v.) that is used to represent the primary use associated with some type of object (usually instances of PhysicalDevice but also instances of Organization, or anything else that can be said to have a function) as a consequence of the intent with which that type of object was designed. (typePrimaryFunction OBJ-TYPE SIT-TYPE ROLE) means that instances of OBJ-TYPE are primarily intended to participate in situations of type SIT-TYPE in the instance of Role ROLE. For example, the primary use associated with any instance of ElectricalToaster is making toast: we can represent this by (typePrimaryFunction ElectricalToaster MakingToast deviceUsed). As another example, the primary use associated with a government intelligence organization is performing instances of IntelligenceAnalysisProcess. We can represent this as (typePrimaryFunction GovernmentIntelligenceOrganization IntelligenceAnalysisProcess performedBy).

Note that this predicate should be used to represent only the very specific SIT-TYPE in which something is intended to function in some role. For example, in most contexts, while it is correct to assert (typePrimaryFunction Telephone AudioCommunicating deviceUsed), it is not correct to assert (typePrimaryFunction Telephone Communicating deviceUsed) since Communicating is not specific enough. Instead of the latter sentence, (typeIntendedBehaviorCapable Telephone Communicating deviceUsed) is preferable. When asserting a typePrimaryFunction GAF, use the most specific Situation SIT-TYPE available in the microtheory in which you are making the assertion, as long as you do not believe SIT-TYPE is too specific. If no Situation specific enough is available, consider creating one.

This predicate presupposes that instances of the first argument have the function that they do in virtue of the design of some intelligent agent. If the "functionality" in question does not obviously derive from some agent's design or artifice, typePrimaryFunction_AgnosticIntentional (q.v.) should be used instead. See also (TypeCapableFn behaviorCapable), typeIntendedBehaviorCapable and primaryFunction.
label: Type Primary Function
typePrimaryFunction

comment: This predicate is used to indicate those instances of SomethingExisting that are used by some instance of Agent_PartiallyTangible in any instance of Communicating and that are created for the purpose of aiding information transfer. (meansOfCommunicationFor COMM THING AGT) means that the instance AGT of Agent_PartiallyTangible uses the instance THING of SomethingExisting in the instance COMM of Communicating and that (meansOfInfoTransfer COMM THING) holds. For instance, if a particular student Student001 uses a particular telephone Telephone001 to call her father in some instance of Communicating Communicating001, we could represent this by (meansOfCommunicationFor Communicating001 Telephone001 Student001). If her father FatherOfStudent001 uses telephone Telephone002 in this same instance of Communicating, then we would have (meansOfCommunicationFor Communicating001 Telephone002 FatherOfStudent001). See also meansOfInfoTransfer_Artifact and meansOfInfoTransfer_ComputerProgram. Using the former predicate, for example, we could state for the above example (meansOfInfoTransfer_Artifact Communicating001 Telephone001) and (meansOfInfoTransfer_Artifact Communicating001 Telephone002). Note that the former of these implies (meansOfInfoTransfer Communicating001 Telephone001).
label: Means Of Communication For
meansOfCommunicationFor

comment: (costOfAction ACT AGENT PROP SUBJ-ATTR) holds iff the AGENT's evaluation of the desirability of PROP, the outcome of ACT, corresponds to SUBJ-ATTR. In other words, costOfAction expresses the agent's judgment about whether the action is worth the effort of performing it. Such a judgment is evaluative, because it depends upon the agent's assignment of preferences to the expected outcome of the action. Notice that, given the way outcomeOfAction is defined, PROP involves a specification of all value-relevant features of the result of ACT.
label: Cost Of Action
costOfAction
greater than with respect to a slot
greaterThanWRTSlot

comment: (typePlaysRoleInRegion TYPE SIT-TYPE ROLE REGION) says that in REGION, it is common-place for instances of TYPE to play ROLE in instances of SIT-TYPE. So, for example, (typePlaysRoleInRegion Opium MoneyTransfer objectTendered Afghanistan) says that in Afghanistan, Opium is frequently used like money.
label: Type Plays Role In Region
typePlaysRoleInRegion
First IABP At Date WRT Operation
firstIABPAtDateWRTOperation

comment: agentFinalScoreInGame is a TernaryPredicate and a TemporallyQualifiableRelation. An assertion of the form (agentHasScoreInGame AGENT SCORE EVENT) states that the Agent_Generic had scored a total of SCORE points within the entirety of GameEvent EVENT.
label: Agent Final Score In Game
agentFinalScoreInGame

comment: This predicate is used by the SKSI code to estimate the cost of querying the fields of a physical schema. More precisely, let SCHEMA denote a physical schema, let PF-1, PF-2, ..., PF-N, denote the physical fields of SCHEMA, and let SELECT_SET and WHERE_SET denote two disjoint subsets of (TheSet PF-1 PF-2 ... PF-N). Then (resultSetCardinality SCHEMA SELECT_SET WHERE_SET NUM) means that NUM is the average cardinality of the result set returned from a query in which the fields in SELECT_SET left unbound and the fields of WHERE_SET are bound.
label: Result Set Cardinality
resultSetCardinality
Unknown Deceased
unknownDeceased
comment: (unknownDeceased ANIMAL) means that ANIMAL is not known (by the Cyc system) to be deceased. This predicate is not assertible.

(scheduledStartDateOfSitOfTypeInScriptedSitOfType SUB-SIT-TYPE SIT SIT-TYPE SCHED-DATE) means that SCHED-DATE is the date that an instance INST of SUB-SIT-TYPE is scheduled to occur, at which time INST will be a sub-situation of SIT, which is itself an instance of SIT-TYPE that has SUB-SIT-TYPE as at least a candidate sub-situation type (see candidateSubSituationTypes).
label: Scheduled Start Date Of Sit Of Type In Scripted Sit Of Type
scheduledStartDateOfSitOfTypeInScriptedSitOfType

comment: (userComputerToolUsageLevel USER SOFTWARE SKILL-LEVEL) means that USER can use running instantiations of SOFTWARE with the skill level, SKILL-LEVEL (an instance of ToolUsageLevel).

userComputerToolUsageLevel

comment: This predicate relates two instances of TemporalThing to the (longest) instance of TimeInterval between, and including, them. (timeIntervalInclusive INTERVAL EARLIER LATER) means that INTERVAL is the time interval that starts when EARLIER begins and ends when LATER ends. LATER must begin after EARLIER begins.
label: Time Interval Inclusive
timeIntervalInclusive

comment: (earthCoordinatesOfObject OBJ LAT LONG) means that the latitude of OBJ is LAT and the longitude of OBJ is LONG. It was created in service to the geographical reasoner being constructed at NWU, which needs to see latitude and longitude as arguments in the same predicate structure.
label: Earth Coordinates Of Object
earthCoordinatesOfObject

comment: This predicate relates a creation event to the number or level of production of a kind of thing in that event. (amountProducedInEvent EVENT OBJECT-TYPE NUM) means that the number of instances of OBJECT-TYPE created in EVENT is NUM.
label: Amount Produced In Event
amountProducedInEvent

comment: Arg3 is the proportion out of total dollar sales in the market ARG2 that went to the agent Arg1.
label: Market Share
marketShare

comment: The predicate waveSource_Direct is used to indicate that there is a wave propagation of some type directly between two points. (waveSource_Direct SOURCE ENDPOINT WAVETYPE) means that there is a WavePropagation of type WAVETYPE between the fromLocation SOURCE and the toLocation ENDPOINT, and the propagation is direct in the sense that there are no significant diffusion or reflection subevents of that WavePropagation.
label: Wave Source Direct
waveSource-Direct
Needs Hand Lexification
needsHandLexification
comment: (needsHandLexification TERM-STRINGS-ASSERTION) implies that the Cyc-term specified in TERM-STRINGS-ASSERTION needs to be lexified manually. It should not be lexified with the help of the SubL Function 'lex-loop'
(fieldCodes FIELD VALUE MEANING) indicates that if the value of the logical or physical field FIELD is VALUE, it should be interpreted to mean MEANING.

fieldCodes

comment:
A RuleMacroPredicate. (most_GenQuantRelnFromType BINPRED SOC1 SOC2) means that most elements ELEM2 of SOC2 are such that for some element ELEM1 of SOC1, (BINPRED ELEM1 ELEM2). It is equivalent to the more complex form: 
(most SOC2
  (TheSetOf ?OBJ
    (thereExists ?THING
      (and
        (elementOf ?THING SOC1)
        (BINPRED ?THING ?OBJ))))).
For example, (most_GenQuantRelnFromType musicTracks GreatestHitsAlbum_CW HitSong_CW) means that most hit songs are tracks on some greatest hits album.

When SOC1 and SOC2 are Collections, use the more specialized relationExistsMost.
label: Most Gen Quant Reln From Type
most-GenQuantRelnFromType

comment: instances of ExistingObjectType (and subsets of Agent_Generic) perform all their Actions of the given type in a location of ObjectType. Invented for use *only* when location information is local to the Actor. For example, Ballerina performs Dancing in ConcertHall, but Dancing may occur in lots of places. Invented to describe Professionals but may evolve for use with other collections. For an instance-level version of this predicate, see performsInsAtLocation.
label: Performs Ins At Loc Type
performsInsAtLocType
Reln Holds Between Proper Parts In Viable Instance
relnHoldsBetweenProperPartsInViableInstance

comment: From the perspective of ARG1, ARG2 is apparently between (colinear with) ARG3 and ARG4.
label: Apparently Between
apparentlyBetween

comment: (positionNotUserEditable TEMPLATE POSITION TOPIC) means that when TEMPLATE in invoked under TOPIC, the user will not be able to type information for replaceable position POSITION. In other words, this position will restrict the user to the candidate replacements generated in the drop-down menu.
label: Position Not User Editable
positionNotUserEditable

comment: The predicate corresponding to SchemaIndexFn. (schemaFieldsIndex SCHEMA FIELD-LIST NAME INDEX) means that INDEX is an IndexDataStructure named NAME in the physical schema SCHEMA which indexes the physical fields in FIELD-LIST. See also indexType and indexName.
label: Schema Fields Index
schemaFieldsIndex

comment: A sentence of the form (pegDerivedSentenceFromInterpretation PEG CYCL MT) means that the Microtheory MT is a possible interpretation of the LinguisticExpressionPeg_CompleteUtterance PEG and that CYCL is a CycLSentence that is both entailed by the content of MT (see #$mtFocalContent) and that is known to be true from the content model of PEG (see, contentModelFocalPeg).
label: Peg Derived Sentence From Interpretation
pegDerivedSentenceFromInterpretation
subPropertyOf: Peg Derived Sentence Draws On Interpretations

comment: (programRunningOnComputerHasFault PROG COMP FAULT) means that the copy of PROG which is currently running on (programRunningOn, q.v.) COMP manifests FAULT.
label: Program Running On Computer Has Fault
programRunningOnComputerHasFault

comment: '(significantSubEvents RESULT-TYPE COMPONENT-TYPE PERF-QUANT-TYPE QUANTITY)' means that performing acts of type COMPONENT-TYPE with the quantity QUANTITY is required for the performance of RESULT-TYPE to have a high degree of PERF-QUANT-TYPE. For example, '(significantSubEvents SpeedSkatingSportsEvent BodyMovementEvent Effectiveness (HighToVeryHighAmountFn Agility))' means that performing a speed skating sporting event with a high degree of effectiveness requires performing some body movement events with a high to very high amount of agility.
label: Significant Sub Events
significantSubEvents

comment: Where (properSubSituationTypes SITTYPE SUBSITTYPE), (disjunctiveProperSubSituationTypes SITTYPE SUBSITTYPE-TYPE LIST) means that in an instance SIT of SITTYPE with a sub-situation that is an instance SUBSIT of SUBSITTYPE, SUBSIT is also required to be an instance of at least one of the collections listed in LIST. For instance, one might specify that in a bank robbery, the getaway scene is an instance either of Running or of (TransportViaFn RoadVehicle).
label: Disjunctive Proper Sub Situation Types
disjunctiveProperSubSituationTypes

comment: requiresToPlayRole is an instance of ResourcePredicate. (requiresToPlayRole OBJ OBJTYPE EVENTTYPE ROLE) means that, in order to play ROLE in an event of EVENTTYPE, OBJ requires an instance of OBJTYPE. Note that this is neutral as to whether or not OBJ desires to, needs to, or actually will play ROLE in such an event. See also typeRequiresToPlayRole.
label: Requires To Play Role
requiresToPlayRole

comment: An instance of ExistentialQuantifier_Bounded (q.v.) that can be used to make rough or inexact statements about the number of things that satisfy a given criterion. (thereExistRange RANGE VAR SENT) is true if and only if the number of things in the universe of discourse that satisfy SENT with respect to VAR falls within RANGE (see NonNegativeIntegerRange). (A given THING "satisfies SENT with respect to VAR" just in case any sentence obtained by substituting a CycL name of THING for each free occurrence of VAR within SENT is true.) For example, the sentence '(thereExistRange Billions_Quant ?X (isa ?X Star))' means that there are billions of stars.
label: There Exist Range
thereExistRange

comment: (unemploymentRateDuring REGION THING NR) means that NR is the average unemployment rate of the GeographicalRegion REGION during the temporal extent of the TemporalThing THING, where the unemployment rate of a region at a point in time is the quotient of the number of unemployed persons in the region and the region's labor force (that is, the sum of the number of employed and unemployed persons in the region). THING will often be a calendar time period; but it may also be, for instance, a particular Event. For example, to express the fact that the United States' unemployment rate in 1996 was 5.4%, we can say (unemploymentRateDuring UnitedStatesOfAmerica (YearFn 1996) .054).
label: Unemployment Rate During
unemploymentRateDuring
Sample Space
sampleSpace
comment:
A UnaryPredicate that applies to a Set_Mathematical. (sampleSpace SET) means that, for the purposes of probabilistic reasoning, SET is the relevant sample space in the current context. Intuitively, SET is the set of possible worlds (or completely specified outcomes -- see PossibleWorld_Specification) that are considered possible with respect to the current context.

Suppose, for example, that we want to reason about a single roll of a die. We would want to consider just six possible worlds, corresponding to the six possible outcomes. Thus our sample space might be (TheSet 1 2 3 4 5 6), with 1 representing the world in which 1 is rolled, etc.

See also mtSampleSpace.

Mx4rv3W2hJwpEbGdrcN5Y29ycA: Structure Prior To Structure In Structure
comment:
An instance of TernaryOrderingPredicate that identifies an ordering among two instances of ContextualizedInformationStructure in some larger structure. 
   (cisPriorToCISInStructure CIS-1 CIS-2 STRUCTURE)
means that CIS-1 occurs prior to CIS-2 within the context STRUCTURE, an instance of AbstractStructure. "occurs prior to" in this context means that CIS-1 comes before CIS-2 as understood by the conventions used in interpreting STRUCTURE. So if CIS-1 and CIS-2 are textual occurrences of English strings and STRUCTURE is a document formatted in the typical way that English documents are formatted, then any physical instantiation PRINTOUT of STRUCTURE will be such that an instantiation of the text for CIS-1 will appear to the left of or higher than an instantiation of the text for CIS-2 on PRINTOUT.
label: Cis Prior To CIS In Structure
cisPriorToCISInStructure
subPropertyOf: Structure Prior To Structure In Structure

comment: (nnRule NAME CONDITION_TEMPLATE MEANING_TEMPLATE) means that for a noun-noun pair of words (WORD1 and WORD2) if they have nominal denotations :NOUN1 and :NOUN2, and the CONDITION_TEMPLATE matches those denotations, then the MEANING_TEMPLATE, filled in with those meanings, is the meaning for the noun-noun pair.  The string, NAME, should be an example noun-noun compound that this form applies to.
label: Nn Rule
nnRule

comment: (typicallyLikesRelationshipToType AGENT_TYPE REL COLLECTION) means that a typical instance of AGENT_TYPE likes to be in the relationship REL with an instance of COLLECTION [likesRelationshipToType]. If the relationship is a Role and the Collection is a spec of Event, then likesRoleInEventType applies among the typical instance of AGENT_TYPE, Role, and Event type.
label: Typically Likes Relationship To Type
typicallyLikesRelationshipToType
Pred Highly Relevant For Justification Paraphrase
predHighlyRelevantForJustificationParaphrase
comment: (predHighlyRelevantForJustificationParaphrase PRED) means that when PRED is the arg0 in a support for a proof, a paraphrase of that proof explicitly mention that support, and that paraphrase should print the support in a manner that emphasizes it (e.g. by printing the support in bold or italic).

(preferredChoiceInWeaponType AGENTTYPE BASISTYPE WEAPONTYPE ACTIONTYPE) means that under ordinary circumstances, if an instance of AGENTTYPE is expectedto perform an instance of ACTIONTYPE, that agent will prefer having an instance of WEAPONTYPE based on BASISTYPE be the deviceUsed in the action to having an instance of WEAPONTYPE based on anything else be the deviceUsed in the action.
label: Preferred Choice In Weapon Type
preferredChoiceInWeaponType

A ternary SetOrCollectionPredicate that relates two Collections and a Set_Mathematical such that the first collection is the largest subcollection of the second that is a subsetOf the set. (subcollectionOfAndSubsetOf SUB COL SET) means that SUB is, by definition, the collection of all and only those instances of COL that are also elements of SET.

See also the corresponding function CollectionSubsetFn.

mostRecentHistoryPriorToDateWithStatus

comment: An assertion of the form (netMigrationRateDuring PLACE ORG-TYPE REAL DATE) states that measurements made of the situation during the Date DATE indicate that there there was a total change in the population of PLACE of REAL persons for every 1000 people. If this number is positive, then the immigration surpassed emigration. If this number is negative, then emigration surpassed immigration. For example, an assertion of the form (netMigrationRateDuring Syria HomoSapiens 3.4 (YearFn 2005)) states that records indicate that for every 1000 citizens of Syria, 3.4 people migrated to Syria during 2005. This represents a measurement and estimate.
label: Net Migration Rate During
netMigrationRateDuring

comment: This is a type level version of the predicate resemblesInValue. (typesResembleInValue TYPE1 TYPE2 COLL-TYPE) means that where INST1 and INST2 are any instances drawn, respectively, from TYPE1 and TYPE2, it will be the case that (resemblesInValue INST1 INST2 COLL-TYPE).
label: Types Resemble In Value
typesResembleInValue

comment:
A ternary predicate that relates a fixed-ary predicate to a typed-specialization of it to a list of collections, such that each of the more specialized predicate's argument-places is restricted (beyond the constraints it inherits from the more general predicate) to instances of the corresponding collection in the list.

More precisely, (typedGenlPredWithArgumentSignature SPECPRED GENLPRED ARG-SIGN-LIST) is true only if all of the following hold: 

  1. GENLPRED is a typedGenlPreds of SPECPRED.
  2. The lengthOfList of ARG-SIGN-LIST is equal to the arity of both GENLPRED and SPECPRED. 
  3. No member COLI of ARG-SIGN-LIST is disjointWith any collection CONSTRAINT such that (argIsa GENLPRED I CONSTRAINT) holds.
  4. For each member COLI of ARG-SIGN-LIST, (argIsa SPECPRED I COLI) holds.
For example, (typedGenlPredWithArgumentSignature birthDate objectStartingDate (TheList Animal Date)) holds. As this shows, a given COLI might be the same as, or a proper specialization of (see genls), an argIsa constraint on the Ith place of GENLPRED.

In practice, SPECPRED is defined using the corresponding function TypedSpecPredWithArgSignatureFn.

comment:
A ternary RuleMacroPredicate that is used to state that a given binary predicate holds between a given thing and all instances of a given collection. (relationInstanceAll BINPRED THING COL) means that THING bears the relation PRED to every instance INST of COL such that (BINPRED THING INST) holds. It is equivalent to (and can thus be used in effect as shorthand for) the more complex form:

(implies (isa ?INST COL) (BINPRED THING ?INST)) .

For example, `(relationInstanceAll geopoliticalSubdivision UnitedStatesOfAmerica State_UnitedStates)' means that each State in the Union is a subdivision of the United States. Cf. relationAllInstance, and see #$NoteAboutUseOfRuleMacroPredicates.

comment: A MetaRelation that is used to indicate that a given relation is "antisymmetric" with respect to two given argument-places. (antiSymmetricInArgs REL M N) means that REL is antisymmetric in its Mth and Nth arguments: these arguments are freely permutable _only_ if they are identical. This entails that, given any closed semantically well-formed formula built from (the CycL term for) REL, inter-substituting the formula's Mth and Nth arguments (while leaving the other arguments unchanged) will result in a change in the formula's semantic value (i.e. its truth-value or denotation) _unless_ the Mth and Nth arguments are identical. If REL is a binary predicate this is equivalent to its being an AntiSymmetricBinaryPredicate. More generally: (i) If REL is a Predicate that holds of given argument-sequence SEQ, then REL also holds of the sequence SEQ-PERMUTED obtained by permuting the Mth and Nth items in SEQ (while leaving the other items unchanged) only if these Mth and Nth items are identical (and thus SEQ and SEQ-PERMUTED are themselves identical sequences). (ii) If REL is a Function_Denotational whose value for a given argument-sequence SEQ is VALUE, then REL also has VALUE as its value for SEQ-PERMUTED (defined as above) only if SEQ-PERMUTED is identical with SEQ. For example, a (hypothetical) ternary predicate called "greaterThanOrEqualToOnScale", which took as arguments two physical objects (_not_ constrained to be distinct) and a scale for measuring some physical property, would be antisymmetric in its first and second arguments; i.e. (antiSymmetricInArgs greaterThanOrEqualToOnScale 1 2) would hold. For a function example, a (hypothetical) ternary function called "TransportToFromViaVehicleTypeFn" that took as arguments two locations (_not_ constrained to be distinct, in order to include round-trips) and a vehicle-type (and returned, say, the collection of all trips from the first location to the second location in vehicles of that type) would also be antisymmetric in its first and second arguments. Note that (each of) the argIsa constraint(s) on REL's Mth argument-place must not be disjoint with (any of) the argIsa constraint(s) on REL's Nth argument-place (see disjointWith), and likewise for the corresponding argGenl constraints (if any). For some discussion of why this is so, see the #$NoteOnArgumentCosatisfiabilityRequirement. See also asymmetricInArgs and commutativeInArgs.
label: Anti Symmetric In Args
antiSymmetricInArgs

comment: (sitTypeIsIteratedSubSitType_ForEach SITTYPE SUBSIT-TYPE BINPRED SUBSIT-TYPE-ROLE) means that each instance, SIT, of SITTYPE consists of one instance of SUBSIT-TYPE for each thing, THING, such that (BINPRED SIT THING). Moreover, each such thing plays the role SUBSIT-TYPE-ROLE in exactly one such instance of SUBSIT-TYPE.

comment:
(collectionIsaBackchainEncouraged COLLECTION)

means that rules that conclude

(isa <anything> COLLECTION)

are most likely going to have to be used in order to prove literals of the form

(isa <anything> COLLECTION).

This directs the inference engine to use such rules even if HL predicate transformation is disabled. Note that it will not necessarily use rules of the form

(isa <anything> <variable>)

where <variable> might bind to COLLECTION, and it will not necessarily use rules of the form

where (genls SPEC COLLECTION).

See also backchainEncouraged for the analogue of this predicate applicable to predicates rather than collections.

comment: (casualtyCountByAilment EVT WHAT AILMENT NUM) means that as a result of the event EVT, the number of WHAT who are suffering with the physical condition AILMENT is NUM. WHAT is a type of Organism_Whole, and AILMENT is a type of AilmentCondition. The subsets of AilmentCondition cover injuries as well as illnesses, allergies, and psychological disorders. Note that an organism that suffers from some instance of an ailment is the bodilyDoer of that ailment instance. Examples: casualtyCountByAilment may be used to state the number of persons who are afflicted by smoke inhalation in a particular fire, the number who contract food poisoning from a family picnic, or the number who suffer shell shock as a result of a particular battle.
label: Casualty Count By Ailment
casualtyCountByAilment

A TernaryPredicate that relates a specialization of Agent_Generic to a BinaryRolePredicate to a specialization of Event. (agentTypeTypicallyLikesRoleInEventType A-TYPE ROLE E-TYPE) means that instances of A-TYPE typically like playing ROLE in instances of E-TYPE.

For example, (agentTypeTypicallyLikesRoleInEventType Dog objectTakenCareOf WalkingAPet) means that instances of Dog typically like playing the role of objectTakenCareOf in instances of WalkingAPet -- that is, dogs like to be taken for walks.

comment: evidentialSupportForBelief AGENT INFO GEN-VAL-PRED) means that the evidence AGENT has bearing on the truth of INFO makes it reasonable to have degree represented by GEN-VAL-PRED of belief in INFO. Roughly, this is to say that there is some (possibly complex) proposition PROP such that (beliefs AGENT PROP) and (conditionalProbability INFO PROP NUMBER), where given the domain assumptions of the relevant Mt, NUMBER falls within the range determined by the GenericValuePredicate GEN-VAL-PRED. What this means is if there were a quantity type called "EvidentialSupport" and GEN-VAL-PRED was, say, mediumAmountOf, then AGENT would have a (MediumAmountFn "EvidentialSupport") for the Information INFO. (evidentialSupportForBelief AGENT INFO GEN-VAL-PRED) does not mean that AGENT in fact does have that degree of belief in INFO; that is, it does not entail (confidenceLevel AGENT INFO AMOUNT)) wher AMOUNT corresponds to the amount represented by GEN-VAL-PRED. arg3 is constrained to be an instance of GenericValuePredicate, rather than of Real0_1, in order to make use of this predicate feasible in practice (since we can often say of an agent that she has a low, medium or high amount of evidence for a given proposition, but can rarely or never say she has exactly N degree of evidence, for some particular instance N of Real0-1). This predicate's main use is in stating relations among propositional attitudes such as those expressed by beliefs, knows, goals and so on; there will probably be relatively few occasions to assert GAFs with evidentialSupportForBelief as arg zero.
label: Evidential Support For Belief
evidentialSupportForBelief

comment: (educationInFieldSufficientForActType EDU-LEVEL FIELD ACT-TYPE) holds just in case someone with an education level of EDU-LEVEL who is competent in FIELD would be capable of learning to (capableOfLearningTo) perform acts of ACT-TYPE. This predicate states that anyone with the EDU-LEVEL and competence FIELD, as a default, would likely have the knowledge to perform acts of ACT-TYPE or could easily obtain that knowledge. This entails that the basic procedures for performing acts of ACT-TYPE are known to that person or could easily be grasped with a minimal to moderate amount of study. This predicate captures a sufficient condition on the educational requirements for performing act types, it doesn't state anything about further skills or materials that may be necessary to perform act of type ACT-TYPE. So, this does not entail that anyone with that education level and competence in the field would be able in some stronger sense to perform acts of that type.

educationInFieldSufficientForActType

comment: This is a macro-predicate which can be used to represent the meaning of English sentences such as `two or three cats live in my house' in NL parsing. (numRange_GenQuant COL1 COL2 N M) means that there are between N and M elements of COL1 which are also elements of COL2. N and M must be different integers, and M is greater than N. This constant doesn't replace num-GenQuant or any other more specific GeneralizedQuantifier. Its primary use is as an intermediate target for parsing: not for general KE/OE.
label: Num Range Gen Quant
numRange-GenQuant

comment:
A quaternary NLSemanticPredicate that relates natural language words to CycL terms to which they correspond in a certain way. Some words have multiple such denotations due to the fact that they possess multiple WordSenses (q.v.), which word-senses might or might not belong to the same parts of speech (i.e. nouns, verbs, adjectives etc.); thus denotation also has argument-places for specifying both a SpeechPart (q.v.) and a particular word-sense (as represented by an integer understood in relation to some standardized word-sense numbering scheme).

(denotation WORD SPEECH-PART N TERM) means that the CycL correlate (or "denotation") of WORD, with respect to SPEECH-PART and the corresponding word-sense numbered N, is TERM. Examples: (1) #$Place-TheWord, an instance of EnglishWord, has the denotation PuttingSomethingSomewhere when used as a Verb with its word-sense 0, and the denotation Place when used as a CountNoun with that same word-sense; (2) #$Ring-TheWord currently has four denotation assertions in the Knowledge Base: EmittingSound (as a Verb with its word-sense 1); AudibleSound (as a CountNoun with its word-sense 1); RingShapedObject (as a CountNoun with its word-sense 0); and Ring_Jewelry (as a CountNoun with its word-sense 2). An example of a denotation sentence that has a NAT (see CycLNonAtomicTerm) rather than a constant in its fourth argument-position is

`(denotation #$Density-TheWord Adjective 0 (IntervalMinFn LowAmountFn Density))'.

Note that denotation is _not_ to be confused with denotes (q.v.), which relates denoting CycL terms to things "out there in the world" (i.e. in the intended model of the CycL language).
label: denotation

comment: (vulnerableInType SITUATION-TYPE OBJECT RESULT-TYPE) means that when in situations of type SITUATION-TYPE, existing object OBJECT is vulnerable to hardships of type RESULT-TYPE. The purpose of vulnerableInType is to represent knowledge that an object is vulnerable in an entire class of situations. For restrictions on RESULT-TYPE please see the comment on vulnerableIn. Note that this is a type-level predicate in the first argument place and that care needs to be taken in developing rules that draw vulnerableIn conclusions from vulnerableInType GAFs so that we do not overpopulate the KB with potentially questionable vulnerableIn judgments.
label: Vulnerable In Type
vulnerableInType

For example, (tacticalTerrainFromPositionForUnitType Hill ObservationFacilitatingTerrain on_Physical InfantryUnit_MilitarySpecialty) says that instances of Hill facilitate observation for instances of InfantryUnit_MilitarySpecialty when they are on them. Also see tacticalTerrainFromPositionForUnitType and tacticalTerrainTypeFromPosition.
Mx4rwLSVCpwpEbGdrcN5Y29ycA: tactical terrain types from a position for a type of unit
label: tactical terrain type from a position for a type of unit
tacticalTerrainTypeFromPositionForUnitType

comment: (totalRoledTypeByAffectedTypeInType NUM AGENT ROLE TYPE-PLAYING-ROLE TYPE) means that NUM is the total number of things of TYPE-PLAYING-ROLE that played ROLE in situations of TYPE which AGENT performs. comment: This predicate can be used to describe propositional attitudes in terms of an agent attributing a certain type of evaluative attitude (q.v.) to a proposition. (evaluates_Propositional AGENT SENT EVAL-PRED) means that AGENT attributes to some action, ACT, described by SENT the attitude that would be expressed by (EVAL-PRED AGENT ACT). Thus it represents a certain propositional attitude on the part of AGENT toward that action. Such attitudes correspond in some case to stances that are largely based on emotion, and in other cases to reasoned evaluative judgments. Entities capable of taking evaluative stances are entities capable of manifesting interests in purposeful action, hence the restriction of the first argument to Agent_Generic.
label: Evaluates-Propositional
evaluates-Propositional

comment: A ternary ArgGenlPredicate (q.v.) used to place a specified genls based argument-type constraint on a given VariableArityRelation (q.v.) with respect to any of its argument-places whose ordinal position is greater than or equal to a specified number. (argAndRestGenl RELN N COL) means that, as a necessary condition for semantic well-formedness, anything given as the Nth or greater argument to RELN must be an specialization of COL. Thus a closed formula (RELN ARG1..ARG(N)..ARG(N+1)..) is well-formed only if each of ARG(N)..ARG(N+1).. is an instance of COL. See also argsGenl and argAndRestIsa.
label: Arg And Rest Genl
argAndRestGenl

comment: (translationOfAISFromTo AIS1 CC1 AIS2 CC2) means that the meaning attributed the AbstractInformationStructure AIS1, by CommunicationConvention CC1, is the same as the meaning attributed to AIS2 by CC2. Thus, if TEXT1 = 'Schnee ist weiss' and TEXT2 = 'Snow is white' then it would be true that (translationOfAISFromTo TEXT1 GermanLanguage TEXT2 EnglishLanguage).
label: Translation Of AIS From To
translationOfAISFromTo

comment: (weatherForecastForRegion FORECAST REGION TIME) means that the WeatherForecast_PCW FORECAST contains propositional information about the predicted weather for GeographicalRegion REGION for the given time period TIME.

comment: This predicate is used for specifying locations, of various types, where particular agents can be contacted. (pointOfContact AGENT LOCTYPE LOC) means that AGENT has as its LOCTYPE (a ContactLocationType, such as Workplace, HumanResidence, or BillingLocation) the particular ContactLocation (q.v.) LOC. Thus, AGENT can be contacted at LOC. Typically, LOC will correspond to a specific street address, as opposed to being a more generic location like CityOfAustinTX.

pointOfContact

comment: (backupOfFor DEVICE BACKUP CLIENT) means that when DEVICE is unble to provide the service to CLIENT that it ordinarily provides, it is expected that BACKUP witl be able to provide that service.

comment: The predicate amountOfSalesByToDuring is used to indicate how much of a certain product was sold by a particular seller to a particular buyer. (amountOfSalesByToDuring SELLER BUYER TIMEPD PRODTYPE REVENUE) means that, during the TimeInterval TIMEPD, SELLER (an Agent_PartiallyTangible) sold to BUYER (another Agent_PartiallyTangible) some amount of the ProductType PRODTYPE, worth the total amount of MonetaryValue REVENUE. For example, to say that a restaurant, Threadgills, sold $3000 worth of their pumpkin pies to a local grocery store in November, we would say: (amountOfSalesByToDuring Threadgills HEBAt2222 (MonthFn November (YearFn 1996)) PumpkinPie (Dollar_UnitedStates 3000)).
label: Amount Of Sales By To During
amountOfSalesByToDuring

comment: An instance of TernaryPredicate, used to relate a specialization of BiologicalLivingObject to the recommended allowance of some type of sustenance, for instances of that specialization. (recommendedAllowanceForBLOType BLO-TYPE TYPE AMOUNT) says that, as a default, it is recommended that any instance of BLO-TYPE ingest AMOUNT of TYPE. For example, (recommendedAllowanceForBLOType HumanAdult (LiquidFn Water) ((PerFn Cup_UnitOfVolume DaysDuration) 8 10)) says that it is recommended that adult humans consume 8 to 10 cups of water per day. Who or what is doing the recommendation is unspecified with this predicate; accordingly, assertions should go in a Microtheory (for example, the PITOfIBTFn for some conceptual work on nutrition) that makes the source clear. See also recommendedAllowanceForBLO, which relates individual BLOs to their recommended consumption allowances.
label: Recommended Allowance For BLO Type
recommendedAllowanceForBLOType

comment: (titleOfWorkForStyleAndRendering WORK STYLE RENDERING STRING) means that STRING is the canonical string used to express the title of WORK according to STYLE-SPECIFICATION, for rendering using MARKUP-LANGUAGE.
label: Title Of Work For Style And Rendering
titleOfWorkForStyleAndRendering

comment: (crossPriceElasticityOfDemand MARKET PRODUCT-1 OLD-PRICE NEW-PRICE PRODUCT-2 ELASTICITY) identifies ELASTICITY as the real numeric value of the degree to which demand in MARKET for PRODUCT-2 shifts in response to a change in price of PRODUCT-1 from OLD-PRICE to NEW-PRICE in MARKET.
