crossPriceElasticityOfDemand

comment: (ambientAtmosphericConcentration PLACE STUFF CONCENTRATION) holds just in case the concentation of the substance type STUFF is CONCENTRATION in the ambient atmospere in PLACE. For instance, (ambientAtmosphericConcentration MyOffice Cyanide ((PerFn Gram CubicCentimeter) .003)) holds just in case the ambient atmospheric concentration of Cyanide in MyOffice is .003 grams per cubit centimeter.
label: Ambient Atmospheric Concentration
ambientAtmosphericConcentration

comment: (dilutedEPSForPeriod ORG MONEY TIME) means MONEY is the amount earned (i.e. profit) by ORG during TIME per share of stock. This is calculated using the diluted number of shares in ORG, which may be higher than the actual number of shares outstanding. The diluted number of shares includes the number of shares that are 'spoken for', through means such as options or warrants to buy stock.
label: Diluted EPS For Period
dilutedEPSForPeriod

comment: (prefersToMinimize AGENT THING SLOT) means that AGENT prefers (see also prefers) smaller values of SLOT (its second argument) when applied to THING (as the first argument of SLOT). In a sense it means that AGENT will prefer situations whereby SLOT of THING becomes smaller, or stays the same, over situations whereby SLOT of THING becomes greater. It need not imply that the agent will directly pursue such minimization (in order to imply direct pursuit, see goals)
label: Prefers To Minimize
prefersToMinimize

comment: (majorTradingCenterByMarketCapitalization EXCHANGE MARKET INTERVAL) means that stock exchange EXCHANGE is the major trading center for the stock market MARKET during the entire duration of INTERVAL.
label: Major Trading Center By Market Capitalization
majorTradingCenterByMarketCapitalization

comment: This is the corresponding predicate of the function CollectionArgModeFn.
label: Mode For I Oand Collection
modeForIOandCollection

comment: nthDayTypeOfMonth is used to say that a CalendarDay occurs annually on a specified nth DayOfWeekType during a certain month. For example, if the CalendarDay always falls on the third Friday in June, one would use (nthDayTypeOfMonth CalendarDay Friday 3). The month June needs to be specified in a separate assertion. Notice that if the day is not a CalendarDay, but an Event or Holiday, the predicate eventTypeFallsOnNthDayTypeInMonth needs to be used instead.
label: Nth Day Type Of Month
nthDayTypeOfMonth

comment: (favorableExchangeRateDuring UM1 UM2 THING) means that in some market or markets the UnitOfMoney UM1 has a favorable exchange rate with UnitOfMoney UM2 during the temporal extent of TemporalThing THING. Note that THING will often be a calendar time period.
label: Favorable Exchange Rate During
favorableExchangeRateDuring

comment: (providesResourceTo GIVER RESOURCE RECEIVER) means that RESOURCE is useful to RECEIVER in some action, and GIVER provides that RESOURCE to that RECEIVER. Positive examples include: rain providing mosquitoes with puddles, a parent providing a child with an allowance, a massage therapist providing a client with a masssage, and a scientist providing people with an explanation of phenomena.
label: Provides Resource To
providesResourceTo

comment: An assertion of the form (fileFromStringOnEngine FILE STRING ENGINE) means that the ComputerFile_Abstract FILE represents a result that was generated during an internet search that used the SubLString STRING as its search string with the SearchEngine ENGINE.
label: File From String On Engine
fileFromStringOnEngine

comment: An assertion of the form (unreservedWorkTimeAvailableFromForDuring QUANT IND AGENT INTERVAL) is used to express the amount of work time (the Time_Quantity QUANT) of the IntelligentAgent IND that the Agent_Generic AGENT can, by default, make further reservations on during the TimeInterval INTERVAL. QUANT is determined by subtracting from the Time_Quantity represented relative to an instance of RootAllotment for IND.
label: Unreserved Work Time Available From For During
unreservedWorkTimeAvailableFromForDuring

comment: An expression of the form (incompatibleArgIsas PRED1 ARG1 PRED2 ARG2) means that the collection that is the argIsa value for the Predicate PRED1's ARG1th argument is disjoint with the collection that is the argIsa value for the Predicate PRED2's ARG2th value.
label: Incompatible Arg Isas
incompatibleArgIsas

comment: '(averageDurationForSubSituationType_Mean SIT-TYPE SUB-SIT-TYPE DURATION)' means that SUB-SIT-TYPE is a subsituation type of SIT-TYPE, and that the mean average duration of subsituations of an instance of SIT-TYPE which are instances of SUB-SIT-TYPE is DURATION.
label: Average Duration For Sub Situation Type Mean
averageDurationForSubSituationType-Mean

comment: (closingTagForStructure STRUC TAG) means that STRUC, an instance of either GraphicalStructure or TextString generated from SOURCE, an HTMLSource, has, in SOURCE, a closing tag of TAG, a tag that is the result of CloseTagFn.
label: Closing Tag For Structure
closingTagForStructure

comment: The ReifiedMapping ARG4 will be used to interpret the PhysicalField ARG3 when the PhysicalField ARG1 has the value ARG2.
label: Dependent Mapping
dependentMapping

comment: (equivPredsWRTTypes BINPRED1 BINPRED2 COL1 COL2) means that if either BINPRED1 or BINPRED2 apply to (INS1 INS2) where INS1 is an instance of COL1 and INS2 is an instance of COL2, then the other one does also. This is a combination of (genlPredsWRTTypes BINPRED1 BINPRED2 COL1 COL2) and (genlPredsWRTTypes BINPRED2 BINPRED1 COL1 COL2).
label: Equiv Preds WRT Types
equivPredsWRTTypes

comment: (totalRoledTypeByAffectedTypeInType NUM AFFECT-TYPE ROLE TYPE-PLAYING-ROLE TYPE) means that NUM is the total number of things of TYPE-PLAYING-ROLE that played ROLE in situations of TYPE in which some instance of AFFECT-TYPE plays some role or other. For instance, (totalRoledTypeByAffectedTypeInType 180 BankBuilding organismKilled Person TerroristAttack) means that, as far as we know in the KB, a total of 180 persons were killed in terrorist attacks where a bank was somehow involved.
label: Total Roled Type By Affected Type In Type
totalRoledTypeByAffectedTypeInType

comment: (secondVADInsertForOperationWithDeviceAndPatientAtDate OP INSERT DEVICE PATIENT DATE) means that INSERT is the second cardiac device insertion perfomed on PATIENT at DATE during the same hospitalization as the operation OP (which is also performed on PATIENT).
label: Second VAD Insert For Operation With Device And Patient At Date
secondVADInsertForOperationWithDeviceAndPatientAtDate

comment: (oughtToBe_SitRelationToSitType SIT PRED OBLIGATORY-TYPE) means that there should be an instance OBLIGATORY-INS of OBLIGATORY-TYPE such that (PRED SIT OBLIGATORY-INS). Assertions involving this predicate -- which specify what should be the case -- should be made in a normative context, e.g., one that reflects the contents of a particular CodeOfConduct. Usually, SIT will be subject to such a requirement in virtue of satisfying some general description, e.g., one stated in the antecedent of a CycLRuleAssertion.
label: Ought To Be Sit Relation To Sit Type
oughtToBe-SitRelationToSitType
subPropertyOf: Ought To Be Sit Relation To Type
Permitted Sit Relation To Sit Type

label: User Behavior WRT Salient Descriptor For Term
userBehaviorWRTSalientDescriptorForTerm

comment:
An instance of TaxonomicPredicateForPredicates that is a specialization of genlPredsWRTQuotedArgs, bearing a relationship to that predicate that is analogous to the relationship between typedGenlPreds and genlPreds. typedGenlPredsWRTQuotedArgs is used to express a typedGenlPreds -like relationship between a predicate SPEC-PRED that has at least one quoted argument place (see quotedArgument) and a predicate GENL-PRED of the same arity that

1) has argIsa/argGenl constraints that are at least as general as those of SPEC-PRED,

2) is not quoted in at least one of the argument places in which SPEC-PRED is, and

3) is only quoted in argument places in which SPEC-PRED is also quoted.

As such, GENL-PRED need not have any quoted argument places.

In (typedGenlPredsWRTQuotedArgs SPEC-PRED GENL-PRED SET), SET is the set of integers that correspond to quoted argument places in SPEC-PRED that are not quoted in GENL-PRED, thereby indicating a recipe for deriving a sentence SPEC-SENT whose arg0 is SPEC-PRED from a sentence GENL-SENT whose arg0 is GENL-PRED: First, each argument ARG in GENL-SENT occuring in the Nth argument place, where N is neither 0 nor a member of LIST, will occur in the Nth argument place in SPEC-SENT if and only if ARG meets the Nth argument constraints of SPEC-PRED. All other non-0 arguments OTHER-ARGS in GENL-SENT, which by definition occur in the Mth argument place, where M is an element of SET, will appear as explicitly quoted arguments in SPEC-SENT, in those same argument places, just in case OTHER-ARGS meets the quoted argument constraints of the Mth argument place in SPEC-PRED. For example, 

   (typedGenlPredsWRTQuotedArgs cycLActors situationConstituents (TheSet 2))
entails that whenever 
   (situationConstituents WritingACommentForHashDollarDog
       (Quote Dog))
holds, 
   (cycLActors WritingACommentForHashDollarDog Dog)
follows.
label: Typed Genl Preds WRT Quoted Args
typedGenlPredsWRTQuotedArgs

comment: A predicate to characterize the default frontage size of military units, classified by echelon, relative to a given task. The frontage dimension is used for the tactical analysis of terrain in military planning contexts. (defaultFrontageSizeByEchelonForTask ECHELON SIZE TASK) is true if and only if the default frontage space for an arbitrary instance of ECHELON assigned to a task of type TASK is SIZE (usually expressed in meters).
label: Default Frontage Size By Echelon For Task
defaultFrontageSizeByEchelonForTask

comment: (relationAllExistsUnique PRED COL1 COL2) means that, for each instance INS1 of COL1, there is exactly one instance INS2 of COL2 such that (PRED INS1 INS2) holds. Thus it is equivalent to (relationAllExistsCount PRED COL1 COL2 1).
label: Relation All Exists Unique
relationAllExistsUnique

comment: (wantsToRelnA AGT COL RELN) means that the Agent_PartiallyTangible ?AGT wants to be in the relation RELN (expressed by a BinaryPredicate) to some element of the collection COL. The desired object may be indefinite (except for being a member of COL). E.g., (wantsToRelnA Muffet TennisBall possesses).
label: Wants To Reln A
wantsToRelnA
Functionality Compromised
functionalityCompromised
comment: (functionalityCompromised SIT-TYPE) means that the ability for things to act in a situation of SIT-TYPE is provably compromised. If some type TYPE of object is such that its instances are defeasibly capable of playing some role in instances of SIT-TYPE, that functionality is compromised if some instance of TYPE is provably incapable of playing that role in SIT-TYPE.

(isaBoth TERM COL-1 COL-2) states that TERM is an element of both of the collections COL-1 and COL-2. This predicate is notAssertible, since it must always be recomputed from the current state of the genls heirarchy. For comparison, see also nearestCommonIsa and nearestCommonSpecs.
label: Isa Both
isaBoth

comment: (personTakingTourMightDislikeObject TOUR PERSON OBJ) means that if PERSON were to take TOUR, there is a better-than-even chance they would dislike OBJECT, featured on TOUR.
label: Person Taking Tour Might Dislike Object
personTakingTourMightDislikeObject

comment:
A quaternary RuleMacroPredicate that can be used to state that a given binary predicate stands in a certain numerical relationship with respect to a given collection and a given thing. (relationExistsRangeInstance BINPRED COL THING RANGE) means that there are between the minimum and maximum of RANGE (see NonNegativeIntegerRange) many instances INST(i) of COL such that (BINPRED INST(i) THING) holds. Thus it is equivalent to the more complex form: 

  (thereExistRange RANGE ?INST
     (and
        (isa ?INST COL)
        (PRED ?INST THING))) .

For example, (relationExistsRangeInstance objectFoundInLocation Star MilkyWay_Galaxy Billions_Quant) means there are billions of stars in the Milky Way. Cf. relationExistsRangeAll, and see the shared #$NoteAboutUseOfRuleMacroPredicates.
label: Relation Exists Range Instance
relationExistsRangeInstance

comment: An assertion of the form (budgetRevenuesDuring GEO DATE AMOUNT) states that the GeopoliticalEntity GEO took in the MonetaryValue AMOUNT during the Date DATE. For example, an assertion of the form (budgetRevenuesDuring Syria (YearFn 2003) (Dollar-UnitedStates 10000000000)) states that Syria took in $10 billion during 2003.
label: Budget Revenues During
budgetRevenuesDuring

comment: If A, B, and C are Points, AB is the straight line segment between A and B, and BC is the straight line segment between B and C, then (angleBetweenPoints A B C ANGLE) means that ANGLE is the non-reflex angle (see ReflexAngularDistance) between AB and BC, measured in the Plane in which A, B and C all lie.
label: Angle Between Points
angleBetweenPoints

comment: A predicate used to state the number of shares being offered for purchase at the bid market price of a company's Stock (of a given class, e.g. common or preferred) at a given time. (stockSize_Bid STOCK NUM DATE EXCHANGE) means that there are NUM shares of STOCK being offered for purchase at the latter's current stockPrice_Bid (q.v.) at DATE on the exchange EXCHANGE. Cf. stockSize_Ask.
label: bid size
stockSize-Bid

comment: (numberOfInstancesOfCollRelatedToInstancesOfType TYPE INSTANCE TYPE2 NUM BIN-PRED) holds of every NUM such that NUM is the number of instances of TYPE2 in which (BIN-PRED INSTANCE INSTANCE-OF-TYPE2) holds where INSTANCE is an instance of TYPE.
label: Number Of Instances Of Coll Related To Instances Of Type Inverse
numberOfInstancesOfCollRelatedToInstancesOfType-Inverse
Rendering Properties For Node Type In System
renderingPropertiesForNodeTypeInSystem

comment: Instances of ARG2 have products-or-inputs which are instances of ARG3.  ARG1 is the ObjectSpecification for ARG3 - i.e. the mt which contains the specification info.
label: Object Specification For
objectSpecificationFor

comment: (repValue ?PT ?KEYOBJ ?LF ?VAL) means that ?VAL is the meaning of the contents of the field ?LF in the physical table ?PT, in the tuple identified by ?KEYOBJ. repValue is similar to cellValue, but cellValue states actual cell contents, while the fourth argument of repValue has been translated into the meaning of the contents.
label: Rep Value
repValue

comment: In many organizations, it is important to be able to record the fact that a pair of positions (see #$OrganizationalPosition), are not expected to be held concurrently by the same individual. nonConcurrentPositions_OrganizationalPosition allows us to do this with respect to a specified temporal 'granularity'. Specifically, (nonConcurrentPositions_OrganizationalPosition ORG POS1 POS2 DURATION) means that we would not expect to find the same individual holding POS1 and POS2 in ORG within the space of a time-frame demarcated by DURATION. More specifically, (nonConcurrentPositions_OrganizationalPosition ORG POS1 POS2 DURATION) means that if it is the case that (holdsIn TEMP1 (POS1 ORG AGENT)) and (holdsIn TEMP2 (POS2 ORG AGENT)), the expectation is that the duration of (TimeIntervalBetweenFn TEMP1 TEMP2) is greaterThan DURATION.
label: Non Concurrent Positions Organizational Position
nonConcurrentPositions-OrganizationalPosition

comment: (softwareAgentSupportsServiceIterations AGT TYPE N) says that the #$SoftwareAgent AGT can, at most, support N ProgramActions of type TYPE simultaneously.
label: Software Agent Supports Service Iterations
softwareAgentSupportsServiceIterations
Use Reformulation Rule For Canonicalization
useReformulationRuleForCanonicalization
comment: (useReformulationRuleForCanonicalization RULE), asserted in the microtheory MT, tells the CycCanonicalizer to consider RULE at canonicalization time, and use it to help canonicalize CycLExpressions in MT or a specMt thereof.

(actionResourceQuantForTime ACT THING QUANT TEMP) means that in ACT, a quantity QUANT of THING is a required resource for the duration of TEMP, in the sense that the agent performing ACT must have 'access' to a QUANT amount of THING for TEMP in order for ACT to be successfulForAgents.
label: Action Resource Quant For Time
actionResourceQuantForTime

comment: (typePromotesRisk SIT-TYPE1 ROLE1 SIT-TYPE2 ROLE2) means that if an object OBJ plays ROLE1 in an instance of SIT-TYPE1, then OBJ is at risk for playing the role ROLE2 in an instance of SIT-TYPE2. For instance, '(typePromotesRisk Smoking doneBy (CancerFn Lung) bodilyDoer)' means that smoking promotes the risk of getting lung cancer. See also typeImmediateRisk and promotesRisk.
label: Type Promotes Risk
typePromotesRisk

comment: (typesNeedToBeSimilarInScalar COL1 COL2 ATTR-TYPE) means that instances of COL1 need the same degree of an instance of ATTR-TYPE as instances of COL2. Typically, assertions using this predicate will be made in a context in which there is a presupposed goal. COL1 needs to have the same degree of ATTR-TYPE as COL2 in order to help achieve some goal or purpose.
label: Types Need To Be Similar In Scalar
typesNeedToBeSimilarInScalar

comment: An instance of SlotCalculationFormulaPredicate, used to state (slotCalculationFormula_Addition SLOT-SUM SLOT-1 SLOT-2 . SLOT-N) means that for any valid argument ARG such that (SLOT-SUM ARG VALUE), VALUE is the result of adding the arg2 values of SLOT-1 through SLOT-N for ARG.
label: Slot Calculation Formula Addition
slotCalculationFormula-Addition

comment: The corresponding predicate to the logical schema denoting function LogicalSchemaForKSWithNameFn
label: Logical Schema With Name For KS
logicalSchemaWithNameForKS

comment: (defaultValueForPredInArg PRED NUM THING) means that when generating queries using PRED you should generate them with THING in arg-NUM.
label: Default Value For Pred In Arg
defaultValueForPredInArg

comment: (delayUntilTime OP TEMP UNIT) means that in the instance of MilitaryOperation, OP, UNIT has been tasked with delaying enemy movement until the time interval started by TEMP.
label: delaying for time period
delayUntilTime

comment: (logicalFieldCorrespondingToPhysicalFieldNameUsesQueryInPosition KS FIELD-NAME QUERY ARG-POS-1-STRING ARG-POS-2-STRING) means that there is a logical field indexical corresponding to FIELD-NAME in KS and its value is determined by running the base query for KS and plugging the result into ARG-POS-1 in QUERY. The resulting answer for ARG-POS-2 is the value of the logical field indexical. The ARG-POS-N-STRINGs are automatically converted into FormulaArgPositionFn terms when populating bindingInPositionFromUsedInPositionInFor.
label: Logical Field Corresponding To Physical Field Name Uses Query In Position
logicalFieldCorrespondingToPhysicalFieldNameUsesQueryInPosition

comment: (sourceOfFor_TypeLevel ?SOURCE-TYPE ?OF ?FOR) means that ?SOURCE-TYPE is a source of ?OF for ?FOR, e.g. plants are a source of food for many mammals or electricity is a source of energy for computers.
label: Source Of For Type Level
sourceOfFor-TypeLevel

comment: (instanceDiffersFromPrototypicalInstance_Lacuna INST TYPE SCRIPT LACUNA) means that when INST is compared with a prototypical instance of TYPE generated by propagating the assertions in SCRIPT to deductive closure, the assertio LACUNAE is found referencing the prototypical instance, and no comparable assertion (an assertion formed by substituting occurrence of INST for occurrences of the prototype) is found for INST.
label: Instance Differs From Prototypical Instance Lacuna
instanceDiffersFromPrototypicalInstance-Lacuna

comment: (transferValue NEW-PENSION OLD-PENSION VALUE) means that VALUE is the amount of money that must be transferred to NEW-PENSION for the person holding NEW-PENSION to get the same benefits built up under OLD-PENSION.
label: transfer value
transferValue

comment: A sentence of the form (numberOfCNCTestsMeetingCompoundThreshold RULE ?RESULTS COUNT THRESHOLD) means that for an implicit #$CandidateNounCompondSearh for RULE with RESULTS, there were COUNT compound strings that met the minimum hit count of THRESHOLD.
label: Number Of CNC Tests Meeting Compound Threshold
numberOfCNCTestsMeetingCompoundThreshold

comment: (numberOfInstancesOfCollRelatedToSpecsOfType TYPE INSTANCE TYPE2 NUM BIN-PRED) holds of every NUM such that NUM is the number of instances of TYPE2 that have BIN-PRED to INSTANCE where INSTANCE is a specialization of TYPE. For example, if BIN-PRED is intendedAttackTargets and TYPE is GovernmentalBuilding, the running the query with a specified subcollection of Event fro TYPE2 will return pairs consisting of a specialization of GovernmentalBuilding and the number of instances of the event type that targeted that type of building. Note that although arg3 takes any sort of collection, It is mostly designed for use with collections of events
label: Number Of Instances Of Coll Related To Specs Of Type
numberOfInstancesOfCollRelatedToSpecsOfType

comment: An instance of InterArgFormatPredicate (q.v.). (interArgFormat1_2 PRED COL FORMAT) means that FORMAT is a Format (q.v.) requirement for the second argument-place of PRED when PRED's first argument is an instance of COL. That is, with respect to a sentence of the form (PRED ARG1 ARG2 ... ARGN) in which ARG1 is an instance of COL, PRED's arg2 position (i.e. the position occupied by the metavariable `ARG2' in the preceding sentence-form) is subject to FORMAT. See Format and its instances for further explanation.
label: Inter Arg Format 1 2
interArgFormat1-2

comment: (occurrencesPerPeriod SUB-TYPE SUPER-TYPE N) means that N instances of TemporalObjectType SUB-TYPE occur during each instance of TemporalObjectType SUPER-TYPE. For example, (occurrencesPerPeriod CalendarDay CalendarWeek 7) means that there are seven calendar days in each calendar week.
label: Occurrences Per Period
occurrencesPerPeriod

comment: (ingestingToxicityFor STUFF ORGTYPE TOXLEVEL) means that under ordinary circumstances, stuff has the Toxicity TOXLEVEL for instances of ORGTYPE that ingest it.
label: ingesting toxicity for a type of organism
ingestingToxicityFor

comment: (candidateForRelationExtractionBasis STRUCTURE COLLECTION WORD) means that the instance STRUCTURE of AbstractStructure is a candidate for the reification of a new relation due to its relationship to the collection COLLECTION and the word WORD. In particular, COLLECTION is a concept that has been extracted from (see conceptExtractedViaReferenceInStructure) a structure PRIOR such that a larger structure WHOLE spans PRIOR and STRUCTURE in the right way (e.g., in the way that "president of" spans "president" and "of") and where WORD (e.g., #$Of-TheWord) is related to STRUCTURE by virtue of sharing a common string.
label: Candidate For Relation Extraction Basis
candidateForRelationExtractionBasis

comment: An assertion of the form (literalHasCDTInArg LIT TERM N) states that the CycLClosedDenotationalTerm TERM is the value of the Nth argument in the (CycLObjectTypeFn CycLAtomicSentence) LIT.
label: Literal Has CDT In Arg
literalHasCDTInArg

comment: (grossDomesticProduct_Nominal GE THING MONEY) means that the instance of MonetaryValue MONEY is a measure of the value of the GeopoliticalEntity GE's total domestic production of goods and services (its gross domestic product) during the temporal extent of the TemporalThing THING, and that the value of the currency (UnitOfMoney) in terms of which MONEY is specified is that which prevailed during the temporal extent of THING. A country would be a typical instance of GE. THING will often be a time period -- for example, a calendar year such as (YearFn 1997) or a calendar quarter such as (QuarterFn 4 (YearFn 1997)); but it may also be, for instance, a particular Event. For example, (grossDomesticProduct_Nominal COUNTRY (YearFn 1997) (Dollar_UnitedStates NR)) means that COUNTRY's gross domestic product for 1997 was $NR in 1997 US dollars. See also grossDomesticProduct.
label: nominal gross domestic product
grossDomesticProduct-Nominal

comment: (salientDifferenceBetween COL1 COL2 COL3 BINPRED) means that while COL1 and COL2 contain instances that are similar in many salient respects, they differ in the fact that for every instance, INS1, of COL1 there is an instance of COL3, INS3 such that (BINPRED INS1 INS3). On the other hand, instances of COL2 do not bear the relation BINPRED to any instance of COL3. The differences noted with this predicate should be salient ones, e.g., differences that one familiar with COL1 and COL2 might note if asked to compare and contrast COL1 and COL2. See salientDifferenceBetweenSiblings and salientDifferenceBetween_Inverse for closely related predicates.
label: Salient Difference Between
salientDifferenceBetween

comment: (bridgingPredicateForPredicate PRED-BASE PRED-BRIDGE (TheSet ARG1, ... , ARGN)) means that PRED-BRIDGE is the consequent of a transformation rule that, essentially, transforms into PRED-BASE in order to generate bindings. The third argument will be a set of lists that determine the correspondence between the argument positions in PRED-BASE and PRED-BRIDGE. The first item in the list corresponds to the argument position of PRED-BASE and the second item in the list corresponds to the argument position of the PRED-BRIDGE. For example, (bridgingPredicateForPredicate rdf_type isa (TheSet (TheList 1 1) (TheList 2 2))) means that, in certain contexts isa literals are solved by transforming into rdf_type and the arg1 of rdf_type corresponds to arg1 is isa and arg2 of rdf_type corresponds to arg2 of isa.
label: Bridging Predicate For Predicate
bridgingPredicateForPredicate

comment: With respect to Agent ARG1, the value of F(ARG2) can optionally assume the values v1, v2...
label: Options Available
optionsAvailable

comment:
An ExistentialQuantifier (q.v.) and a specialization of both thereExistAtLeast and thereExistAtMost (qq.v.). Compared to the standard existential quantifier thereExists, thereExistExactly has an extra argument-place for specifying exactly how many things satisfy a given condition (specified by an CycLSentence_Assertible, in which the also-specified CycLVariable will typically occur free). A closed sentence of the form (thereExistExactly NUM VAR SENT) means that there are exactly NUM distinct things that satisfy SENT, i.e. that render SENT true when taken as the value of VAR. For example, the sentence 

  (thereExistExactly 7 ?X (isa ?X Sea))

means that there are exactly seven seas.

In the degenerate case where VAR does not appear free in SENT, then (thereExistExactly NUM VAR SENT) is equivalent to SENT.
label: There Exist Exactly
thereExistExactly

comment: (averageDailyLowTemperature REGION TEMP TYPE) means that during instances of TYPE, the average daily low temperature in the GeographicalRegion REGION is TEMP. Note that TYPE will often be a type of calendar time period, such as a subset of CalendarMonth.
label: Average Daily Low Temperature
averageDailyLowTemperature

comment: (timeSheetPeriod PERIOD DATE NUMBER) means that PERIOD, an instance of TimeInterval, is denoted by the NUMBER timesheet period for DATE. (timeSheetPeriod TimeSheetPeriod51 (MonthFn December (YearFn 2005)) 1) means that TimeSheetPeriod51 is the first time sheet period in December 2005.
label: time sheet period
timeSheetPeriod

comment: The predicate compoundString expresses the relationship between a multi-word string, a part of speech, and its denotation. (compoundString WORD LIST PART TERM) means that the translation of the multi-word phrase containing both WORD and the word-strings in LIST, when the part of speech is PART, is TERM. TERM must be an element of either Collection or Individual. If TERM is a collection, the semantic meaning of TERM is (isa :noun TERM). If TERM is an individual object, the semantic meaning of TERM is (equals :noun TERM). See also multiWordString, multiWordSemTrans, and #$compoundVerbSemTrans.
label: Compound String
compoundString

comment:
(most_RelationFrom BINPRED THING SOC) means that most elements ELEM of SOC are such that (BINPRED THING ELEM). It is equivalent to the more complex form: 
(most SOC (TheSetOf ?OBJ (BINPRED THING ?OBJ))).
When SOC is a Collection, use the more specialized predicate relationInstanceMost.
label: Most Relation From
most-RelationFrom

comment: (kePredArgStrongSuggestionPreds PRED N BINPRED) means that if the relation expression (PRED . ARGS) is known, and ARGN appears as the Nth argument in (PRED . ARGS) it is strongly suggested that Cyc know there exists a THING such that (BINPRED ARGN THING).
label: Ke Pred Arg Strong Suggestion Preds
kePredArgStrongSuggestionPreds

comment: (relationExistsAllSpecs PRED COL1 COL2) means that for every SUBCOL2 which is a subcollection of COL2, there is some INS1 which is an instance of COL1, such that (PRED INS1 SUBCOL2) holds.
label: Relation Exists All Specs
relationExistsAllSpecs

comment: (delegatesPowersOfType NORM AGENT ACTIVITY-TYPE ROLE) means that ther NormativeSpecification NORM delegates to AGENT the legal authority and responsibility to play ROLE in extended instances of ACTIVITY-TYPE.
label: Delegates Powers Of Type
delegatesPowersOfType
Types Differ WRT Facet Via Bin Rel
typesDifferWRTFacetViaBinRel

comment: ?correspondence has ?target-item in ?sme as its base item.
label: Correspondence For Target Item
correspondenceForTargetItem

comment: (uniqueRolePlayerOfTypeForSubSitType SIT-TYPE SUBSIT-TYPE ROLE-PLAYER-TYPE ROLE) means that for any situation, SUBSIT, that is an instance of SUBSIT-TYPE and a subsituation of an instance of SIT-TYPE, at most one thing of type ROLE-PLAYER-TYPE plays ROLE in SUBSIT.
label: Unique Role Player Of Type For Sub Sit Type
uniqueRolePlayerOfTypeForSubSitType

comment: A TernaryPredicate that relates a specialization of PartiallyTangible to an OrganismClassificationType to a Toxicity. (inhalingToxicityOfTypeFor PT-TYPE ORG-TYPE TOXICITY) means that the inhaling toxicity of PT-TYPE for ORG-TYPE is TOXICITY. For example, (inhalingToxicityOfTypeFor Ammonia HomoSapiens Toxic) means that ammonia is toxic to humans when inhaled.

comment:
A quaternary RuleMacroPredicate that can be used to state that a given binary predicate stands in a certain numerical relationship with respect to two collections. (relationAllExistsMax BINPRED COL1 COL2 N) means that for any instance INST of COL1 there are at most N instances (INST(1), ..., INST(N)) of COL2 such that (BINPRED INST INST(i)) holds (for 1 <= i <= N). This is equivalent to (and can thus be used in effect as shorthand for) the more complex form:

(implies (isa ?INST COL1) (thereExistAtMost N ?INST-I (and (isa ?INST-I COL2) (BINPRED ?INST INST-I)))) .

For example, `(relationAllExistsMax anatomicalParts Dog Leg 4)' means that all dogs have at most four legs.

Cf. relationExistsMaxAll; also see #$NoteAboutUseOfRuleMacroPredicates.
label: Relation All Exists Max
relationAllExistsMax

comment: queryTemplate_Test relates a class of natural language questions (e.g. sentences) to CycL. In addition the slot for the Relation (function or pred) that is the focus of the CycL translation, queryTemplate-Test also has a test that must succeed for the template to match. The test is carried out in InferencePSC as a removal-only ask (e.g. no backchaining allowed). For example, (queryTemplate_Test STemplate objectHasColor ((Be-TheWord Verb) (NPTemplate :obj) (AdjPTemplate :color)) (objectHasColor :obj :color) (isa :color Color)) would map "Is Muffet green" to (objectHasColor Muffet GreenColor), but would not match "Is Muffet happy?".

Has Denotatum
hasDenotatum
comment: A unary MetaLanguagePredicate (q.v.) that holds of instances of CycLTerm that denote or refer to something in the intended model of the CycL language. (hasDenotatum TERM) means that there is something THING such that TERM denotes (see denotes) THING. Note that hasDenotatum's argument-place is not implicitly quoted (see quotedArgument); instead, TERM will often be an explicitly quoted term -- i.e. something wrapped in the syncategorematic quotation symbol 'Quote' (see Quote). For example, the sentence '(hasDenotatum (Quote Plato))' means that the CycL term 'Plato' denotes something, which is true because that term denotes the man Plato. But note that the argument to hasDenotatum need not be quoted. Suppose (e.g.) that the term 'Plato' were the CycL constant most beloved of Cyclists, and that a new constant 'CyclistsFavoriteConstant' were reified and defined so as to reflect this fact. Then 'CyclistsFavoriteConstant' would refer to the CycL constant 'Plato', which in turn denotes the man Plato; and so the sentence '(hasDenotatum CyclistsFavoriteConstant)' would be true. Note finally that the sentence '(hasDenotatum Plato)' is not true, as it means that the man Plato is a CycL term that denotes something, which is a patent falsehood since no man is a CycL term and no man denotes anything. See also EscapeQuote, quotedIsa, and the shared #$NoteAboutQuotingInCycL.

(objectRequiresNCapabilitiesOfTypeToSupportRoleInType OBJ N SET EVENT-TYPE ROLE) means that OBJ requires other systems to provide at least N many of the capabilities in the set SET in order itself to play the role ROLE in an instance of EVENT-TYPE.

comment: (doDenialOfServiceAttackOfType AGENT MANNER DENIED ATTACK-TYPE COMPUTER) means, from COMPUTER, that AGENT performs in MANNER a denial of service attack of ATTACK-TYPE to render DENIED incapable of performing basic services, such as responding to network requests.

comment: (caloricContent STUFF MASS CAL) means that MASS of STUFF, if burned, releases CAL of energy. CAL will generally be stated using the unit function #$Calorie. For example, (caloricContent PeachPie001 (Gram 1) (#$Calorie 7)) means that PeachPie001 has 7 Calories per gram. To state the caloric content of a homogenous type of substance, for example to state that Water_Ingestible has 0 calories per gram, use (implies (isa ?WATER Water_Ingestible) (caloricContent ?WATER (Gram 1) (#$Calorie 0))). This predicate applies not only to food, but to anything that has any tangible part, and it is measured quantitatively and absolutely, with the arg3 representing the stored energy of the substance in kilocalories per MASS. If it can't burn, CAL will be equivalent to zero calories, regardless of the unit of mass. If it can burn, it will have a non-negative value for CAL. To specify the relative caloric content of food, use caloricContentOfFood, which allows qualitative values like High in addition to numeric values.
label: Caloric Content
caloricContent

comment: This predicate relates performers to particular individual actions. (performanceLevel OBJ EVT ROLE QUANT) means that the individual OBJ plays the role ROLE in the action EVT, and does so with the quantity indicated by QUANT. Such an assertion expresses actual performance in a particular action; for example, (performanceLevel Joe DiggingHole54001 performedBy (LowAmountFn Strength)) means Joe exerted a low level of strength while digging that particular hole. This does not imply much about Joe's potential to exert strength, about strength required in general for hole-digging, etc., it just talks about that one single event. To talk about typical or expected performance, use skillLevel.

comment: A ternary predicate that relates a sample of something -- typically a solution -- to the molar concentration of *chemical objects* of a given species which it contains. (molarityOfChemicalObjectInSample SAMPLE CHEM-OBJ-TYPE VALUE) holds just in case SAMPLE has VALUE, expressed in moles per liter, of ions/molecules of type CHEM-OBJ-TYPE. The concentration of ions in a sample is expressed in terms of ((PerFn Mole_ChemicalCountUnit Liter) NUM). Note that for ionic compounds this expresses the molarity of the *dissociated* species in a solution: e.g., if SAMPLE is a 1M aqueous solution of HCl, it would be incorrect to state (molarityOfChemicalObjectInSample SAMPLE (MoleculeFn HydrogenChloride) ((PerFn Mole_ChemicalCountUnit Liter) 1)) since HCl, a strong acid, dissociates completely in HydrogenPlusIons and ChlorideIons, so that SAMPLE contains virtually no amount of HCl *molecules*. On the other hand, it would be correct to assert (molarityOfChemicalObjectInSample (q.v.) SAMPLE HydrogenPlusIons ((PerFn Mole_ChemicalCountUnit Liter) SOME-NUM)).

label: molarity of the chemical species in sample
molarityOfChemicalObjectInSample

PT might, for example, be a Country, a Business, or a household (CohabitationUnit). THING will often be a calendar time period; but it may also be, for instance, a particular Event. If AMOUNT is a Rate, AMOUNT indicates what would be the average rate of consumption of instances of PRODUCT-TYPE by PT during the temporal extent of THING if PT were consuming PRODUCT-TYPE at the limit of its capacity.

comment:
A ternary RuleMacroPredicate (q.v.) that is used to state that a given binary predicate holds between some two instances of two respective collections. (relationExistsExists BINPRED COL1 COL2) means that there is some instance INST1 of COL1 and some instance INST2 of COL2 such that (BINPRED INST1 INST2) holds. This is equivalent to (and so can be used in effect as shorthand for) the more complex form: 
  (thereExists ?INST1
    (thereExists ?INST2
      (and
        (isa ?INST1 COL1)
        (isa ?INST2 COL2)
        (BINPRED ?INST1 ?INST2)))).

For example, (relationExistsExists possesses Dog Bone_BodyPart) means that some dog has a bone. See the shared #$NoteAboutUseOfRuleMacroPredicates.
label: Relation Exists Exists
relationExistsExists

comment:
A ternary instance of InterArgIsaPredicate (q.v.). (interArgEqualsIsa4_5 RELN INDEPENDENT-ARG DEPENDENT-ARG-COL) means that, when INDEPENDENT-ARG appears as the fourth argument to RELN, a necessary condition for semantic well-formedness is that the fifth argument must be an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. That is, (RELN ARG1 ARG2 ARG3 INDEPENDENT-ARG ARG5 ...) is semantically well-formed only if ARG5 is an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL.

For an explanation of semantic well-formedness, see CycLExpression_Assertible and its direct specializations. See interArgEqualsIsa for a similar but more general predicate that is quintary, allowing the user to specify the positions of the independent and dependent arguments.

SET-OF-STRINGS is the union of the all the strings that are associated with all of the synsets in which WORD appears for POS.

comment: (findAnalog ?Src-Mt ?Src ?Tgt-Mt ?Tgt) causes ?Tgt to become bound to the best analog (according to structure-mapping metrics) for the source concept ?Src as defined source domain microtheory ?Src-Mt in the target domain ?Tgt-Mt. That is, find the ?Tgt-Mt equivalent of ?Src as it is defined in ?Src-Mt. Example: (findAnalog Iraq #$DesertShieldMt #$Y1Phase2-AllStagesMt ?What) should cause ?What to be bound to Iran. See also structureMaps and structureDiffs.
label: Find Analog
findAnalog

comment: (keContrastingSentences TERM1 TERM2 SENTENCE1) means that SENTENCE1 has the following properties: it mentions TERM1, it is not true if TERM2 is substituted for TERM1, it contains no keIrrelevantTerms, and it is useful for contrasting TERM1 and TERM2.
label: Ke Contrasting Sentences
keContrastingSentences

comment: This variable-arity predicate (see VariableArityRelation), all of whose argument-places are quotedArguments (q.v.), is used to make non-identity statements about two or more symbols. Stated loosely, (differentSymbols X1 X2 ... Xn) means that each of the Xi is a symbol that is different from all of the others. Given that the arguments are "quoted", however, it is more accurate to say: A ground atomic formula (or "GAF"; see CycLClosedAtomicSentence) consisting of the expression `differentSymbols' followed by the CycL expressions E1, ..., En (all enclosed within a pair of parentheses) is true if and only if each Ei is a different expression from all of the others. Note that two symbols can denote the same thing (in ordinary circumstances) and still be different symbols. As an example (using English expressions for convenience), the proper name `Bertrand Russell' and the descriptive phrase `the author of "On Denoting"' are two different expressions, even though they both denote the same person. Two symbols can even share the same intensional meaning and yet be different symbols; e.g. `bachelor' and `unmarried man'. The sentence `(differentSymbols BertrandRussell BertrandRussell)', on the other hand, is false. See also equalSymbols and different.
label: Different Symbols
differentSymbols

comment: ksImportationTemplate states a template used for mapping statements in an external knowledge source into CycL. comment: (realGDPGrowthRateDuring GE THING NR) means that NR is the growth rate of the GeopoliticalEntity GE's real (adjusted for inflation) gross domestic product during the temporal extent of the TemporalThing THING. (THING will often be a calendar time period.) That is, NR is the quotient of the difference between GE's gross domestic product for the temporal extent of THING and GE's gross domestic product for the time interval immediately preceding, and of the same duration as, THING (as dividend) and GE's gross domestic product for the time interval immediately preceding, and of the same duration as, THING (as divisor). For example, to express the fact that Oman's real gross domestic product growth rate for 1997 was 5.9%, we can say (realGDPGrowthRateDuring Oman (YearFn 1997) .059). See also grossDomesticProduct.

comment:
A SummaryPredicate. (interestingForArgOfTypeInReln N COL PRED) means that for any assertion ASSERTION of the form (RELN . ARGS) such that (genlPreds RELN PRED) and (assertionSentence ASSERTION SENTENCE), (interestingSentence THING SENTENCE) will be true for the Nth argument ARG-N of SENTENCE, provided that ARG-N is an instance of COL.

For example, if (interestingForArgOfTypeInReln 1 Politician affiliatedWith) and (isa BillClinton Politician) are true, then (interestingSentence BillClinton (headOfStateOf BillClinton UnitedStatesOfAmerica)) holds, since BillClinton is the arg 1 of (headOfStateOf BillClinton UnitedStatesOfAmerica), that sentence is asserted in the KB, and (genlPreds headOfStateOf affiliatedWith).

interestingForArgOfTypeInReln

comment:
A TernaryPredicate that is used to state that a special relation holds between a FacetingCollectionType and a Predicate -- that the former is "based on" the latter in a specific way.

Where (facets_Generic COL FACET-COL) and PRED is an n-place predicate, (facetBasedOnTypePredicateArg FACET-COL PRED ARG) means that for all X in FACET-COL, there is an ordered n-tuple <Y1,...,Yn> such that, by the definition of X, for any specialization Z of COL, the result of replacing YARG with Z in (PRED Y1...Yn) holds iff Z = X.

For example, (facetBasedOnTypePredicateArg OrganizationTypeByActivityType characteristicActivityTypeOfOrganizationType 1) means that for all ORG-TYPE in OrganizationTypeByActivityType there is an ordered pair <DUMMY, ACT-TYPE> such that, by the definition of ORG-TYPE, for any specialization SPEC of Organization, (characteristicActivityTypeOfOrganizationType SPEC ACT-TYPE) holds iff SPEC = ORG-TYPE.

Note that it is also true that (facetBasedOnTypePredicateArg OrganizationTypeByActivityType equals 1) and (facetBasedOnTypePredicateArg OrganizationTypeByActivityType equals 2). Indeed, (facetBasedOnTypePredicateArg FACET-COL equals 1) and (facetBasedOnTypePredicateArg FACET-COL equals 2) are trivially true for any FACET-COL, since the following is a logical truth: 

(forAll ?X
  (thereExists ?Y
    (forAll ?Z
      (equiv
        (equals ?Z ?Y)
        (equals ?Z ?X))))).
For precisely this reason, there is no point in asserting that a facet is based on equals.

For the very common special case in which PRED is a BinaryPredicate, see facetBasedOnTypeBinaryPred and facetBasedOnTypeBinaryPredInverse. See also facetBasedOnPredicateArg and #$SharedNoteOnFacetBasisPredicates.
label: Facet Based On Type Predicate Arg
facetBasedOnTypePredicateArg

comment: An assertion of the form (roleMapping_Equivalence SIT-TYPE TYPE SET) is used to represent a role-mapping relations between actors of TYPE in the sub-events of instances of SIT-TYPE. The relevant set of roles is captured by SET. SET is a set of lists, each element of which has two elements. The first element is a sub-collection of Situation that SIT-TYPE is either identical to or which SIT-TYPE has as at least a candidate scene (see: candidateProperSubSituationTypes) and the second element is a BinaryRolePredicate. Specifically, it asserts that if SET contains as elements (TheList SUBSIT-TYPE1 ROLE1) and (TheList SUBSIT-TYPE2 ROLE2), given certain other conditions, this entails that any instance of TYPE playing ROLE1 in the instance of SUBSIT-TYPE1 will also play ROLE2 in the instance of SUBSIT-TYPE2. It is worth noting that SUBSIT-TYPE1 and SUBSIT-TYPE2 can be identical, or one could be identical to SIT-TYPE itself.
label: Role Mapping Equivalence
roleMapping-Equivalence

comment: (negationInverseWRTTypes BINPRED1 BINPRED2 COL1 COL2) means that if (BINPRED1 INS1 INS2) where INS1 is an instance of COL1 and INS2 is an instance of COL2, then (not (BINPRED2 INS2 INS1)). This allows us to specify a pseudo-negationPreds relationship between two BinaryPredicates when their arguments are of the appropriate types. At a more specific level, negationInverseWRTTypes can serve as a useful rule macro predicate. See also genlPredsWRTTypes, genlInverseWRTTypes, and #$negationPredsWRTTypes.
label: Negation Inverse WRT Types
negationInverseWRTTypes

comment: (importAmountDuring REGION PRODUCT-TYPE THING AMOUNT) means that the ScalarInterval AMOUNT is a measure of the amount of instances of the ProductType PRODUCT-TYPE imported by the GeographicalRegion REGION during the temporal extent of the TemporalThing THING. THING will often be a calendar time period; but it may also be, for instance, a particular Event. In the case of automobile imports, for example, AMOUNT might be an Integer indicating the number of cars imported. In the case of oil imports, AMOUNT might be a Volume (a number of barrels) indicating the total quantity of oil imported, or it might be an instance of MonetaryValue indicating the monetary value of all the oil imported. Alternatively, AMOUNT might be a Rate, characterizing the average rate of import of instances of PRODUCT-TYPE by REGION during the temporal extent of THING. Oil imports, for example, might be expressed in terms of so many million barrels per day or in terms of so many dollars per day (again, indicating the monetary value of the oil). The total value of a region's imports of all goods and services (over a given time period) can be expressed with this predicate using the constant Product as the second argument.
label: Import Amount During
importAmountDuring

comment: (lexicalNodeDenotMeetsNounCompoundConstraint NODE DENOT CONSTRAINT) means that NODE meets the semantic constraint specified by CONSTRAINT, by virture of denoting DENOT.
label: Lexical Node Denot Meets Noun Compound Constraint
lexicalNodeDenotMeetsNounCompoundConstraint

comment: A ternary complex action predicate. (doDefineFunction PROGRAMMER FILE FUNCTION) means that PROGRAMMER appends to the end of FILE code that declares FUNCTION, an instance of ProgramFunction.

comment: (disableDeviceWithRespectToFunction AGENT DEVICE SIT-TYPE ROLE) means that AGENT prevents DEVICE from playing the role ROLE in situations of type SIT-TYPE.

amountSold

comment: This relation is used to specify the 'mortality risk' for a particular type of AilmentCondition. We conceive this risk to be the prior ProbabilityInterval that an individual afflicted with a particular AilmentCondition will die of that condition. Alternatively (and equivalently) the relation can be viewed as making a prediction about the percentage of individuals in a population afflicted with a certain AilmentCondition that will ultimately die as the result of having that condition, assuming normal conditions and no preventative/ameliorative measures.
label: Mortality Risk For Condition
mortalityRiskForCondition

comment: (standardEchelonSpecialtySubstructure ORG-TYPE-BY-EGB-SUPER MIL-ORG-COL ORG-TYPE-BY-EGB-SUB SPECIALTY-TYPE N) means that ordinarily, a unit with the #$MilitaryEchelon, sovereignAllegianceOfOrg, and BranchOfMilitaryService of ORG-TYPE-BY-EGB-SUPER, of the military organization class MIL-ORG-COL can be expected to have exactly N subOrganizations with MilitaryUnitSpecialtyType SPECIALTY-TYPE and with the #$MilitaryEchelon, sovereignAllegianceOfOrg, and BranchOfMilitaryService of ORG-TYPE-BY-EGB-SUB.

standardEchelonSpecialtySubstructure

comment: (instanceDiffersFromPrototypicalInstance_Addition INST TYPE SCRIPT ADDITION) means that the assertion ADDITION references INST, and when INST is compared with a protototypical instance of TYPE generated by propagating the assertions in SCRIPT to deductive closure, no comparable assertion (an assertion formed by substituting occurrences of the prototype for occurrences of INST) is found for the prototype.

comment: (quarterTypeOfYearType QUARTER-TYPE N YEAR-TYPE) identifies QUARTER-TYPE as the collection of Nth quarters of any year that is an instance of YEAR-TYPE, a sub-collection of CalendarYear.

quarterTypeOfYearType

comment:
This predicate relates a set of ObjectDefiningSchemas that are all input schemas of the same type for an IntegratingASetOfKnowledgeSources event (see schemaIntegrationTypeForInputODSSet) to the set of multiplicity lists (see ListMultiplicityListFn) of the schemas' respective logical field type lists (See logicalSchemaFieldTypeList). That is, (schemaIntegrationInputODSSetHasTypeMultiplicityListSet INTEGRATION INPUT-ODS-SET INPUT-ODS-TYPE-MULTIPLICITY-LIST-SET) means that:

1. The elements of INPUT-ODS-SET are all input object defining schemas in INTEGRATION;

2. INPUT-ODS-TYPE-MULTIPLICITY-LIST-SET is the set of lists of length two obtained by first taking the TYPE-LIST for each of the elements of INPUT-ODS-LIST (obtained from the arg2 of logicalSchemaFieldTypeList), applying the function ListMultiplicityListFn to TYPE-LIST to obtain TYPE-MULTIPLICITY-LIST-LIST, applying SetOfListMembersFn to TYPE-MULTIPLICITY-LIST-LIST to obtain TYPE-MULTIPLICITY-LIST-SET and then finally taking the set union of the TYPE-MULTIPLICITY-LIST-SETs over all elements of INPUT-ODS-SET.

This predicate is used in further analysis of the input schemas to determine the correct set of logical fields and meaning sentences for their corresponding schemas.
label: Schema Integration Input ODS Set Has Type Multiplicity List Set
schemaIntegrationInputODSSetHasTypeMultiplicityListSet

comment: (assertionTrivialForJustificationParaphrase ASSERTION) means that when ASSERTION, an instance of CycLAssertion, is used in a transformation proof, it is deemed trivial. It is unnecessary to explicitly mention ASSERTION as a support for returned bindings, because a human would regard it as obvious.
label: Assertion Trivial For Justification Paraphrase
assertionTrivialForJustificationParaphrase

comment: A ternary predicate intended to express the quantity of chemical species (see ChemicalObjectTypeByChemicalSpecies) in a sample of something, (possibly a sample of the same substance) when the quantity is measured in terms of number of basic parts or units. A standard unit used in chemistry is Mole_ChemicalCountUnit. Thus, for instance, (quantityOfChemicalObjectInSample SAMPLE HydroniumIon (Mole_ChemicalCountUnit 0.5)) says that SAMPLE is a partially tangible thing containing 0.5 moles of hydronium ions. Cf. quantityOfSubstanceInSample.
Mx4rwLSVCpwpEbGdrcN5Y29ycA: quantities of moles of chemical object in a sample

quantityOfChemicalObjectInSample

comment: This predicate defines how a logical field in a logical schema is interpreted and given a physical value in a corresponding physical schema. The sentence (fieldEncoding PHYSICAL-SCHEMA PF-INDEXICAL LOGICAL-SCHEMA ENCODING-EXPRESSION) is used to state an ENCODING-EXPRESSION, which is one of the term-level translation templates (encodings) from LOGICAL-SCHEMA into PHYSICAL-SCHEMA. More precisely, ENCODING-EXPRESSION expresses a translation in terms of some of the the logical fields of LOGICAL-SCHEMA into a physically encoded term suitable for PF-INDEXICAL in PHYSICAL-SCHEMA.
label: Field Encoding
fieldEncoding

providerTreatsNumPatientsWithAilmentDuring

comment: A ternary predicate, an assertion of the form (partiallyProtectedAgainst_RoleInType OBJ TYPE ROLE) says that OBJ is partially protected against playing ROLE in some instance of TYPE. The notion of protection here is to be cashed out in terms of an agent's interests or desires being promoted through the prevention of the occurrence of some instance INS of TYPE such that (ROLE INS OBJ). It is possible that the relevant agent is not OBJ.

partiallyProtectedAgainst-RoleInType

comment:
(closestEventPriorToWithinIntervalWithValueFor EVT1 EVT2 INTERVAL PROPERTY ) means that EVT1 is the nearest event prior to EVT2 within INTERVAL that has some value for PROPERTY. This entails that 
   
     (thereExists ?VALUE 
          (PROPERTY EVT1 ?VALUE))
In medical contexts it is assumed that both events involve the same patient.

comment: '(alphabeticalIndexTo CWSTRUC BODY INDEX)' means that, within the CWStructure CWSTRUC, the TextString INDEX is an alphabetical index to the GraphicalStructure BODY. The instance of GraphicalStructure which is indexed by the TextString that is the third argument of alphabeticalIndexTo may be the entire TextualPCWStructure of which the index is a part (i.e., some indices reference only the body of a work, while others reference the body, the preface, appendices, and other parts of the work). Consequently, the value for the first and second arguments of alphabeticalIndexTo may be identical.

alphabeticalIndexTo

comment: (scheduledAttendeeDate EVENT PERSON DATE) means that the Agent_PartiallyTangible PERSON is scheduled to be a participant in (deliberateActors) the referredTo event starting at the referenced date. If the starting time for EVENT is unknown, then it would default to DATE, except for certain event types such as War. Similarly, if (scheduledAttendee EVENT PERSON) and the starting time of EVENT is known, then that time is the default scheduledAttendeeDate.
label: Scheduled Attendee Date
scheduledAttendeeDate

costBenefitSentenceForSituationType

comment: (programListeningOnComputerHasFault PROG COMP FAULT) means that the copy of PROG which is currently listening on some port on COMP (programOnPort, q.v.) COMP manifests FAULT.

programListeningOnComputerHasFault

comment: A KEFacilitationPredicate and RuleMacroPredicate. (keStrongSuggestionPredsInverse_InsOfType COL BINPRED TYPE) means that for every known (i.e. Cyc-reified) instance INST of COL, it is strongly suggested that there be some reified instance INS-TYPE of TYPE such that (BINPRED INS-TYPE INST) is known in the Knowledge Base.
label: Ke Strong Suggestion Preds Inverse Ins Of Type
keStrongSuggestionPredsInverse-InsOfType

comment: This specialization of foreignKeyMap entails an additional constraint on deleting or modifying the rows of the referenced schema. That is (foreignKeyMap_SetDefault REFERENCED_SCHEMA REFERENCED_KEY REFERENCING_SCHEMA REFERENCING_FIELD_LIST) means in addition to the constraints inherited from foreignKeyMap, on deleting a row of REFERENCED_SCHEMA with a row of REFERENCING_SCHEMA that references it, the referencing fields in REFERENCING_SCHEMA are set to their default values. Contrast this behavior with foreignKeyMap_Cascade, foreignKeyMap_Restrict, and foreignKeyMap_SetNull.
label: Foreign Key Map Set Default
foreignKeyMap-SetDefault

comment: (electricForceBetween OBJ1 OBJ2 CHARGE) means that CHARGE is the electric force between OBJ1 and OBJ2.

electricForceBetween

comment: A ternary MetaRelation predicate for stating that a certain kind of complex, partly isa based relationship holds between the second argument to a given function and the corresponding value that is returned. (interArg2ResultIsa FUNC INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL DEPENDENT-ARG-COL) means that, when an instance of INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL appears as the second argument to FUNC, then -- regardless of what the other arguments to FUNC might be -- the value (if any) of that function for those arguments is an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. That is: if INST is an instance of INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL and (FUNC ARG1 INST ...) = VALUE, then VALUE is an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. Note that, unlike (e.g.) the InterArgTypePredicates, interArg2ResultIsa _cannot_ be used to put semantic well-formedness constraints on functions. See also the similar but more flexible quaternary interArgResultIsa.
label: Inter Arg 2 Result Isa
interArg2ResultIsa

comment: (schemaIntegrationInputODSSetHasTargetODS INTEGRATION INPUT-ODS-SET TARGET-ODS) means that in the SKS schema integration INTEGRATION (see IntegratingASetOfKnowledgeSources), TARGET-ODS is the object defining schema in the target knowledge source that unifies all of the input object defining schemas in INPUT-ODS-SET.
label: Schema Integration Input ODS Set Has Target ODS
schemaIntegrationInputODSSetHasTargetODS

comment: (maximalConstraint_Isa PRED N COL) says that the known maximal constraint for the Nth argument place of PRED is any instance of COL. Here, 'maximal constraint' means that typically, the best or most sensible collection, any instance of which could fill the Nth argument place, is COL. The maximal isa constraint for a predicate need not always be determined by its argIsa assertions, though sometimes it will be (when it its not, the maximal isa constraint is determined by the predicates typicalArgIsa assertions). An example of a predicate for which the argIsa assertions do not determine a maximal isa constraint could be, primaryFunction, whose arg1Isa is SomethingExisting. This isn't maximal, since this allows one to construct well-formed instances of #$ELSentence-Assertible by putting an instance of HumanInfant in the arg1 position, and we generally do not consider infants to be things with a 'primary function' (see the comment on primaryFunction), though we *could*.
label: Maximal Constraint Isa
maximalConstraint-Isa

comment: (participantStatus AGENT EVENT PARTICIPATION-FORM) means that the Agent_Generic, AGENT, participates in Event, EVENT, in the manner of PARTICIPATION-FORM, an instance of SocialGatheringParticipationPredicate. I.e. (PARTICIPATION-FORM AGENT EVENT). Examples of such particpation forms are confirmedParticipantIn, declinedParticipationIn, #$noShowFor, etc. The status of the participant can change over time; e.g., when a passenger with an airline reservervation shows up and gets a boarding pass, or when s/he actually surrender the boarding pass and boards the plane.
label: Participant Status
participantStatus

comment: (willBe_Metric_CalendarTime METRIC-TYPE k TIME-TYPE PROP) means that PROP will be the case at the time TIME-TYPE of the k-th time interval of type METRIC-TYPE in the future. Here are a few examples: (willBe_Metric_CalendarTime Monday 1 (TimeOfDayFn TimeOfDay_10AM (MinuteOfHourFn 30)) `Charles goes to a business meeting') means that Charles will go to a business meeting at 10:30am-10:31am next Monday (the coming Monday), (willBe_Metric_CalendarTime CalendarDay 2 (TimeOfDayFn TimeOfDay_10AM (TimeOfHourFn (MinuteOfHourFn 0) (SecondOfMinuteFn 0))) `Charles goes to a business meeting') means that Charles will go to a business meeting at 10:00:00am-10:00:01am the day after tomorrow, and (willBe_Metric_CalendarTime CalendarMonth 1 (TimeOfMonthFn (DayOfMonthFn 3) TimeOfDay_10AM) `Charles goes to a business meeting') means that Charles will go to a business meeting the third day of next month, at 10am-11am. (See other metric tense predicates willBe_Metric, was_Metric and was_Metric_CalendarTime, and plain tense operators willBe and was etc.)
label: Will Be Metric Calendar Time
willBe-Metric-CalendarTime

comment: followsFromPrecedingDiscourse is a natural-language-based predicate that applies to a single propositional argument. (followsFromPrecedingDiscourse PROP) means that PROP follows logically from the immediately preceding statements in a discourse context. In English it can be rendered as "Therefore, PROP", or "Q.E.D. PROP".

comment: (actionUsedQuantity AGENT ACTION PERFORMANCE-QUANT) holds just in case AGENT experiences the degree of experience represented by PERFORMANCE-QUANT while performing ACTION. The third argument of this predicate will most often be occupied by a NART created by an instance of GenericValueFunction. The argument to the value function will, in those cases, be an instance of PerformanceLevelQuantity. that instance will mark the type of experience and the value function will return the Quantity of that experience expressed by the value function. For instance, '(actionUsedQuantity WilliamShakespeare ReadingHamlet04 (LowAmountFn PhysicalEffortLevel))' means that WilliamShakespeare found his reading of Hamlet (on that particular occasion) to require only a slight physical effort.

comment: The functionCorrespondingPredicate of PreparingToPlayRoleInTypeFn (typePreparesForRoleInType PREPARATION-TYPE ROLE TYPE) identifies PREPARATION-TYPE as the collection of events in which an intelligent agent prepares to play the role ROLE in a situation of type TYPE. For example, (typePreparesForRoleInType StudyingForTheSATs performedBy TakingTheSATs) says that StudyingForTheSATs is the collection of events in which someone prepares to take the SATs.
label: Type Prepares For Role In Situation
typePreparesForRoleInSituation

Mx4rwLSVCpwpEbGdrcN5Y29ycA: orders to submit to operational control

ordersOperationalControl

comment: An assertion (roleMapping_Branch_Identity SIT-TYPE TYPE BRANCH-SET LINK-LIST) is used to represent the inheritance relations among actors within instances of some complex type of Situation. Specifically, it is used to represent situations where a single actor fills a set of common roles, but and then goes on to be one of possibly several actors who fill some other roles in other scenes. The argument BRANCH-SET is used to represent the first set of roles. BRANCH-SET is a set of lists with the following structure: (TheList (TheList SUBSIT-TYPE-1 ROLE-1) ... (TheList SUBSIT-TYPE-N ROLE-N) ...). Assertions using this predicate behave similarly to roleMapping_Identity in terms of their arguments SIT-TYPE TYPE and BRANCH-SET. Thus, in an instance of SIT-TYPE, if an actor of TYPE plays ROLE-1 in a subSituations of type SUBSIT-TYPE-1, then that actor is numerically identical to the actor playing ROLE-N in a subSituations of type SUBSIT-TYPE-N. The difference comes in the relation to the argument LINK-LIST. LINK-LIST also represents a role within a scene, and it could be that LINK-LIST will be an element of LIST for some assertion of the form (roleMapping_Equivalence SIT-TYPE TYPE LIST), where SIT-TYPE and TYPE are the same as above. Thus, the LINK-LIST could be used to connect the BRANCH-SET to a single scene-role pair, or to several scene-role pairs that are another actor path for TYPE within SIT-TYPE. Because the roles on BRANCH-SET only entail the roles on LINK-LIST, there is no identity constraint on the role in LINK-LIST or any othe role-mapping structure of which LINK-LIST is a part.
label: Role Mapping Branch Identity
roleMapping-Branch-Identity

comment: An instance of GeneralizedQuantifierRelation (q.v.). (num_GenQuantRelnTo RELN COL THING NUM) is true if for exactly NUM instances X of COL (RELN X THING) holds. For example, (num_GenQuantRelnTo objectFoundInLocation Pizzeria CityOfAustinTX 5) means that there are exactly five pizzerias in Austin, Tex. The second argument place of this predicate is constrained to instances of SetOrCollection -- the more specific relationExistsCountInstance (the second argument place of which is constrained to instances of Collection) should be used instead of num_GenQuantRelnTo whenever possible.
label: Num Gen Quant Reln To
num-GenQuantRelnTo

comment: If INTEGRATION is an IntegratingASetOfKnowledgeSources, ODS is an ObjectDefiningSchema, and SKS is a StructuredKnowledgeSource, then (schemaIntegrationODSHasTargetSubSKS INTEGRATION ODS SKS) means that SKS is the target sub-knowledge source of INTEGRATION (see schemaIntegrationTargetSubSKS) that is associated with the target object defining schema ODS. See schemaIntegrationTypeForTargetODS.

schemaIntegrationODSHasTargetSubSKS

comment: The agent ARG1 owes to (is obliged to pay toward) account ARG2 the amount ARG4 by the date ARG3.  ARG3 is the payment due date.  This says nothing about whether the payment is actually made.  It is just a way of stating that there is an obligation to pay.
label: Payment Due For Account
paymentDueForAccount

comment: (potentialDutyOfAgent AGENT ACTTYPE ROLE) means that AGENT may potentially be called upon to play ROLE in an event which satisfies the description given in the set or collection expression that is ACTTYPE in the context of the assertion. Ordinarily GAFs which use this predicate will be asserted in fairly constrained contexts in which a limited number of contingent options exist. The fact that arg3 is an instance of ActorSlot presupposes that the set identified in the arg2 position is a subset of Event.
label: Potential Duty Of Agent
potentialDutyOfAgent

comment: (fetViewableAssertionsForTerm THING ASSRT TEMPLATE-TYPE) holds just in case ASSRT is a CycL assertion whose form corresponds to some FET template formula that is in some instance of TEMPLATE-TYPE. This means that the assertion should be viewable via template that's an instance of TEMPLATE-TYPE when THING is loaded as the focal term.
label: Fet Viewable Assertions For Term
fetViewableAssertionsForTerm

comment: (importanceOfThingInSet THING SET GENERIC-VALUE-PRED) means that of the elements of SET, THING is an important member by some measure of 'importance' that is legitimate in the current microtheory. Assertions about 'major', 'moderate', 'low' importance of THING should have highAmountOf, mediumAmountOf, and lowAmountOf for GENERIC-VALUE-PRED. Importance is a highly context dependent notion. This context dependence may be determined by the goals of the current conversation, or by the properties of the Microtheory that a given importanceOfThingInSet assertion occurs in, or by some implicit agent's judgements about what is important, or some other factors. Concluding importance is a heuristic matter, i.e. there are often not hard and fast rules concluding importanceOfThingInSet except in more narrowly defined contexts. Thus, it would probably not be correct to write a rule such as 'If ?STATE is one of the 10 biggest U.S. states its importance is high.' unless, for example, such an assertion were stated in a conversational microtheory where conversational agents share the belief that 'the bigger a thing is, the more important it is'. On the other hand, a rule such as 'If ?STATE is one of the 10 oldest U.S. states its importance is high.' might be of some worth in the 'HistoriansMt' in which history experts would be identified as the aforementioned implicit importance evaluating agents. Finally, a rule such as 'If ?STATE is one of the 10 most populous U.S. state's then its importance is high' is a rule that could be re-used in a wider variety of applications. The original motivation of this constant was to preserve the level of vagueness in a natural language statement such as 'Houston is an important oil port.'
label: importance
importanceOfThingInSet

comment: (performsInsAtLocation AGENT TYPE LOC) means that the Agent_PartiallyTangible AGENT performs instances of activities of type TYPE at location LOC. For example, (performsInsAtLocation DallasCowboys HomeFootballGames TexasStadium) means that the Dallas Cowboys play home football games at Texas Stadium.
label: Performs Ins At Location
performsInsAtLocation

comment: (customary_SitRelationToType SIT BIN-PRED CUSTOMARY-TYPE) means that there it would follow custom or convention in some culture (see CulturalConvention_Specification) if there were an instance CUSTOMARY-INS of CUSTOMARY-TYPE such that (BIN-PRED SIT CUSTOMARY-INS). customary_SitRelationToType is a very general requirement predicate most useful for querying. Representations of particular conventions will normally employ specializations of this predicate. E.g., if BIN-PRED is an instance of BinaryRolePredicate, use customary_SitRolePlayerOfType. If CUSTOMARY-INS is a type of Situation (e.g., one an instance of which should be a subEvents of SIT), use customary_SitRelationToSitType.
label: Customary Sit Relation To Type
customary-SitRelationToType
Default Reformulator Mode Precedence
defaultReformulatorModePrecedence
comment: (defaultReformulatorModePrecedence PRIMARY-MODE SECONDARY-MODE TERTIARY-MODE ...), asserted in the microtheory MT, means that in MT or a specMt thereof (unless overridden), the CycLReformulator will use PRIMARY-MODE as its primary mode, SECONDARY-MODE as its secondary mode, etc. This helps the reformulator establish precedence of CycLReformulatorDirectives. Do not specify both tersify and verbosify.

label: Concept Tagging Irrelevant Term
conceptTaggingIrrelevantTerm
comment: (conceptTaggingIrrelevantTerm X) is true for those concepts X that should, by default, not be returned for any string when tagging a string with Cyc concepts. For example, it makes little sense to return a term like (InstanceNamedFn "Fred" Thing) when performing concept-tagging for the purpose of document indexing.

(abstractOfOtherWork WORK TEXT SUMMARIZEDWORK) means that the StructurallySpecificWork WORK contains (see containsStructure_CW) TEXT, a TextString which is an abstract of SUMMARIZEDWORK, a TextualPCW. WORK and SUMMARIZEDWORK are necessarily different ConceptualWorks. Instances of Bibliography often contain abstracts of the works cited therein. For abstracts of a work within that work itself, see abstractOfSameWork
label: Abstract Of Other Work
abstractOfOtherWork

comment: (languageAvailableForUIAInteractions LANGUAGE) means that LANGUAGE is supported by the UIA -- i.e., the user can select LANGUAGE from the menu of languages in the user modeller, and conduct a KE session.
label: Language Available For UIA Interactions

comment: (relationInstanceMember PRED INST GROUP) states that for every MEMBER of GROUP the following is true: (PRED INST MEMBER). This predicate enables one to make claims about the members of a group by referencing only the group itself.
