(equivRolePlayers SIT-TYPE SUBSIT-TYPE1 SUBSIT-TYPE2 ROLE1 ROLE2) means where SIT is a complex situation of type SIT-TYPE, any actor that plays the role ROLE-FROM in any instance of SUBSIT-TYPE-FROM that is a subSituations of SIT is identical to any actor that plays the role ROLE-TO in any instance of SUBSIT-TYPE-TO that is a subSituations of SIT.

That is, with respect to a sentence of the form (PRED ARG1 ARG2 ARG3 ARG4 ARG5 ... ARGN) in which ARG1 is an instance of COL, PRED's arg5 position (i.e. the position occupied by the metavariable `ARG5' in the preceding sentence-form) is subject to FORMAT. See Format and its instances for further explanation.

label: Do Exploit Fault Of Program On System Report Indexed
doExploitFaultOfProgramOnSystem-ReportIndexed

comment: An assertion of the form (roleMappingOverlap SIT-TYPE TYPE SUBSIT-TYPE ROLE) states that in instances of the complex type of Situation SIT-TYPE, there can be more than one instance of TYPE playing ROLE in the subSituations of the situation-instance which is itself an instance of SUBSIT-TYPE. Additionally, and more significantly, the different instances can go on to play seprate roles in other scenes. So, the instances are following different role-mappings through SIT-TYPE, but those role-mappings share a common point at ROLE in the subSituations that is an instance of SUBSIT-TYPE. These path crossings are inferentially significant because if one only knows that an actor is playing ROLE in an instance of SUBSIT-TYPE in an instance of of SIT-TYPE, one cannot deductively infer what other roles that actor is playing. Other information is required. For example, in a script representing the hijacking of an Airplane during flight, there will be many instances of Person who play the role of transportees during the first stage of the flight. However, only some of those transportees will go on to play the role of hijackerPerpetrator while others will go on to play the role of crimeVictim. Although it is safe to infer that the instances of Person playing the role of hijackerPerpetrator had played the role of transportees, the inference from transportees to hijackerPerpetrator cannot be deductively inferred because some of the transportees play the role crimeVictim. So, we introduce the predicate roleMappingOverlap to block incorrect inferences while allowing for the representation of the relevant facts.
label: Role Mapping Overlap
roleMappingOverlap

comment: termTemplate relates a class of natural language utterances to CycL terms. For example, (termTemplate NPTemplate ("pictures" "of" (NPTemplate :obj)) (PicturesFn :obj)) would map "pictures of The Beatles" to (PicturesFn TheBeatles_MusicGroup).

The equipment in question may merely be carried, or it may be mounted on the vehicle that is carrying it. comment: The corresponding predicate (see functionCorrespondingPredicate_Canonical) for IncreaseInValueReturnedByFn. Where FN is a unary, evaluatable function whose value changes over time for admitted argument ARG, (increaseInValueReturnedBy FN ARG INCREASE-COL) means that COL is the collection of all events in which the value returned by FN for ARG is greater at the end of the event than at the start.

comment: This predicate is used by the SKSI code to estimate the cost of querying the fields of a logical schema. More precisely, let SCHEMA denote a logical schema, let LF-1, LF-2, ..., LF-N, denote the logical fields of SCHEMA, and let SELECT_SET and WHERE_SET denote two disjoint subsets of (TheSet LF-1 LF-2 ... LF-N). Then (#$ logicalResultSetCardinalityWRTValue SCHEMA SELECT_SET WHERE_SET NUM VALUE) means that NUM is the average cardinality of the result set returned from a query in which the fields in SELECT_SET left unbound and the fields of WHERE_SET are bound with VALUE.
label: Logical Result Set Cardinality WRT Value
logicalResultSetCardinalityWRTValue

comment: The predicate behaviorCapable is used to indicate that an object (an instance of SomethingExisting) can play a role (an instance of BinaryRolePredicate) in a type of situation (a specialization of Situation). (behaviorCapable OBJ SIT-TYPE ROLE) means that OBJ is able to play ROLE in a situation of type SIT-TYPE. Note that OBJ may or may not have been designed to function in that way (see the specializations of behaviorCapable, primaryFunction and intendedBehaviorCapable). Moreover, unlike capableOf (q.v.), behaviorCapable does not imply that OBJ can unquestionably act in that way in every such situation, since extrinsic factors may prevent it from doing so; for example, if OBJ is a tool, it may be in the wrong location or operated by a person lacking the requisite skills. Examples: (intended capability) a hammer is behaviorCapable of being the deviceUsed in instances of HammeringANail; (unintended capability) an inner tube is capable of being the deviceUsed in instances of people FloatingInLiquid.
label: Behavior Capable
behaviorCapable

comment: (nthInSeries SERIES ITEM N) means that ITEM is the Nth item in the Series SERIES.

comment: A TernaryPredicate that relates a PartiallyTangible to a TemporalThing to an EnergyQuantity. (netWorkDoneOnObjectIn OBJ TEMP-THING QUANT) means that the net work done on OBJ in TEMP-THING is QUANT; that is, QUANT equals the kinetic energy of OBJ at the end of TEMP-THING minus the kinetic energy of OBJ at the beginning of TEMP-THING. comment: (retainTerm TERM) states that TERM should remain defined in the system, even if it would otherwise appear that TERM could be removed from the system. This is most useful when applied to NATs, since NATs are functionally defined and added to the system whenever they are used in some assertion. If the assertions motivating the addition of the NAT are later removed from the KB, there is no longer any a priori reason to retain the NAT in the system. This predicate provides the means to state the expectation that such a NAT should stay defined, even in such cases. When manually asserting, cyclists are encouraged to use retainTermBecause.

comment:
(predicateLicensesSenseExtensionFromNamestringPredInArgToNamestringPredInArg PREDICATE NSPRED-1 N NSPRED-2 M) means that PREDICATE, an instance of SenseExtendingPredicate, licenses the extension of the sense of a name NAME for a thing THING to some other thing OTHER iff:

1) S is a true sentence such that 

   (operatorFormulas PREDICATE S)

   (argN THING N S)

   (argN OTHER M S),
2) NAME is a name for THING such that 
   (NSPRED-1 THING NAME)
and

3) the extension of NAME to OTHER is such that 
   (NSPRED-2 OTHER NAME).
For example, 
   (predicateLicensesSenseExtensionFromNamestringPredInArgToNamestringPredInArg territoryOf placeName_Standard 1 #$namestring 2)
means that where both of the following hold: 
   (territoryOf GEO-AGENT TERRITORY)

   (placeName_Standard GEO-AGENT NAME),
one is licensed to extend the use of NAME to refer to TERRITORY via 
   (nameString TERRITORY NAME).
See also predicateLicensesSenseExtensionFromPOSInArgToPOSInArg, which operates in a way similar to this predicate, but pertains to the sense extension of instances of LexicalWord.
label: Predicate Licenses Sense Extension From Namestring Pred In Arg To Namestring Pred In Arg
predicateLicensesSenseExtensionFromNamestringPredInArgToNamestringPredInArg

comment: An assertion of the form (sitServesSpecificationForAgents SIT SPEC AGENT) is used to relate an instance of Situation SIT to an instance of NormativeSpecification and an instance of Agent_Generic. Instances of NormativeSpecification describe types of situations that some agents want to come about, and agents can have a variety of attitudes towards a NormativeSpecification. The meaning of the initial assertion is that SIT helps, in a very generic sense, AGENT with regard to bringing about SPEC. As an example, consider a person who wants to be a millionaire (where we represent that desire as an instance of NormativeSpecification), if that person won a hundred thousand dollars in a lottery then that winning event would bear the relation sitServesSpecificationForAgents to that NormativeSpecification and that person. AGENT need not have any awareness of SIT.
label: Sit Serves Specification For Agents
sitServesSpecificationForAgents

comment: (exportThroughAmountDuring REGION PRODUCT-TYPE PT THING AMOUNT) means that the ScalarInterval AMOUNT is a measure of the amount of instances of the ProductType PRODUCT-TYPE exported by the GeographicalRegion REGION through the instance of PartiallyTangible PT (on their way to their destination) during the temporal extent of the TemporalThing THING. PT might, in the case of oil exports, for instance, be a GeographicalRegion or a Pipeline. THING will often be a calendar time period; but it may also be, for instance, a particular Event. In the case of automobile exports, for example, AMOUNT might be an Integer indicating the number of cars exported. In the case of oil exports, AMOUNT might be a Volume (a number of barrels) indicating the total quantity of oil exported (by REGION through PT), or it might be an instance of MonetaryValue indicating the monetary value of all the oil exported. Alternatively, AMOUNT might be a Rate, characterizing the average rate of export of instances of PRODUCT-TYPE by REGION through PT during the temporal extent of THING. Oil exports, for example, might be expressed in terms of so many million barrels per day or in terms of so many dollars per day (again, indicating the monetary value of the oil).
label: Export Through Amount During
exportThroughAmountDuring

comment: This predicate relates a military unit type to its typical march speed over unrestricted, restricted, or severely restricted terrain. More precisely, (marchSpeedOfUnitTypeOnTerrain SPEED UNIT_TYPE TERRAIN_RESTRICTION) means that military vehicle of type UNIT_TYPE typically move at rate SPEED over terrain with movement restriction TERRAIN_RESTRICTION. See also TerrainTypeByTrafficabilityLevel.
Mx4rwLSVCpwpEbGdrcN5Y29ycA: marching speeds of unit type with respect to terrain
label: marching speed of unit type with respect to terrain
marchSpeedOfUnitTypeOnTerrain

comment: (typeImmediateRisk SIT-TYPE1 ROLE1 SIT-TYPE2 ROLE2) means that if an object OBJ plays ROLE1 in an instance of SIT-TYPE1, then OBJ is at immediate risk for playing the role ROLE2 in an instance of SIT-TYPE2. typeImmediateRisk

comment: (permitted_SitRelationToSitType SIT PRED PERMITTED-TYPE) means that, in some specified CodeOfConduct, it is permissible that there be an instance of PERMITTED-TYPE such that (PRED SIT PERMITTED-INS). The CodeOfConduct which grants this permission should be specified by assertion or rule microtheory. Note that 'permitted' here is meant only in the weak sense that the relationship is not prohibited. In particular, (permitted_SitRelationToSitType SIT PRED TYPE) is consistent with such a relationship being required, cf., oughtToBe_SitRelationToSitType.

permitted-SitRelationToSitType

nthFiscalQuarterOfFiscalYear

comment:
A binary Quantifier that corresponds to the standard universal quantifier of predicate calculus. The relation forAll takes as its arguments a variable (#$ELVariable) and a sentence (#$ELSentence-Assertible) in which, typically, that variable occurs free. A closed formula (see CycLClosedFormula) of the form (forAll VAR SENT) is a "universally quantified" sentence that states (roughly) that every thing in the universe of discourse satisfies SENT. For example, 

  (forAll ?THING (isa ?THING Individual))

means that everything is an individual. And the sentence 

  (forAll ?X
    (implies
      (isa ?X Cat)
      (eatsWillingly ?X Grass_Plant)))

means that all cats eat grass.

A more precise definition of forAll is as follows. Any occurence of VAR that is free in SENT is bound in (forAll VAR SENT). If VAR is the only variable free in SENT, then (forAll VAR SENT) is a closed sentence that is true if and only if every thing that meets all of the argument-type constraints (see ArgTypePredicate) to which the position(s) in SENT occupied by VAR is (are) subject to satisfies SENT. If the variable VAR does _not_ occur free in SENT, then (forAll VAR SENT) is equivalent to SENT (and the 'forAll' is said to be "vacuous"). If variables other than VAR occur free in SENT, then (forAll VAR SENT) is an open sentence in which those other variables are still free.

Note that, for the sake of convenience and readability, universally quantified assertions (i.e. "rules") in the Cyc Knowledge Base appear in the KB browser -- and may be asserted to the KB -- without (any of) their initial 'forAll's. Such assertions are considered to be "implicitly quantified": they are interpreted by the system just as if their initial quantifiers were explicitly present. Thus the above sentence about cats would actually appear in the KB as: 

  (implies
    (isa ?X Cat)
    (eatsWillingly ?X Grass_Plant)) .

Note also that certain RuleMacroPredicates (e.g. those with 'All' in their names) can be used to abbreviate universally quantified sentences. Thus the same statement about cats can be even more tersely expressed with the atomic sentence 

  (relationAllInstance eatsWillingly Cat Grass_Plant) .

Cf. the existential quantifier thereExists.
label: For All
forAll
Common Relation
commonRelation
comment: (commonRelation RELN) means that RELN is a very commonly used relationship in all of the Cyc contexts which access the context in which the formula is asserted.

A KEFacilitationPredicate and RuleMacroPredicate. (keStrongSuggestionPreds_InsOfType COL BINPRED TYPE) means that for every known (i.e. Cyc-reified) instance INST of COL, it is strongly suggested that there be some reified instance INS-TYPE of TYPE such that (BINPRED INST INS-TYPE) is known in the Knowledge Base.
label: Ke Strong Suggestion Preds Ins Of Type
keStrongSuggestionPreds-InsOfType
Pragmatically Acceptable
pragmaticallyAcceptable
comment: pragmaticallyAcceptable is a natural-language-based predicate that applies to a single pragmatic attribute argument. (pragmaticallyAcceptable ATTR) means that ATTR is an acceptable pragmatic attribute for speech in the current dialog context, i.e. that the addressee should not be shocked or surprised if the speaker uses speech characterized by ATTR. It is notAssertible, because its value depends on the current dialog context.

This predicate allows us to relativize a subject's discomfort with respect to a particular symptom or ailment condition. (relativeIntensityOfCondition COND BLO DIS-LEVEL) means that BLO has the level of discomfort DIS-LEVEL as a result of COND. Note that (relativeIntensityOfCondition COND BLO DIS-LEVEL) implies that the agent has the condition COND.
label: relative intensity of a condition
relativeIntensityOfCondition

comment: (wordForms WORD PRED STRING) states that STRING is a PRED form of WORD in the current context, where PRED is an instance of SpeechPartPredicate. For instance, in the EnglishMt and its spec-Mts, (wordForms #$Ox-TheWord plural "oxen"); (wordForms #$Walk-TheWord pastTense_Universal "walked"). The code support for this predicate looks up irregular forms stated in the KB -- such as (plural #$Ox-TheWord "oxen") -- and generates regular forms such as "walked", which need not be stated in the KB.
label: Word Forms (language-describing predicate)
wordForms

comment:
A ternary MetaRelation predicate that relates a Collection to an integer (representing an argument-place) to a Relation such that some instance of the collection is an admittedArgument (q.v.) to the specified argument-place of the relation. (admittedSomeArgument COL ARGNUM RELN) means there is at least one instance of COL that satisfies all of the (single-argument) argument-type constraints (see ArgIsaPredicate and ArgGenlPredicate) for the ARGNUMth argument position of RELN.

For example, (admittedSomeArgument Animal 2 spouse) and (admittedSomeArgument ExistingObjectType 1 JuvenileFn) both hold.

See also the more specialized predicate admittedAllArgument.
label: Admitted Some Argument
admittedSomeArgument

comment: (resultGenlArgArgIsa FUNCTION ARG-NUM ARGISA-NUM) says that any CycLNonAtomicTerm NAT built from the CollectionDenotingFunction FUNCTION will be a specialization of TYPE, where (argIsa RELN ARGISA-NUM TYPE) and (argN RELN ARG-NUM NAT). So, for example, (resultGenlArgArgIsa SubcollectionOfWithRelationToFn 2 1) entails that (genls (SubcollectionOfWithRelationToFn Thing likesAsFriend FRED) PerceptualAgent), since (argIsa likesAsFriend 1 PerceptualAgent) and likesAsFriend appears as the 2nd argument to the NART.
label: Result Genl Arg Arg Isa
resultGenlArgArgIsa

comment: (successorInPosition SUCCESSOR PREDECESSOR POSITION POLITY) means that SUCCESSOR is the person who holds POSITION in the GeopoliticalEntity, POLITY, immediately after PREDECESSOR ceased holding that same position. Since a person can hold a position intermittently, with someone else holding it in between, none of the arguments are SingleEntry.
label: Successor In Position
successorInPosition

comment: (saleToFractionDuring PT1 PRODUCT-TYPE PT2 THING NR) means that NR is the quotient of the monetary value of sales of the ProductType PRODUCT-TYPE by the instance of PartiallyTangible PT1 to the instance of PartiallyTangible PT2 during the temporal extent of the TemporalThing THING (as dividend) and the monetary value of all sales of PRODUCT-TYPE by PT1 during the temporal extent of THING (as divisor). PT1 might, for example, be a Country or a Business; and likewise for PT2. THING will often be a calendar time period; but it may also be, for instance, a particular Event. For example, to express the fact that in January of 1997 Japan accounted for 35 percent of Iran's sales of crude oil, we can say (saleToFractionDuring Iran Petroleum_CrudeOil Japan (MonthFn January (YearFn 1997)) (Percent 35)).
label: Sale To Fraction During
saleToFractionDuring

comment: (xmlExpansionTypeAttributeValue PROGRAM THING STRING) identifies THING as the object denoted by the attribute value STRING in the computer program PROGRAM.
label: Xml Expansion Type Attribute Value
xmlExpansionTypeAttributeValue

comment: There exists some instance of Event, E, during which a change is made to the mt ARG1.  The following relationship holds: ARG2(E ARG3).
label: Mt Change Event Relative Time
mtChangeEventRelativeTime

comment: The predicate (textConformsToGrammar STRING GRAMMAR SYSTEM) relates a specific text STRING to a specific FormalGrammar_CW GRAMMAR and claims that STRING conforms to all the constraints of GRAMMAR as defined in the SyntaxSpecificationSystem SYSTEM. The text STRING is therefore 'grammatical' according to the specifications in GRAMMAR, if SYSTEM is followed. SYSTEM often will have a specific parsing program associated with it to test whether STRING really does conform to GRAMMAR.
label: Text Conforms To Grammar
textConformsToGrammar

comment: (sensoryResponse EVT ROLE QUANT) means that a PerceptualAgent who participates in the PhysicalEvent EVT in the manner ROLE has a quantity of the SensoryQuantity QUANT. For example, if TOUCH is a touching-something-very-cold action, then (sensoryResponse TOUCH doneBy (PositiveAmountFn LevelOfDiscomfort)) is true --- i.e., whoever does that touching action is likely to feel some discomfort.
label: sensory response
sensoryResponse

comment: (withinRangeForEventType OBJECT1 OBJECT2 SITTYPE) means that OBJECT1 is able to affect OBJECT2 in some SITTYPE. For instance, if #$AlbertGore is five meters away from GeorgeWBush, then (withinRangeForEventType #$AlbertGore GeorgeWBush SpokenCommunicating) but not (withinRangeForEventType #$AlbertGore GeorgeWBush ShakingHands). Different kinds of actions have different ranges, and this predicate can be used to express the conditions for being able to do something to something else via different kinds of actions.
label: Within Range For Event Type
withinRangeForEventType

comment: (objectSecureToDegreeAgainstRoleInType OBJECT SECURITY-LEVEL SITUATION-TYPE ROLE) means that the instance OBJECT of SomethingExisting is secure to degree SECURITY-LEVEL against situations of type SITUATION-TYPE in which OBJECT plays the role ROLE.
label: Object Secure To Degree Against Role In Type
objectSecureToDegreeAgainstRoleInType

comment: The value ARG2 is a candidate interpretation of ARG1 when ARG3 has the value ARG4.
label: Field Dependent Coded Values
fieldDependentCodedValues

comment: (increasesCausallyOverPeriod EVENT THING SLOT PERIOD) means that EVENT causes the value of the predicate SLOT applied to THING to be greater immediately after (STIF q.v.) PERIOD than it was immediately before (STIB q.v.) PERIOD. PERIOD must start no earlier than EVENT starts in order to prevent effects preceeding their causes. If PERIOD ends before EVENT, it still must be the case that the value of SLOT applied to THING must be greater immediately following EVENT than it was immediately before EVENT. Like with increasesImmediately, the increase need not be monotonic. This predicate is agnostic as to whether the increase occurs during EVENT or after it. See #$NoteAboutQuantityChangePredicates for a map of related predicates.
label: Increases Causally Over Period
increasesCausallyOverPeriod

comment: Instances of ARG1, when sold by ARG2, are sold at the cost rate of ARG3. So if HEB sells Bananas for $0.49 per pound, (costRateForType Banana-TheFruit HEB (DollarsPerPound 0.49)). Entries on the instance-level slot costRate can be inferred from costRateForType entries.
label: Cost Rate For Type
costRateForType

irExpansionSentencesForTermGivenVerbSem

rivalsWRT

countryPassportIDIssuedToPerson

comment: A QuintaryPredicate used to state exceptions to the applicabilty of transitiveViaArgInverse assertions. (transitiveViaArgInverseExceptions THING FORMULA PRED BINPRED N) means that the Nth argument position of PRED is "transitive" with respect to the inverse of BINPRED except when THING (or a constant that stands in the inverse of BINPRED to THING) occurs as the Nth argument to PRED in a GAF whose arguments are otherwise identical to those of FORMULA. For example, (transitiveViaArgInverseExceptions FlightlessBird (#$typeBehaviorCapable Bird Flying_FlappingWings doneBy) #$typeBehaviorCapable genls 1) means that (#$typeBehaviorCapable COLL Flying_FlappingWings doneBy) is true for all specializations of COLL except for those specializations of COLL that are also specializations of FlightlessBird. See also transitiveViaArgExceptions.
label: Transitive Via Arg Inverse Exceptions
transitiveViaArgInverseExceptions

comment: (softwareParameterRangeInSpecification SPEC PARAM VAL1 VAL2) states that, according to the ProgramSpecification SPEC, the SoftwareParameter PARAM is greater than VAL1 and lesser than VAL2.

softwareParameterRangeInSpecification

comment: (derivedFromCompounds DERIVED-WORD WORD1 WORD2) means that DERIVED-WORD is a compound word derived from the two compounds WORD1 and WORD2.

derivedFromCompounds

comment:
A ternary instance of InterArgEqualsIsaPredicate (q.v.). (interArgEqualsIsa1_2 RELN INDEPENDENT-ARG DEPENDENT-ARG-COL) means that, when INDEPENDENT-ARG appears as the first argument to RELN, a necessary condition for semantic well-formedness is that the second argument must be an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. That is, (RELN INDEPENDENT-ARG ARG2 ...) is semantically well-formed only if ARG2 is an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. For example, (interArgEqualsIsa1_2 softwareParameterValueInSpecification InferenceSentenceParameter CycLSentence_Assertible) means that (softwareParameterValueInSpecification InferenceSentenceParameter VALUE SPEC) is semantically well-formed only if VALUE is an instance of CycLSentence_Assertible.

For an explanation of semantic well-formedness, see CycLExpression_Assertible and its direct specializations. See interArgEqualsIsa for a similar but more general predicate that is quintary, allowing the user to specify the positions of the independent and dependent arguments.
label: Inter Arg Equals Isa 1 2
interArgEqualsIsa1-2

comment:
A TernaryPredicate that relates two quoted instances of CycLPropositionalSentence to an instance of Likelihood_QuantityType. (conditionalLikelihood HYPOTHESIS EVIDENCE LIKELIHOOD) means that the likelihood (in the current context) that HYPOTHESIS holds given only the information that EVIDENCE holds is LIKELIHOOD.

For example, 

(conditionalLikelihood
  (fanOf GeorgeWBush WillieNelson)
  (originallyFromRegion GeorgeWBush Texas_State)
  (MediumToVeryHighAmountFn Likelihood_QuantityType))
means that the likelihood that George W. Bush is a fan of Willie Nelson, given only the information that he (Bush) is originally from Texas, is medium to very high,

This predicate is good for expressing vague or "generic" probabilities (though precise probabilities can be expressed with it, using NumericLikelihoodFn). To express precise (numeric) probabilities, it is better to use conditionalProbability.
label: Conditional Likelihood
conditionalLikelihood
Sks Modifiable
sksModifiable
comment: (sksModifiable SKS) means that the contents of the structured knowledge source SKS is modifiable through Cyc. The extent of this predicate is used in SKSI HL storage module generation, to decide whether HL storage modules should be generated for a given external knowledge source.

A sentence of the form (functionConstantVectorDuringSit FUNCTION VALUE SIT) means that the PhysicalQuantityOrVectorFunction_ConstantValue denotes only the PhysicalQuantity VECTOR relative to PhysicalSituation SIT.

functionConstantQuantityDuringSit

comment: ARG1 will have an allergic reaction whenever participating in instances of situation type ARG2 with instances of ARG3.

allergicTo

label: Equals Constraint For NCR
equalsConstraintForNCR
Post Op Bld Prod Units Of Type
postOpBldProdUnitsOfType

Any process associated with S-PROGRAM that is running on the network of MACHINE is running within parameters delineated by CONFIG.

argIsaWRTDeterminationArgIsaMinColls

comment: (weightOnPlanet OBJECT PLANET WEIGHT) means that OBJECT weighs approximately WEIGHT on the surface of PLANET.

weightOnPlanet

comment: A predicate for documenting decision margins in the UnitedStatesSupremeCourt. Where CASE is a CaseHeardByTheSupremeCourt, (majorityInCase CASE N M) means that in CASE, N justices constituted the majority, and M justices constituted the minority.
label: Majority In Case
majorityInCase

comment:
(cotemporalSubSituationTypes SIT-TYPE SUBSIT-TYPE1 SUBSIT-TYPE2) means that in any instance SIT of SIT-TYPE (a specialization of Situation), if instances SIT1 and SIT2 of SUBSIT-TYPE1 and SUBSIT-TYPE2 occur as subsituations, then SIT1 and SIT2 are cotemporal.

Note that (cotemporalSubSituationTypes SIT-TYPE SUBSIT-TYPE1 SUBSIT-TYPE2) does not imply that instances of SUBSIT-TYPE1 or SUBSIT-TYPE2 occur as subsituations of every instance of SIT-TYPE, since SUBSIT-TYPE1 and SUBSIT-TYPE2 may be merely candidate subsituation types of SIT-TYPE (see candidateProperSubSituationTypes).
label: Cotemporal Sub Situation Types
cotemporalSubSituationTypes

comment: (violators x y z) denotes agent x violated role z in mt y.
label: Violators
violators

comment: A ternary predicate that relates an instance of non-negative integer (representing an argument position) to two instances of CycL formula. (differsOnlyInArg FORMULA-1 FORMULA-2 N) means that FORMULA-1 and FORMULA-2 are the same length, that the arguments in every argument position (including 0, when N is not equal to 0) other than the Nth are the same in the two formulas, and that the two formulas differ in the Nth argument position. For example, the sentence `(differsOnlyInArg (genls Dog Mammal) (genls Cat Mammal) 1)' holds. Note that differsOnlyInArg's first and second argument-places are both "quoted" (see quotedArgument); thus in the context of the above differsOnlyInArg sentence the constituent sentence `(genls Dog Mammal)' denotes _itself_ and similarly for the constituent sentence `(genls Cat Mammal)'.
label: Differs Only In Arg
differsOnlyInArg

comment: (pathBetweenInSystem PATH X Y SYS) means that PATH is a path in the system SYS, and X and Y are the end points (in the PathSystem) of PATH. If PATH is a "link" of the system (see linkInSystem), (pathBetweenInSystem PATH X Y SYS) iff (linkBetweenInSystem PATH X Y SYS). Note that there can be multiple paths in SYS between the same two points in SYS (which may or may not be "nodes" in SYS; see nodeInSystem). See also pathBetween when no PathSystem is specified.
label: path between in system
pathBetweenInSystem
Complete Extent Enumerable Via Backchain
completeExtentEnumerableViaBackchain
comment: A unary #$InferenceCompletenessPredicate and a specialization of minimizeExtent (qq.v.) that applies to predicates whose entire extents can be enumerated by reference to the transformation rules currently asserted on it. For example, #$surgicalIncisionEmployed is completeExtentEnumerableViaBackchain in the context of certain medical domain microtheories because the pair of rules on it are sufficient to completely generate its entire extent within those microtheories.

In some cases where it is necessary to articulate a preliminary mapping of a distributed database schema, it is necessary to map CycL constants to entities represented in so-called list objects which have been created for purposes of streamlining the database. In these cases, multiple fields in the list object jointly comprise a single term that must be mapped to some term in the CycL vocabulary. overlappingListFields enables us to do this. Where LIST_STRINGS is a list comprised of CharacterStrings, (synonymousListFields LIST_STRINGS INFO_SOURCE CYC_TERM) means that CYC_TERM overlaps semantically with the term denoted by the list of character strings that appear on one row of a list object in the database schema INFO_SOURCE.
label: Overlapping List Fields
overlappingListFields

comment: (thirdVADInsertForOperationWithDeviceAndPatientAtDate OP INSERT DEVICE PATIENT DATE) means that INSERT is the third cardiac device insertion perfomed on PATIENT at DATE during the same hospitalization as the operation OP (which is also performed on PATIENT).
label: Third VAD Insert For Operation With Device And Patient At Date
thirdVADInsertForOperationWithDeviceAndPatientAtDate

comment: (kePrecisionSuggestionByTypeRestriction_Binary BROADP NARROWP COL1 COL2) indicates that whenever [1] (BROADP INS1 INS2) is known and [2] COL1, COL2 are respectively the 1st and 2nd argument type constraint on NARROWP and [3] INS1, INS2 are instances of COL1, COL2 resp., then (NARROWP INS1 INS2) is likely to be true. This predicate is used to suggest plausible specializations to ke'rs via the predicate strengthener. If one of the Collection arguments is irrelevant to the suggested restriction, use the arg type constraint for BROADP in that position. E.g. if (kePrecisionSuggestionByTypeRestriction_Binary BROADP NARROWP BROAD_COL1 COL2) and (arg1Isa BROADP BROAD_COL1), then that collection is ignored by the strengthener.
label: Ke Precision Suggestion By Type Restriction Binary
kePrecisionSuggestionByTypeRestriction-Binary

comment: (resultArgIsa FUNCTION INTEGER COLLECTION) means that the result of applying the instance of PredicateDenotingFunction FUNCTION to a series of arguments for which FUNCTION is defined will result in an instance PRED of Predicate such that (argIsa PRED INTEGER COLLECTION).
label: Result Arg Isa
resultArgIsa

comment: This predicate relates a pair of spatial things and a number representing a degree of proximity between them. (nearToDegree OBJ1 OBJ2 N) means that the distanceBetween OBJ1 and OBJ2 is not greater than N times the largest dimension of the smaller of OBJ1 and OBJ2 (where the 'smaller object' is the one having the smaller largest dimension). Note that if A is equidistant from B and C, it may be the case that (nearToDegree A B NUM) but not (nearToDegree A C NUM) if C is smaller than B. Also note that if (nearToDegree OBJ1 OBJ2 NUM) and NUM2 is larger than NUM, then (nearToDegree OBJ1 OBJ2 NUM2). If the third argument is 0, the objects are touching (see touches) each other. Other predicates that specify nearness relations are near, nearRelativeTo, nearForRolesInEventType, nearnessForRolesInEventType.
label: Near To Degree
nearToDegree

comment: This predicate relates agents to types of situations that the agent has plans to actualize. (goalSitRole AGENT SITUATION ROLE) means that AGENT will take steps towards actualizing some instance of SITUATION and play the role ROLE in the situation. See also goals and goalCategoryForAgent.
label: Goal Sit Role
goalSitRole

comment: (expectedResponseToEventType AGT TYPE RESPONSE-TYPE ROLE) says that in response to an instance of TYPE, AGT is expected to play the role ROLE in an instance of RESPONSE-TYPE. More formally, (expected_ToBe (thereExists ?RESPONSE-INS (and (isa ?RESPONSE-INS RESPONSE-TYPE) (ROLE ?RESPONSE-INS AGT)))). This predicate is particularly useful in representing expectations to responses to executions of plans (See Plan_ExpectedSituationType).
label: expected response
expectedResponseToEventType

comment: An assertion of the form (agentScoresForGame AGENT SCORE GAME) means that the Agent_Generic AGENT has been a player in some instantiation of the Game GAME and received a final score of SCORE.
label: Agent Scores For Game
agentScoresForGame

comment: (percentBornIn PLACE-OF-RESIDENCE PLACE-OF-BIRTH PERCENT) means that PERCENT of the residents of PLACE-OF-RESIDENCE were born in PLACE-OF-BIRTH
label: Percent Born In
percentBornIn

comment: Agent A transports thing B from some location C to some location  D.
label: Transports From To
transportsFromTo

comment: (templateTopicAssertion TOPIC FORMULA POS) means that, when dealing with TOPIC, the user can assume that FORMULA is already known to be true. POS denotes the argument position in FORMULA that should be replaced by the focal term for the topic (see templateTypeForFocalTermType). For example, if (templateTypeForFocalTermType Person PersonTopicType) then Cyc should know that (isa X Person), where X should be replaced by the appropriate instance of Person. Therefore, (templateTopicAssertion PersonTopicType (isa X Person) (FormulaArgPositionFn 1)). Note that the above example is incorporated in a rule, so it is unnecessary to assert, but templateTopicAssertion can also be used for other assertions, e.g. for lexical information.
label: Template Topic Assertion
templateTopicAssertion

comment: (ruleTrivialForJustificationParaphrase RULE) means that when RULE is used in a transformation proof, a paraphrase of that proof should explicitly mention RULE, and that paraphrase should print the rule in a manner that emphasizes the rule (e.g by printing the rule in bold or italic).
label: Rule Highly Relevant For Justification Paraphrase
ruleHighlyRelevantForJustificationParaphrase
subPropertyOf: Sentence Highly Relevant For Justification Paraphrase

comment: (consumptionQuotaDuring PT PRODUCT-TYPE THING AMOUNT) means that the NonNegativeScalarInterval AMOUNT is a measure of the consumption quota (or ration) of instances of the ProductType PRODUCT-TYPE for the instance of PartiallyTangible PT during the temporal extent of the TemporalThing THING. (Of course, the existence of consumption quotas is the exception rather than the rule.) PT might, for example, be a Country, a Business, or a household (CohabitationUnit). THING will often be a calendar time period; but it may also be, for instance, a particular Event.
label: Consumption Quota During
consumptionQuotaDuring

comment:
(negationPredsWRTArgs PRED-1 PRED-2 LIST) means that the two predicates PRED-1 and PRED-2 stand in a negationPreds -like relation to each other with respect to a specified correlation among their argument-places. The two predicates, though both of fixed arity (see FixedArityRelation), might have identical or different arity; in the latter case, PRED-1's arity is required to be higher than that of PRED-2. The argument-place correlation between PRED-1 and PRED-2 is encoded in LIST, a list of non-negative integers whose length is equal to the arity of PRED-2. The position of an integer within the list represents that same argument-position within PRED-2, while the size of the integer represents the corresponding argument-position within PRED-1.

Thus (negationPredsWRTArgs PRED-1 PRED-2 LIST) means that whenever PRED-1 holds of a given argument sequence SEQUENCE-1, then negationPreds holds of the sequence SEQUENCE-2, defined as follows: Where the Ith item in LIST is the integer N, the Ith item if SEQUENCE-2 is the same as the Nth item in SEQUENCE-1. For example, 

  (negationPredsWRTArgs touchesWith spatiallySeparated (TheList 3 2))
entails 
  (not
    (and
      (touchesWith #$MingXu Steak8 Fork25)
      (spatiallySeparated Fork25 Steak8))).
label: Negation Preds WRT Args
negationPredsWRTArgs

comment: This predicate relates types of events and is intended to show a possible constraint on the script type, i.e. (nextSubeventTypeInScript STYPE1 STYPE2 STYPE3) means that if an event of SUBTYPE3 has a subevent of STYPE1 it may be followed by an event of type STYPE2, but may not necessarily be followed by such an event.
label: Next Subevent Type In Script
nextSubeventTypeInScript

comment: (rdfGraphLinksToNamespaceVia GRAPH NAMESPACE PROPERTY) means that GRAPH contains triples relating resources via PROPERTY to resources identified using URIs that extend NAMESPACE.
label: Rdf Graph Links To Namespace Via
rdfGraphLinksToNamespaceVia

comment: (nodeCutSetBetweenInSystem SET X Y SYS) means that SET is a node-cut-set in the ConnectedPathSystem SYS, and that the points X and Y in SYS are disconnected in the subsystem of SYS obtained by cutting all nodes in SET from SYS. More strictly, (nodeCutSetBetweenInSystem SET X Y SYS) is true if and only if (nodeCutSetInSystem SET SYS) is true and (connectedInSystem X Y (LinksCut_SubSystemFn SYS SET)) is false.
label: Node Cut Set Between In System
nodeCutSetBetweenInSystem

comment: (argNotIsa REL N COL) means that nothing given as the Nth argument to the Relation REL may be known to be an element of the Collection COL. It is not necessary to prove that it is not an element of that collection.
label: Arg Not Isa
argNotIsa

comment: An instance of TernaryPredicate, used to describe the surface level of the ground on each of the four 'sides' of a GeographicalRegion. (The number 4 is a simplifying assumption used to make knowledge aquisition and representation easier.) (regionTypeHasSurfaceLevelInNumberOfDirections REGION-TYPE LEVEL NUM-SIDES) means that NUM-SIDES of REGION-TYPE have are LEVEL. For example, (regionTypeHasSurfaceLevelInNumberOfDirections Hill TerrainLowGround 4) means that hills have low ground in (all) four directions. To specify how many sides that share this ground level are adjacent, use regionTypeHasSurfaceLevelInNumberOfAdjacentDirections. Note that this predicate not only oversimplifies the number of sides of a type of terrain, but also ignores the point of view and the slope. For example, a hill has low ground on all sides from the point of view of the hilltop, but not from the point of view of the bottom of the hill. This predicate expects that one is refering to the 'most interesting' part of the terrain feature (eg the hilltop of a hill, the low middle part of a valley, the seat part of a saddle, etc.). To also specify the point of view and to be more specific about slopes, see #$regionTypeSlopeOfSidesFromPoint and #$regionTypeSlopeOfAdjacentSidesFromPoint. To specify slopes at an instance level, see #$regionSlopeOfSidesFromPoint and #$regionSlopeOfAdjacentSidesFromPoint.
label: Region Type Has Surface Level In Number Of Directions
regionTypeHasSurfaceLevelInNumberOfDirections

comment: A predicate relating an individual thing, such as a ModernMilitaryUnit_Deployable or a piece of equipment, to the primary military role it is intended to play. For example, (primaryFunction_Military MORTARUNIT01 #$IndirectFire-MilitaryFundamental performedBy) means that the individual unit MORTARUNIT001 is primarily intended to provide fire support. Although MORTARUNIT01 may also be able to engage in other activities, those for which primaryFunction-Military assertions appear are those for which it is most optimized, and are the most probable uses of the unit when it appears in military operations.
label: primary military function
primaryFunction-Military

comment: A sentence of the for (pointIsOriginForAssociatedCoordinateSystem POINT SIT SYSTEM) means that the Point POINT is, relative to a particular context, corresponds to the origin of the CoordinateSystem SYSTEM when SYSTEM is used for representing the constituents of the PhysicalSituation SIT.
label: Point Is Origin For Associated Coordinate System
pointIsOriginForAssociatedCoordinateSystem

comment: A ternary instance of InterArgIsaPredicate (q.v.). (interArgIsa5_3 RELN INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL DEPENDENT-ARG-COL) means that, when an instance of INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL appears as the fifth argument to RELN, a necessary condition for semantic well-formedness is that the third argument must be an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. That is, if ARG-INST is an instance of INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL, then (RELN ARG1 ARG2 ARG3 ARG4 INST ... ARGN) is semantically well-formed only if ARG3 is an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. For an explanation of semantic well-formedness, see CycLExpression_Assertible and its direct specializations.
label: Inter Arg Isa 5 3
interArgIsa5-3

comment: An assertion of the form (genlSituationTypesWRTRolePlayersOfType_SitType SITTYPE1 TYPE1 SITTYPE2 TYPE2 ROLE) means that SITTYPE1 is a more specific version of SITTYPE2 in terms of the type of actors which will play ROLE in instances of SITTYPE1. Specifically, it means that in instances of SITTYPE1, the actors of TYPE2 which play ROLE in the instance of SITTYPE1 will be instances of the more specific type TYPE1.
label: Genl Situation Types WRT Role Players Of Type Sit Type
genlSituationTypesWRTRolePlayersOfType-SitType

comment: A predicate which relates a place name (instance of USBGNPlaceName) assigned by the USBoardOnGeographicNames (BGN) with a string representation of the name and the type of the name string, where the type is either full name, full name no diacritics, short form, generic, and sort. (usbgnPlaceNameStringOfType PLACE-NAME STRING TYPE) means that STRING is a string representation of PLACE-NAME of type TYPE.
label: Usbgn Place Name String Of Type
usbgnPlaceNameStringOfType

comment: (patientAgeDuringMedicalEvent PAT EVT TIME-QUANT) means that the MedicalPatient PAT is of the age TIME-QUANT at the time of the start of the event EVT.
label: years old during
patientAgeDuringMedicalEvent

comment: ARG1 was assigned a unique id ARG2 by ARG3 for transactions of type ARG4 where (ARG5 ARG1 ARG3). ARG5 is an actor slot. For example, (transactionID DexterOrderingSocksFromLandsEnd 1234 LandsEnd RequestingToMakeAPurchase recipient) means that LandsEnd assigned the event DexterOrderingSocksFromLandsEnd an id, 1234, which is unique for the instances of RequestingToMakeAPurchase in which LandsEnd is the recipient
label: Transaction ID
transactionID

comment: A ternary IntangibleObjectRelatingPredicate that holds among Integers only. (integerBetween LOW MED HIGH) means that HIGH is greaterThanOrEqualTo MED, and MED is greaterThanOrEqualTo LOW.
label: Integer Between
integerBetween

comment: An assertion of the form (populationGrowthRateDuring PLACE ORG-TYPE PERCENT DATE) states that measurements made of the population of OrganismClassificationType ORG-TYPE for the Date DATE indicate that the GeographicalRegion PLACE experienced a PERCENT rate of growth in that population. For example, an assertion of the form (populationGrowthRateDuring Syria HomoSapiens (#$PercentFn 1) (YearFn 2005)) says that records indicate that the human population of Syria grew by 1% during 2005. This represents a measurement and estimate.
label: Population Growth Rate During
populationGrowthRateDuring

comment: An assertion of the form (hasTasksWRTGoal AGENT TASK GOAL) asserts that the IntelligentAgent AGENT is planning to perform an instance of TASK, some type of PurposefulAction, as a step towards achieving the TaskState GOAL to which AGENT bears either the relation hasGoals or #$hasDependentGoalsWRTGoal (for the later, GOAL would fill the second argument position).
label: Has Tasks WRT Goal
hasTasksWRTGoal

comment: The profit made by this agent in this transaction
label: Profit (ternary predicate)
profit

comment: The corresponding predicate of NthAppealOfCaseFn.
label: Nth Appeal Of Case
nthAppealOfCase

comment: (eventTypeSuggestsOccurrenceOfIn FLAG NONOBVIOUS MAIN) means that in events of type MAIN, an event of type FLAG provides evidence that an event of type NONOBVIOUS has occurred. For instance, (eventTypeSuggestsOccurrenceOfIn SirenSounding CarAccident Traffic) means that if a siren sounding occurs during a traffic event an observer's evidence for the existence of a CarAccident is increased.
label: Event Type Suggests Occurrence Of In
eventTypeSuggestsOccurrenceOfIn

comment: (expectedTenureInRank COUNTRY BOS ECHELON RANK DURATION) means that an agent who holds RANK in a military unit of the branch-of-service BOS with sovereignAllegianceOfOrg COUNTRY and echelonOfUnit ECHELON is expected to hold that RANK for DURATION.
label: expected tenure in rank
expectedTenureInRank

comment: A TernaryPredicate. (editionOfPeriodicalByDate SERIES DATE ISSUE) means that ISSUE is the PeriodicalIssue of the PeriodicalSeries SERIES for the Date DATE. This is the predicate corresponding to EditionFn (q.v.).
label: Edition Of Periodical By Date
editionOfPeriodicalByDate

comment: The direction of ARG1 is at an angle of ARG3 with respect to ARG2.  ARG2 could be any vector (e.g. the rectilinear trajectory of another object).
label: Direction Relative To Axis
directionRelativeToAxis

comment: An instance of InterArgFormatPredicate (q.v.). (interArgFormat3_3 PRED COL FORMAT) means that FORMAT is a Format (q.v.) requirement for the third argument-place of PRED when PRED's third argument is an instance of COL. That is, with respect to a sentence of the form (PRED ARG1 ARG2 ARG3 ... ARGN) in which ARG3 is an instance of COL, PRED's arg3 position (i.e. the position occupied by the metavariable `ARG3' in the preceding sentence-form) is subject to FORMAT. See Format and its instances for further explanation. Note that interArgFormat3_3 is one of several "degenerate-case" inter-argument format predicates, in which the specified condition and the corresponding format constraint both have to do with the _same_ argument-place of a given predicate.
label: Inter Arg Format 3 3
interArgFormat3-3

comment: (streetIntersectionOf XING STREET AVENUE) means that XING is an intersection of STREET and AVENUE. This predicate is not functional in its first argument because (although uncommon) it is possible for two streets to intersect with each other in more than one place. Nor is it functional in its second or third arguments. For example, if three streets all intersect at XING, then XING is the intersection of any two of them.
label: Street Intersection Of
streetIntersectionOf

comment: (priceFloor MARKET PRODUCT PRICE) means that the instance PRICE of MonetaryValue has been imposed as the minimum price at which PRODUCT may be sold in MARKET.
label: price floor
priceFloor

comment: (mostRecentReferenceToWRTPeg REF EXPR-REF EXPR-NEW) means that the LinguisticExpressionPeg EXPR-REF is the most recent expression to reference the DiscourseReferentPeg REF relative to the new (more recent) expression EXPR-NEW. This predicate
label: Most Recent Reference To WRT Peg
mostRecentReferenceToWRTPeg

comment:
A MetaRelation used for stating a certain kind of necessary condition for being an element of the domain of a given Relation (see relationDomain). Thus (to put it in terms of the semantics of CycL expressions) interArgDifferent can be used for stating a certain kind of truth- or denotation-condition for a given relation-denoting expression. (interArgDifferent RELN N M) means that RELN (if it is a Predicate or other TruthFunction) only holds among or (if it is a Function_Denotational) only has a value for sequences of arguments whose Nth and Mth members are distinct (see different). That is (assuming without loss of generality that N < M): if RELN is a predicate or other "truth-function" then (RELN ... ARGN ... ARGM ...) holds only if ARGN and ARGM are distinct, and if RELN is a function then it is defined for (i.e. associates a value with) a sequence <THING-1, ..., THING-N, ..., THING-M, ...> only if THING-N and THING-M are distinct. For example, (interArgDifferent opponentsInConflict 1 2) means that no-one is his or her own opponent in a conflict.

Note that this predicate trivially holds for any relation with respect those argument-places it has that are subject to mutually disjoint (see disjointWith and cf. cosatisfiableInArgs) argument-type constraints (see ArgTypePredicate).
label: Inter Arg Different
interArgDifferent

comment: ?correspondence is the hypothesis that ?base-item matches  ?target-item.  ?base-item and ?target-item can be entities,  functors, or expressions.
label: Mapping Correspondence Between
mappingCorrespondenceBetween

comment: (hairCoverage ANIMAL PART-TYPE ANIMAL-BY-AMOUNT-OF-HAIR-TYPE) means that the ANIMAL-PART-TYPE of ANIMAL has the level of hair coverage indicated by ANIMAL-BY-AMOUNT-OF-HAIR-TYPE.
label: Hair Coverage
hairCoverage

comment: A sentence of the form (wordHypernymStringsRankedNthForPOS WORD SET-OF-STRINGS RANK POS) means that a consultation of a WordNetKnowledgeBase using the LexicalWord WORD for the WordNetSpeechPart POS returned a ranked-list of sets of strings, each element of which represents a hyperym for WORD, and that SET-OF-STRINGS with the Nth element of that list.
label: Word Hypernym Strings Ranked Nth For POS
wordHypernymStringsRankedNthForPOS

comment: (relationMemberExists PRED GROUP COLL) means that for every MEMBER such that (groupMembers GROUP MEMBER), there exists an instance INS of collection COLL such that (PRED MEMBER INS) is true. This predicate enables one to make claims about the members of a group without referencing the members.
label: Relation Member Exists
relationMemberExists
Has Been Examined In Temporal Predicate Sweep
hasBeenExaminedInTemporalPredicateSweep

comment: (userToolTypeUsageLevel AGENT ARTIFACT-TYPE USAGE-LEVEL) means that AGENT can use instances of ARTIFACT-TYPE with the skill level, SKILL-LEVEL (an instance of ToolUsageLevel).
label: User Tool Type Usage Level
userToolTypeUsageLevel

comment: A ternary ArgQuotedIsaPredicate (q.v.) used to place a specified quoted isa based argument-type constraint on a given VariableArityRelation (q.v.) with respect to any of its argument-places whose ordinal position is greater than or equal to a specified number. (argAndRestQuotedIsa RELN N COL) means that, as a necessary condition for semantic well-formedness, anything given as the Nth or greater argument to RELN must be a quoted instance of COL. Thus a closed formula (RELN ARG1..ARG(N)..ARG(N+1)..) is well-formed only if each of ARG(N)..ARG(N+1).. is a quoted instance of COL. See also argsQuotedIsa.
label: Arg And Rest Quoted Isa
argAndRestQuotedIsa

comment: This is the corresponding predicate of the function UnitAtAddressFn. An assertion of the form (unitWithLabelAtAddress SUB-LOCATION NAME LOCATION) means that the PhysicalContactLocation SUB-LOCATION is the part of the PhysicalContactLocation LOCATION that is picked out with the SubLString NAME.
label: Unit With Label At Address
unitWithLabelAtAddress

comment: An instance of IRExpansionPredicate. (irExpansionSet_DefinitionalSelectedWRTProperty TERM PRED INT SET) identifies SET as the set of collections that (i) are definitional isas for TERM, and (ii) are no more general than the argtype constraint(s) applicable to PRED in the INT-th argument place. This predicate represents an attempt to limit expansions for IR queries to those terms that might be more relevant given what other information is known about TERM -- assuming, in particular, that the property expressed by the predicate PRED is relevant to a given IR context. Contrast with irExpansionSet_Definitional_CoarseGrained.
label: Ir Expansion Set Definitional Selected WRT Property
irExpansionSet-DefinitionalSelectedWRTProperty

comment: (relationInstanceExistsRange PRED INS1 COL2 EXTENT) means that there exist EXTENT many instances (e.g., INS2) of COL2 that have the relation PRED with INS1, i.e. (PRED INS1 INS2) holds. Thus, (relationInstanceExistsRange legalOwnerOf #$Blake RaceCar AFew_Quant) means simply "Blake owns a few race cars.".
label: Relation Instance Exists Range
relationInstanceExistsRange

comment: (eMailReceived RECIPIENT_ADDRESS FROM_ADDRESS TEXT SUBJECT) means that an email was received at RECIPIENT_ADDRESS addressed from FROM_ADDRESS with the subject line SUBJECT and with TEXT as the message.
label: E Mail Received
eMailReceived

comment: It is an elementary fact of geometry that if A, B, and C are three noncollinear points, then there exists a unique plane PLANE which subsumes them. In CycL, we write (planeThroughPoints A B C PLANE).
label: Plane Through Points
planeThroughPoints

comment:
A ternary RuleMacroPredicate that can be used to state that a given binary predicate stands in a certain relationship with respect to two collections. (relationAllExistsMany BINPRED COL1 COL2) means that for any instance INST of COL1 there are many (see Many_Quant) instances INSTi of COL2 such that (BINPRED INST INSTi) holds. It is equivalent to (relationAllExistsRange BINPRED COL1 COL2 Many_Quant), and thus to the more complex form (for which it can in effect be used as shorthand): 

  (implies
     (isa ?INST COL1)
     (thereExistRange Many_Quant ?INST-I
        (and
           (isa ?INST-I COL2)
           (BINPRED ?INST ?INST-I)))).

For example, (relationAllExistsMany anatomicalParts Dog Hair_Strand) means that every dog has many hairs. See also relationAllExistsMin, relationAllExistsMax, relationAllExistsCount, and #$NoteAboutUseOfRuleMacroPredicates.
label: Relation All Exists Many
relationAllExistsMany

comment: (relationAllAll_Different PRED TYPE-1 TYPE-2) means that for every instance, INS1, of TYPE-1 and for every instance of TYPE-2, INS2, such that (different INS1 INS2), (PRED INS1 INS2) holds.
label: Relation All All Different
relationAllAll-Different

comment: An instance of both TernaryPredicate and FunctionalPredicate. (lowestLethalConcentrationForOrganismType SUBSTANCE-TYPE ORGANISM-TYPE DOSE) means that DOSE is the lowest concentration of SUBSTANCE-TYPE known to have killed an instance of ORGANISM-TYPE.
label: lowest lethal airborne concentration
lowestLethalConcentrationForOrganismType

comment: This SituationTypeRelation expresses a relation that holds between the prescribed substructures of two situations, conditional on one situation being a properSubSituations of the other. More specifically, (defaultSubsumptiveSubSitTypes SIT-TYPE1 SIT-TYPE2 SUBSIT-TYPE1 SUBSIT-TYPE2) means that where SIT1 is an instance of SIT-TYPE1 and SIT2 is an instance of SIT-TYPE2 such that (properSubSituations SIT1 SIT2), any proper subsituation of SIT2 that is an instance of SUBSIT-TYPE2 will be a subSituations (not necessarily a properSubSituations) of any instance of SIT1 that is an instance of SUBSIT-TYPE1. For example, suppose that a HostileSeizure occurs as part of a MilitaryOperation, and that it is generally the case that (candidateProperSubSituationTypes HostileSeizure (AcquiringFn Weapon)) and also that (candidateProperSubSituationTypes MilitaryOperation (AcquiringFn MilitaryHardware)). It stands to reason that in a MilitaryOperation which includes a HostileSeizure as a properSubSituations, any (AcquiringFn Weapon) that occurs as part of the seizure should be regarded as a subsituation of any (AcquiringFn MilitaryHardware) that occurs as part of the MilitaryOperation, provided there is no evidence to the contrary; e.g. evidence that the hardware-aquisition qua military op doesn't temporally subsume the weapon acquisition qua seizure.
label: Default Subsumptive Sub Sit Types
defaultSubsumptiveSubSitTypes

comment: A ternary complex action predicate. (doOutputProgramOperator HACKER FILE OPERATOR) means that HACKER appends code signifying OPERATOR to the end of source code file FILE. This is usually done when operator is part of a ProgramExpression.
label: Do Output Program Operator
doOutputProgramOperator

comment: (generateWithFormWhenArgInReln THING FORM ARGNUM RELN) means that any formula whose arg0 is RELN and whose ARGNUMth argument is THING should generate in natural language with a phrase whose head is of the word form FORM. For example, (generateWithFormWhenArgInReln Deceased regularDegree 2 isa) means that a sentence of the form (isa FOO Deceased) should generate as "FOO is deceased" or "FOO is dead," as opposed to something like "FOO is a dead thing."
label: Generate With Form When Arg In Reln
generateWithFormWhenArgInReln

comment:
An instance of QuaternaryPredicate used to individuate instances of ContextualizedInformationStructure.

(nthOccurrenceOfStructureTypeInStructure CIS N TYPE STRUCTURE) means that CIS, an instance of ContextualizedInformationStructure is the Nth occurrence of the specialization TYPE of AbstractInformationStructure in STRUCTURE.

For example, 

   (nthOccurrenceOfStructureTypeInStructure 
     (#$TextualOccurrenceFn 10 "green eggs and ham" (AISForFn GreenEggsAndHam)) 54 NounPhrase (AISForFn GreenEggsAndHam))
means that the 10th occurrence of the string "green eggs and ham" is the 54th occurrence of a noun phrase in the AbstractInformationStructure of the work Green Eggs and Ham.
label: Nth Occurrence Of Structure Type In Structure
nthOccurrenceOfStructureTypeInStructure

comment: A ternary MetaRelation predicate for stating that a certain kind of complex, partly isa based relationship holds between the first argument to a given function and the corresponding value that is returned. (interArg1ResultIsa FUNC INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL RESULT-COL) means that, when an instance of INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL appears as the first argument to FUNC, then -- regardless of what the other arguments to FUNC might be -- the value (if any) of that function for those arguments is an instance of RESULT-COL. That is: if INST is an instance of INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL and (FUNC INST ...) = VALUE, then VALUE is an instance of RESULT-COL. Note that, unlike (e.g.) the InterArgTypePredicates, interArg1ResultIsa cannot be used to put semantic well-formedness constraints on functions. See also the similar but more flexible quaternary interArgResultIsa.
label: Inter Arg 1 Result Isa
interArg1ResultIsa

comment: (pegInterpretationIsOutputOfClarification UTTERANCE-PEG INTERPRETATION EVENT) says that INTERPRETATION is an interpretation of the LinguisticExpressionPeg UTTERANCE-PEG that is the output of the clarification event EVENT (c.f., ClarificationDialogue). See also parsedPegInterpretations.
label: Peg Interpretation Is Output Of Clarification
pegInterpretationIsOutputOfClarification

comment: (doLoginToAccountOn AGENT ACCT COMP) means that AGENT takes steps toward the goal of getting access to a login prompt on COMP. Note that this will seldom (if ever) be an AGENT's goal if AGENT does not yet know the password and username for ACCT. Note that this predicate is appropriate only for instances of LoginAccount, whereas doGetAccessToAccount is appropriate for all accounts.
label: Do Login To Account On
doLoginToAccountOn

Mx4rvWEKXJwpEbGdrcN5Y29ycA: Permitted Sit Relation To Sit Type
comment: (forbidden_SitRelationToSitType SIT PRED FORBIDDEN-TYPE) means that there should be no instance FORBIDDEN-INS of FORBIDDEN-TYPE such that (PRED SIT FORBIDDEN-INS). Assertions involving this predicate -- which specify what should not be the case -- should be made in a normative context, e.g., one that reflects the contents of a particular $#CodeOfConduct. Usually, SIT will be subject to such a prohibition in virtue of satisfying some general description, e.g., one stated in the antecedent of a CycLRuleAssertion.
label: Forbidden Sit Relation To Sit Type
forbidden-SitRelationToSitType
Represents Variable In Sentence
representsVariableInSentence
comment: An assertion of the form (representsVariableInSentence REP VARIABLE SENT) means that the (CycLObjectTypeFn CycLVariable) REP 'represents' the CycLVariable VARIABLE that appears in the (CycLObjectTypeFn CycLSentence) SENT. REP does not denote VARIABLE. Instead, it is a relativized representation which considers VARIABLE as a syntactic element of SENT. This is the corresponding predicate of the function LocalVariableFn. NOTE: The third argument of this predicate is not quoted so that it is possible to use a term to denote SENT without it being the case that the symbols that compose VARIABLE appear within the symbols that compose SENT.

(templateReplacementsInvisibleForPosition_Topic TEMPLATE TOPIC POS) means that all of the potential replacements for POS in TEMPLATE, when it is used in the context of TOPIC, should remain invisible to the user. They will still be potential replacements, they will just not appear in the user interface. This is useful to assert when the list of replacements is especially long or unhelpful (e.g. all positive integers). Compare to templateReplacementsInvisibleForPosition, which indicates that potential replacements for POS in TEMPLATE should remain invisible to the user, regardless of the TOPIC context for which TEMPLATE is used.
label: Template Replacements Invisible For Position Topic
templateReplacementsInvisibleForPosition-Topic

comment: (enables_RoleInSitTypeRoleInSitType SIT-TYPE-1 ROLE-1 SIT-TYPE-2 ROLE-2) holds just in case playing ROLE-1 in instances of SIT-TYPE-1 enables one to play ROLE-2 in instances of SIT-TYPE-2.
label: Enables Role In Sit Type Role In Sit Type
enables-RoleInSitTypeRoleInSitType

comment: (accessibleFromInSystem X Y SYS) means that X is accessible from Y in the Semi_DirectedPathSystem SYS, which in turn means that either X = Y or there is a path PATH from Y to X in SYS, i.e., (pathFromToInSystem PATH Y X SYS) holds. Note that if we fix a Semi_DirectedPathSystem SYS, the relation accessibleFromInSystem is reflexive and transitive (i.e., a quasi-order). If we fix a BidirectedPathSystem SYS, this relation is an equivalence relation, the same as connectedInSystem.
label: Accessible From In System
accessibleFromInSystem

comment: An assertion of the form (incapableOfRoleInSituationType THING ROLE SIT-TYPE) asserts that THING, an instance of SomethingExisting, cannot play ROLE, an instance of BinaryRolePredicate, in some instance of SIT-TYPE, a specialization of Situation. The conditions that would explain why THING cannot play ROLE in an instance of SIT-TYPE, would be carried in an assertion using the predicate roleInScriptRequires_Neg.
label: Incapable Of Role In Situation Type
incapableOfRoleInSituationType

comment: (outranksOnScale PERSON1 PERSON2 SCALE) means that the subabstraction of PERSON1 that is referenced in the context of the assertion outranks the subabstraction of PERSON2 that is referenced in the context, on same military rank scale SCALE. This generally means that for the duration of the time interval in which the assertion is asserted to hold (via holdsIn, or a temporally qualified Mt) PERSON1 is authorized to issue certain sorts of orders to PERSON2, which PERSON2 is in turn required to obey. Since an outranksOnScale assertion will almost never hold true generally of a pair of entities, it should be qualified via holdsIn or deliberately reified subabstractions, or else be asserted within a temporally constrained context.
label: Outranks On Scale
outranksOnScale

comment: (exampleSentenceForValueInFACTTopic VALUE SENTENCE FACTORY-TOPIC) means that SENTENCE is a good example, in the context of FACTORY-TOPIC, of a true statement using VALUE.
label: Example Sentence For Value In FACT Topic
exampleSentenceForValueInFACTTopic

comment: A contextual version of slotDefinition; (slotDefinitionWRTObject OBJ SLOT FUNC) states that FUNC is the slotDefinition of SLOT just for object OBJ, i.e. (SLOT OBJ (FUNC OBJ)) holds. Also, (slotDefinitionWRTObject OBJ SLOT FUNC) can be considered shorthand for (numericFluentValue OBJ (CombineFn QuotientFn SLOT FUNC) 1). See also the similar predicate slotDefinition.
label: Slot Definition WRT Object
slotDefinitionWRTObject

comment: (equivalentRolePlayersOfType_SubSitTypeToSubSitType SITTYPE SUBSITTYPE1 ROLE1 SUBSITTYPE2 ROLE2 TYPE) means that in any instance SIT of SITTYPE, where SUBSIT1 and SUBSIT2 are subsituations of SIT and are instances of SUBSITTYPE1 and SUBSITTYPE2, respectively, whatever things of type TYPE play ROLE1 in SUBSIT1 also play ROLE2 in SUBSIT2, and vice versa.
label: Equivalent Role Players Of Type Sub Sit Type To Sub Sit Type
equivalentRolePlayersOfType-SubSitTypeToSubSitType

  (binaryPredicateLicensesSenseExtensionFromPOSToPOS1_2 PREDICATE POS-1 POS-2)
is shorthand for 
  (predicateLicensesSenseExtensionFromPOSInArgToPOSInArg PREDICATE POS-1 1 POS-2 2)

binaryPredicateLicensesSenseExtensionFromPOSToPOS1-2

comment: (agentStoresProductTypeAtFacility AGT PRODTYPE FACILITY) means that AGT uses FACILITY as a place to store PRODTYPE. For example, (agentStoresProductTypeAtFacility BMGMusicService #$CompactDisc-MusicalDisk BMGWarehouse001) says that BMG stores CD's BMGWarehouse001.

agentStoresProductTypeAtFacility

comment: (withinRangeForRolesInType OBJECT1 ROLE1 OBJECT2 ROLE2 SITTYPE) means that at some time, OBJECT1 is within range of OBJECT2 such that OBJECT1 may play the Role ROLE1 and OBJECT2 may play the Role ROLE2 in an instance of SITTYPE. For example, many times during the USPresidentialElection_2000 it is true that (withinRangeForRolesInType #$AlbertGore performedBy GeorgeWBush performedBy ShakingHands). This does not mean that in fact OBJECT1 and OBJECT2 play said roles, only that the two are within range to do so.
label: Within Range For Roles In Type
withinRangeForRolesInType

comment: (keIrrelevantTerm_UpperOntologyConcept TERM) should be used for all Cyc terms that are considered too high in the ontology for a SME or other non-Cyclist to see in any RKF-based interface.
label: Ke Irrelevant Term Upper Ontology Concept
keIrrelevantTerm-UpperOntologyConcept

comment: (most_GenQuantRelnFrom RELN THING COL) is true if, for most of the instances X of COL (RELN THING X) holds.
label: Most Gen Quant Reln From
most-GenQuantRelnFrom

comment: A ternary predicate relating a person to the character string used to identify that person in a particular online chat session. (onlineChatAlias CHAT PERSON STRING) means that the CharacterString STRING is used to identify PERSON during CHAT. Typically STRING would be an alias for PERSON, but not always.
label: Online Chat Alias
onlineChatAlias

comment: (documentRelativeBasePath APP COMPUTER PATH) means that the default directory location for storing files managed by APP, when APP is running on COMPUTER, can be determined by appending PATH to BASEPATH, where (applicationBasePath APP COMPUTER BASEPATH).
label: Document Relative Base Path
documentRelativeBasePath

comment:
A TernaryPredicate that is used to assert that a special relation holds between a FacetingCollectionType and a Predicate -- that the former is "based on" the latter in a specific sense.

Where (facets_Generic COL FACET-COL) and PRED is an n-place predicate, (facetBasedOnPredicateArg FACET-COL PRED ARG) means that for all X in FACET-COL, there is an ordered n-tuple <Y1,...,Yn> such that, by the definition of X, for any Z in COL, Z is in X iff the result of replacing YARG with Z in (PRED Y1...Yn)) holds.

For example, (facetBasedOnPredicateArg WineTypeByColor uniformColorOfObject 1) means that for all WINE-TYPE in WineTypeByColor, there is an ordered pair <DUMMY, COLOR> such that, by the definition of WINE-TYPE, for any WINE in Wine, WINE is in WINE-TYPE iff the result of replacing DUMMY with WINE in (uniformColorOfObject DUMMY COLOR), i.e. (uniformColorOfObject WINE COLOR), holds.

Note that it is also true that (facetBasedOnPredicateArg PersonTypeByOccupation isa 1). Indeed, (facetBasedOnPredicateArg FACET-COL isa 1) is trivially true for any FACET-COL, since the following is a logical truth: 

(forAll ?X 
  (thereExists ?Y 
    (forAll ?Z 
      (equiv (isa ?Z ?X) (isa ?Z ?Y)))))
For precisely this reason, there is no point in asserting that a facet is based on isa.

For the very common special case in which PRED is a BinaryPredicate, see facetBasedOnBinaryPred and facetBasedOnBinaryPredInverse. (Note that the meanings of these latter two predicates are much easier to understand.) See also facetBasedOnTypePredicateArg.
Mx4rwLSVCpwpEbGdrcN5Y29ycA: facets based on a particular predicate argument
label: facet based on a particular predicate argument
facetBasedOnPredicateArg

comment: (coversWithConformity OBJ SHEET LEVEL) means that OBJ is covered by SHEET, and that the inner surface of SHEET conforms to the surface features of OBJ to the degree LEVEL. SHEET may cover OBJ in either the sense of covers_Ruglike or covers_Baglike. For example, hosiery covers legs with a highAmountOf conformity; sweat pants have lowAmountOf conformity to legs. Level of conformity could probably based on the average of the distance between of lines going normal to the inside surface of OBJ to SHEET. The lowness or highness of this number would be based on comparison to representative exemplars. E.g. in a low conformity case, e.g. the average OBJ to SHEET distance for a pen in a grocery bag would be high relative to the dimensions of the pen. Thus level would be lowAmountOf. The analogous measure for a leg inside spandex pants would be very low compared to the dimensions of the leg. In such a case LEVEL would be highAmountOf.
label: Covers With Conformity
coversWithConformity

comment: (regionTotalZoonoticHostCount REGION AGENT-TYPE NUM) means that there are NUM zoonotic hosts in REGION capable of contracting and transmitting AGENT-TYPE.
label: region's total zoonotic host
regionTotalZoonoticHostCount

fACToryPredTopicForValueInArg

comment:
A specialization of both primaryFunction and intendedBehaviorCapable (qq.v.) that is used to indicate the primary or typical use a given artifact (see Artifact_Generic) was designed to serve. (intendedPrimaryFunction ARTIFACT SITTYPE ROLE) means that:

(i) the primary function of ARTIFACT is to play ROLE in situations of the type SITTYPE and
(ii) ARTIFACT was intended by its designer primarily to play ROLE in SITTYPEs.

For example, the intended primary function of a MammographyProvider is to provide service (see providerOfService) in MammographicBreastCancerScreenings; and the intended primary function of a Pump_Mechanical is to cause things to move (see providerOfMotiveForce) in ConveyingMaterials events. Most artifacts have just one intended primary function, but some have more than one. For example, a clock-radio has two intended primary functions: displaying the current time of day and converting transmitted radio signals into audible sounds. Note that in #$SimpleDeviceFunctioningMt, however, it is assumed that every PhysicalDevice has only one intended primary function.
label: Intended Primary Function
intendedPrimaryFunction

comment: ailmentAcquiredBy is the most general predicate available for identifying ways that an entity can acquire an ailment. Thus (ailmentAcquiredBy ILLNESSTYPE ORGANISMTYPE EVENTTYPE) says that instances of ORGANISMTYPE can become afflicted with ILLNESSTYPE via instances of EVENTTYPE. To identify the most common ways, use the more specific ailmentTypicallyAcquiredBy.
label: Ailment Acquired By
ailmentAcquiredBy

comment: (predicateConnectsCollections PRED COL1 COL2) means that when INST1 is an instance of COL1 and (PRED INST1 INST2) or (PRED INST2 INST1) holds, then (isa INST2 COL2) holds also.
label: Predicate Connects Collections
predicateConnectsCollections

comment: (temporalStage WHOLE MT SUB) means that SUB is the temporal subastraction of WHOLE that is picked out by the mtTime of the Microtheory, MT. This presupposes that WHOLE temporallySubsumes the specified mtTime of MT. In general, assertions of the form (temporalStage WHOLE MT SUB) will be made in contexts to which MT itself has access.
label: Temporal Stage
temporalStage

comment: (cycLQueryInferenceBindingVarValue QUERY-EVENT VAR TERM) means that the CycLFormula representing the query run in QUERY-EVENT contains the variable VAR, and in at least one ELInferenceBinding result of QUERY-EVENT, TERM is bound to VAR.

cycLQueryInferenceBindingVarValue

comment: (resemblesInQuantity THING1 THING2 QUANT-TYPE) means that the two things THING1 and THING2 resemble each other in their values of the specialization of Quantity QUANT-TYPE. Here 'resembles' means has a 'close' or similar value in that dimension -- what this means, and what the standard of closeness or similarity is, depends on the context. See also identicalInQuantity and differentInQuantity.
label: Resembles In Quantity
resemblesInQuantity

comment: (maximumMotionInDirection EVENT SUBEVENT DIRECTION) means that in the subevent SUBEVENT of EVENT, the object that is the primary object moving in SUBEVENT moves a distance in direction DIRECTION that is no less than the distance the object moves in that direction in any other subevent of EVENT.

maximumMotionInDirection

comment:
A specialization of argIsa (q.v.). (nearestArgIsa RELATION NUMBER COL) means that not only is it the case that 
   (argIsa RELATION NUMBER COL)
but also 
   (unknownSentence
     (thereExists ?GENL
        (and
           (argIsa RELATION NUMBER ?GENL)
           (different ?GENL COL)
           (genls ?GENL COL)))).
In other words, COL is a "nearest" -- i.e., non-subsuming -- argIsa constraint for RELATION in the NUMBER-th place.
label: Nearest Arg Isa
nearestArgIsa

comment: A variable-arity predicate (see VariableArityRelation) that is used to state the non-identity of two or more things. (different THING1..THINGn) means that for any THINGi and THINGj (where 0 <= i <= n, 0 <= j <= n, and i =/ j), THINGi is not identical with THINGj. That is, each of THING1, ..., THINGn is distinct from all of the others. Cf. equals.
label: different

This predicate is useful to use instead of the more general softwareParameterValueInSpecification when the value of the parameter is a CycL rule -- this narrower predicate allows us to reference the rule itself.

More specifically, if (rolesTemporallyExclusiveInSystemType SYSTEM-TYPE ROLE1 ROLE2) and (isa SYSTEM SYSTEM-TYPE), and it holdsIn any time interval TEMP that (ROLE1 SYSTEM AGENT), then it should also hold in TEMP that (unknownSentence (ROLE2 SYSTEM AGENT)).

comment: The expression `(objectSought_Definite SEARCH SEEKER CRITERION OBJECT)' means that SEARCH is a LookingForSomething_Definite which is performedBy SEEKER, and that OBJECT is the unique thing which satisfies the PossibleIdentificationCondition which is the searchCriterion_Definite for the search. This predicate is agent-relative in some respects and non-agent-relative in others. Including the searchCriterion-Definite makes is agent-relative in a certain sense. On the other hand, the term used to denote the OBJECT need not be one the agent would use or even recognize as denoting the OBJECT, so that the arg4 position of this predicate is not opaque (see opaqueArgument). Nor need the SEEKER ever be in a position to recognize that the OBJECT satisfies the CRITERION: in some cases the SEEKER may fail to recognize that the OBJECT satisfies the CRITERION even upon coming face to face with said object, because of the guise under which OBJECT is presented.
label: Object Sought Definite
objectSought-Definite

comment: (aggregateCNCScoreForRuleWithThresholds RULE COMPOUND-THRESHOLD COMPONENT-THRESHOLD SCORE SEARCH-ENGINE) means that SCORE (an instance of Real0_1) is the ratio candidate NC test cases passing COMPOUND-THRESHOLD to those passing COMPONENT-THRESHOLD for searches against the corpus covered by SEARCH-ENGINE. The COMPOUND-THRESHOLD value represents a minimum number of hits which a compound-strings must have for candidate compounds to be regarded as sufficiently evident within a corpus to be of interest. The COMPONENT-THRESHOLD value represents a minimum number of hits which the modifier- and head-strings for candiate compounds must have for candidates to count as vaild tests wrt. the corpus.
label: Aggregate CNC Score For Rule With Thresholds
aggregateCNCScoreForRuleWithThresholds

comment:
(wordSenseExtensionBrokeredByPred WORD SPEECH-PART-1 DENOTATION SPEECH-PART-2 EXTENSION BINARY-PREDICATE) means that the fact that 
   (wordSenseExtension WORD SPEECH-PART-1 DENOTATION SPEECH-PART-2 EXTENSION)
is explained in part by the fact that 
   (BINARY-PREDICATE ARG1 ARG2)
for some ARG1 and ARG2 such that 
   (denotation WORD ARG1 SPEECH-PART-1 N)
for some N.

The reason why this sense extension is only partly explained by the above considerations reflects the fact that due to Cyc's incomplete knowledge, there will be many cases where BINARY-PREDICATE is not an instance of SenseExtendingPredicate, and so cannot reliably broker sense extensions from SPEECH-PART-1 to SPEECH-PART-2 for any word denoting one of its arg1s. Rather, there is a possibly unreified specialization SPEC-PRED of BINARY-PRED (see genlPreds) that is an instance of SenseExtendingPredicate, and the fact that (SPEC-PRED ARG1 ARG2) fully explains the sense extension in question.
label: Word Sense Extension Brokered By Pred
wordSenseExtensionBrokeredByPred
