That is to say, (cutLinkBetweenInSystem LINK X Y SYS) holds if and only if (linkCutSetBetweenInSystem (TheSet LINK) X Y SYS) holds.
label: Cut Link Between In System
cutLinkBetweenInSystem

comment: (admittedSentence SENTENCE) states that SENTENCE is a CycLSentence which is both syntactically and semantically well-formed with respect to argument constraints only. For example, (admittedSentence (bordersOn Canada France)) is true in WorldGeographyDualistMt, but not in WorldGeographyMt, since Canada and France are known to be instances of GeographicalRegion in the former microtheory, but not in the latter microtheory. See also admittedArgument.
label: Admitted Sentence
admittedSentence

comment: (decreasesStatus_RoleInSitTypeWithRelationToSitType relates certain types of event sequences to certain types of social consequences. (decreasesStatus_RoleInSitTypeWithRelationToSitType ROLE SIT-TYPE SIT-RELATION RELATED-TYPE QUANTITY) means that, if an instance of SIT-TYPE (INS-SIT-TYPE) and an instance of RELATED-TYPE (INS-RELATED-TYPE) are related by SIT-RELATION -- i.e., if (SIT-RELATION INS-SIT-TYPE INS-RELATED-TYPE) holds -- then the agent playing ROLE in INS-SIT-TYPE will suffer a decrease in the SocialQuantity QUANTITY.
label: Decreases Status Role In Sit Type With Relation To Sit Type
decreasesStatus-RoleInSitTypeWithRelationToSitType

comment: (surfaceTensionAtTemperature SUBSTANCE TENSION TEMPERATURE) means that the specialization of LiquidTangibleThing, SUBSTANCE, has a surface tension of TENSION, usually measured in (PerFn Dyne (Centi Meter)), at the temperature specified by TEMPERATURE. Surface tension is a force found in LiquidTangibleThings, exherted by the high concentration of molecules of the liquid upon the lower concentration of molecules at the surface/air interface. These conditions create an internal pressure that restrains the liquid. The higher the surface tension, the less the liquid will flow.
label: surface tension
surfaceTensionAtTemperature

comment: This predicate is used for stating satisfaction conditions with respect to agents' needs. satisfiesNeed relates an agent, something the agent needs (in a very broad sense of 'need'), and a sufficent condition under which the agent's need for that thing would be satisfied. Thus it implies that the agent does have the need, and that it has not (or not yet) been satisfied. For a fuller account of the intended sense of 'need', see the comment on needs_Generic. (satisfiesNeed AGENT WHATEVER COND) means that AGENT's need with respect to WHATEVER would be satisfied (all else being equal) if COND were to become true. There are various sentential forms that COND will tend to take, depending on the type of thing WHATEVER is (and this also determines which specialization of needs-Generic is relevant to a given case). (a) If WHATEVER is a SomethingExisting, then it is something AGENT needs to obtain or possess (see needs), and COND might have the form (possesses AGENT WHATEVER). (b) If WHATEVER is a _collection_ of SomethingExistings, then WHATEVER is such that AGENT needs to obtain some arbitrary instance of it (see needs_Type), and (assuming for simplicity that AGENT currently possesses _no_ WHATEVERs) COND might have the form (relationInstanceExists possesses AGENT WHATEVER). (c) If WHATEVER is a collection of Events, then AGENT needs to be a "doer" (see doneBy) in some arbitrary (future) instance of that event-type (see needsToDo), and (assuming for simplicity that AGENT has never yet done a WHATEVER act) COND might have the form (relationInstanceExists doneBy AGENT WHATEVER). (d) If WHATEVER is an #$AttributeValue, then AGENT needs to have that attribute (see #$needsToHaveAttribute), and COND might have the form (#$hasAttributes AGENT WHATEVER). (e) Finally, if WHATEVER is a sentence (i.e. an #$ELSentence-Assertible), then AGENT needs the proposition expressed by COND to be true (see needs_Prop), and COND might simply be the sentence WHATEVER itself. For other ways that COND might usefully be formulated (e.g. when the simplifying assumptions used above do not apply) see the asserted rules on satisfiesNeed.
label: Satisfies Need
satisfiesNeed

comment: (adjSemTrans ADJ NUM FRAME TRANS) means that the translation of word sense number NUM of ADJ, appearing with subcategorization frame FRAME, is TRANS.
label: Adj Sem Trans

uses MAC/FAC to retrieve cases (typically one, but sometimes

comment:
A ternary instance of InterArgIsaPredicate (q.v.). (interArgEqualsIsa2_5 RELN INDEPENDENT-ARG DEPENDENT-ARG-COL) means that, when INDEPENDENT-ARG appears as the second argument to RELN, a necessary condition for semantic well-formedness is that the fifth argument must be an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. That is, (RELN ARG1 INDEPENDENT-ARG ARG3 ARG4 ARG5 ...) is semantically well-formed only if ARG5 is an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL.

For an explanation of semantic well-formedness, see CycLExpression_Assertible and its direct specializations. See interArgEqualsIsa for a similar but more general predicate that is quintary, allowing the user to specify the positions of the independent and dependent arguments.
label: Inter Arg Equals Isa 2 5
interArgEqualsIsa2-5

comment: (parseVisualizationTableForPeg PEG WIDTH TABLE) means that TABLE is an HTML table source string graphically illustrating the extent to which PEG has rewrites with successful parses.
label: Parse Visualization Table For Peg
parseVisualizationTableForPeg

comment: (acquaintances PERSON AGENT ACQUAINTANCE-PRED) means that PERSON is acquainted with AGENT, at least in the way (and/or to the degree) specified by ACQUAINTANCE-PRED; i.e. (ACQUAINTANCE-PRED PERSON AGENT). Note that AGENT must be an IntelligentAgent, so this is not the predicate to use to express the fact that Fred `is acquainted with' drag racing. Note that, depending on the value for ACQUAINTANCE-PRED, there may or may not be some way in which one can conclude that AGENT is acquainted with PERSON.
label: Acquaintances (ternary predicate)
acquaintances

comment: This predicate relates a thing to a role and situation type in which it might be reasonably expected to play the role but is unable to do so adequately because of a flaw. Note that this only applies to expected capabilities. For instance, if Cow001 is a Cow_FemaleHerdAnimal and is unable to hit a baseball, we would not assert (flawedWRTRoleInSitType Cow001 BaseballContact performedBy).
label: Flawed WRT Role In Sit Type
flawedWRTRoleInSitType

comment: This predicate gives the different parts of the phone number of the fax machine at a given location.
label: Fax Number (ternary predicate)
faxNumber

comment: (instancesDontNeedLexification COLL) means that the usual requirement that a CycL term have lexical assertions associating it with natural language words and phrases does not apply to instances of COLL.
label: Instances Dont Need Lexification
instancesDontNeedLexification

comment: The agent ARG1 is banned from the event/action ARG2 by the agent ARG3.
label: Banned From By
bannedFromBy

comment: This instance of TernaryPredicate is used to specify the salient characteristics of a particular kind of option available to an agent in a specific context. Specifically, (optionAvailableToAgent AGENT (TheSetOf ?VAR PROP1(?VAR)...PROPN(?VAR)) ROLE) means that playing the role ROLE in an event which satisfies the conditions PROP1 through PROPN is an option available to AGENT in the context in which the assertion is made. Ordinarily GAFs which use this predicate will be asserted in fairly constrained contexts in which a limited number of contingent options exist. The second argument must be an instance of Set_Mathematical, not an instance of Collection. This is because there is no a priori reason that a set of propositions describing the 'situational type' of an option should happen to characterize a natural kind, such as a specialization of Event or Situation. The fact that arg3 is an instance of ActorSlot presupposes that the set identified in the arg2 position is a subset of the collection Event.
label: Option Available To Agent
optionAvailableToAgent

comment: This predicate represents the complete unbalanced ionic equation listing the reactants and products of a type of chemical reaction in which ions occur. (ionicEquation_Net_Unbalanced TYPE I-REACTANTS I-PRODUCTS)expresses the equation of a reaction in which each member of I-REACTANTS or I-PRODUCTS is an instance of ChemicalSubstanceType.
label: complete unbalanced ionic equation
ionicEquation-Complete-Unbalanced

comment: The corresponding predicate (functionCorrespondingPredicate_Canonical) of ProperSubcollectionNamedFn_Ternary.
label: Proper Subcollection Of Named With ID
properSubcollectionOfNamedWithID

incapableOfRoleInSitType

comment: A predicate that relates a market to the income elasticity of demand (the responsiveness of demand to changes in consumer income) for a product-type in that market, in terms of a real numeric value. (incomeElasticityOfDemand MARKET PRODUCT OLD-INCOME-LEVEL NEW-INCOME-LEVEL ELASTICITY) means that given a change in income level from OLD-INCOME-LEVEL to NEW-INCOME-LEVEL for consumers in MARKET, the value of the change in demand for PRODUCT has a numeric value of ELASTICITY.
label: income elasticity of demand
incomeElasticityOfDemand

comment: (exchangeRateDuring_Official UM1 UM2 THING NR) means that the GeopoliticalEntity GE whose currency UM1 is has set NR as the official exchange rate of the UnitOfMoney UM1 for the UnitOfMoney UM2 during the temporal extent of the TemporalThing THING. (THING will often be a calendar time period.) The official exchange rate will not necessarily be the same as the (financial) market exchange rate, but in at least some markets regulated by GE, NR UM1's can be traded for 1 UM2, and conversely. (Official exchange rates are typically more stable than market exchange rates; but to the extent that there is fluctuation in the official exchange rate during the temporal extent of THING, NR should be taken to be the average official exchange rate during the temporal extent of THING.) For example, the fact that during October of 1995 the official exchange rate between Liberian and UnitedStates dollars was 1 Liberian dollar for 1 US dollar can be expressed as (exchangeRateDuring_Official Dollar_Liberia Dollar_UnitedStates (MonthFn October (YearFn 1995)) 1.0). See also exchangeRateDuring_Market and exchangeRateDuring.
label: official exchange rate
exchangeRateDuring-Official

comment: An instance of InterArgFormatPredicate (q.v.). (interArgFormat2_5 PRED COL FORMAT) means that FORMAT is a Format (q.v.) requirement for the fifth argument-place of PRED when PRED's second argument is an instance of COL. That is, with respect to a sentence of the form (PRED ARG1 ARG2 ARG3 ARG4 ARG5 ... ARGN) in which ARG2 is an instance of COL, PRED's arg5 position (i.e. the position occupied by the metavariable `ARG5' in the preceding sentence-form) is subject to FORMAT. See Format and its instances for further explanation.
label: Inter Arg Format 2 5
interArgFormat2-5

comment: (sihmSupportForPresupposedContent MT PEG CYCL) means that the CycL expression CYCL reflects possible presupposed content (see candidatePresupposedContents_CycL) of the instance PEG of LinguisticExpressionPeg that was extracted due to focal content (see #$mtFocalContent) of the instance MT of SemanticInterpretationHypothesisMicrotheory.

(exclusiveSubSituationTypes SIT-TYPE EITHER-TYPE XOR-TYPE) means that instances of EITHER-TYPE and XOR-TYPE cannot both occur as properSubSituations of instances of SIT-TYPE.

comment: enables_RemovesContraryFactors expresses the notion that an agent may be 'enabled' by an event in the following sense: the event removes all factors that are 'contrary', i.e., that would decrease the likelihood of the agent's success -- put another way: all factors that would make it less likely that the agent would succeed in performing the action if she tried. More accurately, (enables_RemovesContraryFactors SIT AGENT ACT_TYPE) is true iff SIT obtains, there are no contrary factors for AGENT to do an instance of ACT_TYPE, and SIT is the cause of there being no such contrary factors. Hence enables_RemovesContraryFactors does not imply that the agent is in fact capable of doing an action: rather, it entails that, given SIT, the probability of the agent's success is increased. Example: proper bicycle maintenance enables the cyclist to complete the race.
label: Enables Removes Contrary Factors
enables-RemovesContraryFactors

comment: (feelsTowardsObject_AssignedValueOnScaleWRTPurpose AGENT OBJECT NUMBER SCALE EVALUATION-TYPE) says that on a scale SCALE used in carrying out evalations of type EVALUATION-TYPE, where NUMBER is a point on SCALE, AGENT feels the feeling that corresponds to NUMBER towards OBJECT. To assign a number to a feeling on SCALE, use assignedValueOfQuantityForEvaluationType.

feelsTowardsObject-AssignedValueOnScaleWRTPurpose

comment: An instance of both LogicalConnective and UnaryRelation. which takes an instance of #CycLSentence-Assertible as its argument. (not SENT) is true if and only if SENT is false (and false if and only if SENT is true).

not

comment: A predicate used to state the difference in value, in terms of percentage, that a share of a particular company's stock has undergone between the previous day's close and its most-recently quoted price on the current day. (stockPriceChange_CloseToLast STOCK PERCENTCHANGE DATE EXCHANGE) means that PERCENTCHANGE is the percentage of increase or decrease in price for a share of STOCK between (i) the stockPrice_Close for a share of STOCK on EXCHANGE for the day before DATE and (ii) (stockPrice_Last STOCK PRICE DATE EXCHANGE). stockPercentageChange-CloseToLast

(latestSubsumedIntervalOfType TEMPORAL-THING INTERVAL TYPE) means that the instance of TimeInterval INTERVAL is the latest interval of type TYPE that is temporally subsumed by (c.f., temporallySubsumes) the temporal extent of the instance of TemporalThing TEMPORAL-THING. For example,

comment:
A unary #$InferenceCompletenessPredicate that is a specialization of completelyDecidableCollection (qq.v.). (completelyEnumerableCollection COL) means that the CycInferenceEngine can generate a list of all of (and only) the instances of COL. More precisely: given a query of the form (isa VAR COL), the Inference Engine can (without using transformations) return a list of terms -- bindings for the variable VAR -- such that every instance (and no non-instance) of the collection COL is denoted by some binding on the list.

For example, SkolemFunction is a completely enumerable collection. (But note that SkolemFunction does not satisfy the more specialized completelyAssertedCollection (q.v.), as most of its instances are only asserted to be instances of one of its specializations, such as FixedAritySkolemFunction.)

See also completeExtentEnumerable, which applies to Predicates.
label: Completely Enumerable Collection
completelyEnumerableCollection

comment: A ternary predicate. (renownWithinGroup THING AGENTTYPE RENOWN) means that THING's LevelOfRenown among agents of AGENTTYPE is RENOWN.

See also doGetAccessToData.

comment: (schooling PERSON SCHOOL STATUS) states that person has the student status STATUS at SCHOOL. For instance, if Bob graduated from Stanford University but was previously enrolled at University Of Texas At Austin, then (and (schooling Bob StanfordUniversity Graduate) (schooling Bob UniversityOfTexasAtAustin PreviouslyEnrolled)) holds.

comment: (increasesCausally TEMP-THING THING SLOT) means that TEMP-THING causes the value of the predicate SLOT applied to THING (in the first argument position) to increase over some time period after the start of TEMP-THING. This is defined in terms of increasesCausallyOverPeriod (see also). Compared with its value immediately before TEMP-THING, the value of SLOT applied to THING is guaranteed to be higher immediately following or some time after TEMP-THING. This net increase need not be monotonic. See #$NoteAboutQuantityChangePredicates for a map of related predicates.

increasesCausally

label: Date Awarded
dateAwarded

comment:
An instance of both MetaKnowledgePredicate and MetaPredicate (qq.v.) that is used to state that the Cyc system will "assume" that a (sequence of) thing(s) is not in the extension (see relationExtension) of a given predicate if the CycInferenceEngine is unable to prove that it is.

(minimizeExtent PRED) means that, for any sequence of things <THING1, ..., THINGn> such that (PRED THING1 ... THINGn) holds, the fact that this holds is either expressed by some GAF (i.e. a "ground atomic formula"; see CycLClosedAtomicSentence) that is asserted in the Cyc Knowledge Base or is deducible via the inference engine from what is in the KB.

The practical import of a minimizeExtent assertion is that it reflects an underlying assumption that if the inference engine cannot prove some given sentence of the form (PRED ARG1 ... ARGN), then that fact constitutes an argument for its negation (not (PRED ARG1 ... ARGN)); and, if the "negation by failure" inference parameter is turned on, the inference engine will actually conclude that this negation is true. Note that a minimizeExtent assertion is weaker than the corresponding completeExtentEnumerable (q.v.) assertion would be, in that the latter does not require that the inference engine attempt to deduce (PRED ARG1 ... ARGn) before concluding that it is not true. See also minimizeExtentForArg and the shared #$NoteOnClosedWorldAssumption.
label: Minimize Extent
minimizeExtent

comment:
A ternary predicate that relates two instances of Quantity to a linear ordering (see TotallyOrderedQuantityType) that they both occur in. (quantitiesShareScale QUANT1 QUANT2 SCALE) means that QUANT1 and QUANT2 are two distinct instances of the totally-ordered quantity-type SCALE (see colinearQuantities). This implies that either (followingValueOnScale QUANT1 QUANT2 SCALE) or (followingValueOnScale QUANT2 QUANT1 SCALE) holds.

Where QUANT1 and QUANT2 are both Quantity[ies], (followingValueOnScale QUANT1 QUANT2 SCALE) also implies (quantitiesShareScale QUANT1 QUANT2 SCALE). We can think of the latter predicate as a version of the former that applies only to quantities and is unconcerned about their ordering with respect to SCALE.
label: Quantities Share Scale
quantitiesShareScale

comment: (rolePlayerValuesMapToProgramFunctionArgs EVENT-TYPE ROLE SLOT FUNC NUM) means that the for FUNC to implement an instance EVENT of EVENT-TYPE it will take as its NUMth argument the arg2 value of SLOT asserted of the role-player RP of which it is true that (ROLE EVENT RP).
label: Role Player Values Map To Program Function Args
rolePlayerValuesMapToProgramFunctionArgs

yearHasEnumerationOnCalendar

comment: It is medically recommended that the BLO ARG1 play the role ARG3 in some instance of ARG2, typically but not necessarily, in order to ameliorate some condition they are experiencing.

medicalRecommendationForBLO

Mx4rv3W2hJwpEbGdrcN5Y29ycA: Normative Specification Describes Reln To Ins
comment: The predicate normativeSpecificationDescribesRoleForInd is used for partially specifying the satisfaction conditions for an instance of NormativeSpecification Specifically, it associates an instance of NormativeSpecification SPEC with a BinaryRolePredicate ROLE and an instance of SomethingExisting THING, to state the part of satisfying SPEC involves a situation in which THING fills ROLE. This predicate works in conjunction with normativeSpecificationDescribesSituationType. In short, given assertions of the form (normativeSpecificationDescribesSituationType SPEC SIT-TYPE) and (normativeSpecificationDescribesRoleForInd SPEC ROLE IND), then the satisfaction of SPEC will involve an instance of SIT-TYPE, SIT, such that the assertion (ROLE SIT IND) is true. This predicate only provides a partial specification because any number of assertions using it or the predicate normativeSpecificationDescribesRoleForType can be used with normativeSpecificationDescribesSituationType to represent what needs to be done to satisfy SPEC. See also completeSpecification for more information on constructing rules using these predicates.
label: Normative Specification Describes Role For Ind
normativeSpecificationDescribesRoleForInd
subPropertyOf: Normative Specification Describes Reln To Ins

comment: (nounCompoundWithRule MOD MOD-DENOT HEAD HEAD-DENOT RULE) means that the phrase consisting of MOD and HEAD, under the semantic interpretations MOD-DENOT and HEAD-DENOT, meets the syntactic and semantic constraints specified by RULE.
label: Noun Compound With Rule
nounCompoundWithRule

comment: (holdsBefore ?THING ?PRED ?OBJ ?VAL) means that (?PRED ?OBJ ?VAL) is true before the temporal extent of ?THING begins.

holdsBefore

comment:
A ternary GeneralizedQuantifier. (relativelyFewComparedToType SOC1 SOC2 SOC3) means that the percentage of instances of SOC1 that are instances of SOC2 is less than the percentage of instances of the average instance of SOC3 that are instances of SOC2. For example,

(relativelyFewComparedToType UnitedStatesPerson BuddhistPerson PersonTypeByNationality)

means that the percentage of Americans who are Buddhists is lower than the percentage of the average nationality who are Buddhists. See also relativelyFew and relativelyFewComparedTo.
label: Relatively Few Compared To Type
relativelyFewComparedToType

comment:
A TernaryPredicate that relates a FinancialOrganization to a specialization of LoanAgreement to an IntervalOnNumberLine. (lenderOffersAgreementTypeAtAPR LENDER AGR-TYPE NUM) means that LENDER offers instances of AGR-TYPE at the annualPercentageRate of NUM.

For example, (lenderOffersAgreementTypeAtAPR ChaseManhattanBank CreditCardAgreement (Percent 12.9)) means that Chase Manhattan offers a credit card with an APR of 12.9%.
label: Lender Offers Agreement Type At APR
lenderOffersAgreementTypeAtAPR

comment: (builderQueryForSchematicElementOfSKS SKS ELEMENT QUERY) means that QUERY is the CycLQuerySpecification for the schematic element ELEMENT in the StructuredKnowledgeSource SKS. Here, a schematic element is either a meaning sentence predicate or a logical field type for SKS. See also the disjoint typed spec preds builderQueryForMeaningSentenceOfSKS and builderQueryForLogicalFieldTypeOfSKS.
label: Builder Query For Schematic Element Of SKS
builderQueryForSchematicElementOfSKS

comment: (constrainsArgs INTER-ARG-PRED M N) means that the InterArgConstraintPredicate (q.v.) INTER-ARG-PRED can be used to place an inter-argument type or format constraint on the Nth argument of a relation to which it is applied, conditional upon the relation's corresponding Mth argument.
label: Constrains Args
constrainsArgs

comment: A ternary complex action predicate. (doProgramStep PROGRAMMER FILE STEP) means that PROGRAMMER appends code to the end of FILE that implements STEP, in the programming language determined by the current context.
label: Do Program Step
doProgramStep

comment: (importRate COUNTRY PRODUCT-TYPE RATE) means that COUNTRY imports PRODUCT-TYPE at the rate of RATE. Note that RATE may be expressed as a MonetaryRate, but also as rate of volume, mass or number depending on the type of product. For example, for oil which is a fluid we can say both (importRate UnitedStatesOfAmerica PetroleumProduct (MillionDollarsPerYear NR)) and (importRate UnitedStatesOfAmerica PetroleumProduct (MillionBarrelsPerYear NR)). Note that services, i.e. specializations of ServiceEvents are included as product types.
label: import rate
importRate
Event Sequence
eventSequence
comment: (eventSequence (TheList FORM_1 FORM_2 ... FORM_n)) means that the actions described by the event formulas FORM_i were performed in the order indicated. Each FORM_i should be an atomic formula whose predicate is an instance of EventPredicate.
(outputProgramToken PROGRAMMER FILE TOKEN) means that PROGRAMMER appends ProgramExpression TOKEN to the end of FILE, an instance of ComputerCode_Source.
label: Output Program Token
outputProgramToken

comment: (interSubSituationTypeRelation SITTYPE RELATION SUBSITTYPE1 SUBSITTYPE2) means that in any instance of SITTYPE the sub-situation of type SUBSITTYPE1 will be related to the sub-situation of type SUBSITTYPE2 by RELATION.
label: Inter Sub Situation Type Relation
interSubSituationTypeRelation

comment: (reformulationDirectionInMode DIRECTION MODE RULE), when asserted in the microtheory MT, tells the CycLReformulator whether to use RULE in the forward (ReformulationForwardDirection) or backward (ReformulationBackwardDirection) direction when reformulating CycLExpressions in MT or a specMt thereof, and when operating in the mode MODE. It will reformulate the 'from' arg into the 'to' arg, based on DIRECTION. ReformulationNeitherDirection indicates the rule is not to be used at all in this mt. This concept of direction has nothing to do with the forward vs. backward rule distinction in inference.
label: Reformulation Direction In Mode
reformulationDirectionInMode

comment: '(subDivisionLevelOf STRUCTURE DIVISION N)' means that DIVISION is one of the subStructures of N divisions of the GraphicalStructure STRUCTURE. For example, if a work is divided into chapters and there are no higher level divisions within which the chapters are contained, then (subDivisionLevelOf CWSTRUCTURE CHAPTER 0) where CWSTRUCTURE is a TextualPCWStructure. As another example, consider a titled section within a chapter within the first part of a TextualPCWStructure (i.e., Section 1 of Chapter 1 of Part I). A number of different assertions could be made regarding the different parts of the overall GraphicalStructure of the text (e.g., (subDivisionLevelOf CWSTRUCTURE CHAPTER 1)...(subDivisionLevelOf CWSTRUCTURE SECTION 2)...(subDivisionLevelOf PART CHAPTER 0)).
label: Sub Division Level Of
subDivisionLevelOf

comment: executePrivilegeOfProgramOnSystem PROG SYS PLEVEL) means that the copy, PROG, of the instance of ComputerProgram_CW on the instance of ComputationalSystem, SYS, executes at PrivilegeLevelType PLEVEL. Compare this predicate to executePrivilegeOfProgramCopy.
label: Execute Privilege Of Program On System
executePrivilegeOfProgramOnSystem

comment: (queryVariableConstraints QUERYFORMULA VARIABLE MEANINGSENTENCE) means that VARIABLE is an open or existentially bound CycLVariable in the formula QUERYFORMULA, and MEANINGSENTENCE expresses the constraints on VARIABLE.
label: Query Variable Constraints
queryVariableConstraints
Hours From First Ventilation To Op Exit
hoursFromFirstVentilationToOpExit
comment: (hoursFromFirstVentilationToOpExit OP HOURS-DURATION) means that the time elapsed from the beginning of the first ventilation event during the hospitalization of the indexed operation OP and the end of that operation is HOURS-DURATION.

(approvedCrossReference ?LTS ?IDTYPE1 ?IDTYPE2) means that the LogicalTableSchema ?LTS is approved as being a source of cross-reference information for the two UniqueIDTypes, ?IDTYPE1 and ?IDTYPE2. For example, (approvedCrossReference DOCTOR-XREF-LTS SocialSecurityNumber DoctorME) means that, for the job of determining an individual's DoctorME if you know his or her SocialSecurityNumber, or vice-versa, DOCTOR-XREF-LTS is an approved table to use.
label: Approved Cross Reference
approvedCrossReference

comment: An assertion of the form (#$deathDueToDuring PLACE ORG-TYPE TYPE N DATE) states that measurements made of the population of the GeographicalRegion PLACE during the Date DATE indicate that N instances of Person died as a result of their playing the role of objectActedOn in some occurrence of TYPE, a subcollection of Situation. For instance, an assertion of the form (deathsDueToDuring Syria HomoSapiens AIDS 200 (YearFn 2005)) would state that records indicate that during 2005, 200 people died from AIDS in Syria. This represents a measurement and estimate.
label: Deaths Due To During
deathsDueToDuring

comment: A specialization of behaviorCapable (q.v.) that is used to specify a primary or particularly important function that a given object serves. (primaryFunction OBJ SITTYPE ROLE) means that the primary function of OBJ is to play ROLE in situations of the type SITTYPE. OBJ might be a natural object that has a primary function (e.g the primary function of a heart is to pump blood), or OBJ might be an artifact that was intentionally designed to have the primary function that it does (e.g. the primary function of a wall clock is to show the current time of day). For cases of the latter sort, consider the more specialized predicate intendedPrimaryFunction. Note that, while most things have one primary function, some have more than one. For example, one might claim that the two primary functions of a lung are to take in oxygen and to expell carbon dioxide. For things that have only one main function, consider the specialization soleFunction.
label: Primary Function
primaryFunction

comment: (was_Metric_CalendarTime METRIC-TYPE k TIME-TYPE PROP) means that PROP was the case at the time TIME-TYPE of the k-th time interval of type METRIC-TYPE in the past. A KBDependentRelation (q.v.) and specialization of consistent (q.v.) that is used to state that a given CycL sentence is true. (trueSentence SENT) means that SENT is true.

trueSentence is a non-assertible predicate (see notAssertible). But this puts no real limitation on the expressive power of the Cyc system since one can assert that SENT is true by simply asserting SENT itself.

Most occurrences of the expression 'trueSentence' in CycL assertions have been added by the canonicalizer, so that certain nested sentences (or variables occurring in argument-positions intended for sentences) can receive special handling during canonicalization or inference. See the accompanying #$cyclistNotes for details.

Mx4rvWEKXJwpEbGdrcN5Y29ycA: subjective decrease in quantity slot in situation
comment: (increasesSitSlot_Subjective SIT THING SLOT) expresses the fact that, everything else being equal, in the situation SIT the value of the QuantitySlot SLOT (i.e. the arg2 to SLOT) to be attributed to THING would be higher than some default or presupposed base value. The `everything else being equal' clause indicates that the value of SLOT for THING might change, even *de*crease, were more information to become available about SIT. This predicate captures an important aspect of probability assignments: they tend to be subjective, i.e., based on the amount of information available to an evaluator, and they are not *persistent* with respect to situations. Consider an example: A situation in which I board a plane from Austin to Chicago at 7am on a given day may *or may not* be one in which it is more likely that I will be in Chicago on time for a 3pm meeting than a situation in which I drive a car, because other undetermined factors might play a negative role. For example, that particular situation might also be a situation in which fierce storms shut down air traffic into Chicago for 2 days. However, barring additional factors and constraints (`everything else being equal'), if all I know about a situation is that in it I take a plane to Chicago at 7am, I would be a fool not to assign a higher probability to my being on time for my meeting in such a situation. The relation expressed by increasesSitSlot_Subjective is not (necessarily) causal. Also, note that (increasesSitSlot_Subjective SIT THING SLOT) doesn't entail (increases_Generic SIT THING SLOT) since the latter implies that the value of SLOT for THING *is actually* higher after the beginning of SIT. Nor does (increases_Generic SIT THING SLOT) entail (increasesSitSlot_Subjective SIT THING SLOT). Finally, the meaning of this predicate is not inherently temporal, unlike increases_Generic.
Mx4rwLSVCpwpEbGdrcN5Y29ycA: subjective increases in quantity slot in situation
label: subjective increase in quantity slot in situation
increasesSitSlot-Subjective

The first element is a sub-collection of Situation that SIT-TYPE has as at least a candidate scene (see: candidateProperSubSituationTypes) and the second element is a BinaryRolePredicate. Specifically, it asserts that if LIST contains as elements (TheList SUBSIT-TYPE1 ROLE1) and (TheList SUBSIT-TYPE2 ROLE2), given certain other conditions, this entails that whatever plays ROLE1 in the instance of SUBSIT-TYPE1 is identical to the player of ROLE2 in the instance of SUBSIT-TYPE2.

An example of a predicate for which the argGenls assertions do not determine a maximal genls constraint could be, primaryFunction, whose arg2Genl is Situation. A ternary RuleMacroPredicate (q.v.) that can be used to state that a given binary predicate stands in a certain relation to two collections. (relationAllAll BINPRED COL1 COL2) means that for any instance INST1 of COL1 and any instance INST2 of COL2, (BINPRED INST1 INST2) holds. This is equivalent to (and can thus be used in effect as shorthand for) the more complex form: 

     (implies
          (and
               (isa ?INST1 COL1)
               (isa ?INST2 COL2))
          (BINPRED ?INST1 ?INST2)) .

For example '(relationAllAll loves Person DomesticCat)' means that all people love all cats. See also the shared #$NoteAboutUseOfRuleMacroPredicates.

comment:
A quintary MetaRelation predicate. (typeLevelVersionInArg RELN TYPERELN N M QUANT) means that TYPERELN is a type-level version of RELN with regard to their respective Nth and Mth argument-places. This implies that if RELN's Nth argument-place is constrained to take instances of a collection COL (see argIsa), then TYPERELN's Mth argument-place is constrained to take specializations of COL (see argGenl). (Usually, N and M will be the same.) Moreover, where INST and SPEC are respectively an instance and a specialization of COL, and RELN and TYPERELN are both predicates, what the sentence (TYPERELN ... SPECM ...) states is a generalization of what the sentence (RELN ... INSTN ...) states. If QUANT is a universal quantifier (i.e. forAll), the former sentence says something about all of the instances of some collection -- which, depending on the case, could either be SPEC or the collection of things RELN relates via its Nth argument-place to the rest of the given arguments. If QUANT is an existential quantifier (e.g. thereExists), it says something about some (unspecified) instance of one of these collections. (Typically, TYPERELN will be a MacroRelation whose expansion involves RELN and QUANT.)

When RELN and TYPERELN are functions rather than predicates, the situation is analogous to the above.

For example, (typeLevelVersionInArg groupMembers groupMemberType 2 2 forAll) holds. While (groupMembers GROUP THING) means that THING is a member of GROUP, (groupMemberTypes GROUP TYPE) means that all the members of GROUP are instances of TYPE. For another example, (typeLevelVersionInArg instrument_Generic instrumentType_Generic 2 2 thereExists) holds. (instrumentType_Generic EVENT TYPE) means that some instance of TYPE plays the role of instrument_Generic in EVENT.

See also the binary generalization typeLevelCognates.
label: Type Level Version In Arg
typeLevelVersionInArg

For example,(interArgCondIsa1_2 anatomicalParts Vertebrate Head_AnimalBodyPart Head_Vertebrate) -- if a Vertebrate has a head as an anatomicalParts, that head is a Head_Vertebrate.
label: Inter Arg Cond Isa 1 2
interArgCondIsa1-2

That is, (RELN ARG1 INDEPENDENT-ARG ARG3 ARG4 ...) is semantically well-formed only if ARG4 is an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL.

For an explanation of semantic well-formedness, see CycLExpression_Assertible and its direct specializations. See interArgEqualsIsa for a similar but more general predicate that is quintary, allowing the user to specify the positions of the independent and dependent arguments.

A unary #$InferenceCompletenessPredicate and a specialization of completeExtentEnumerable (q.v.) that applies to predicates whose entire extents are explicitly asserted in the Cyc Knowledge Base. (completeExtentAsserted PRED) means that, for every sequence <THING1,..., THINGN> that satisfies PRED, (PRED THING1 ... THINGN) is asserted in the Knowledge Base. That is, for each such sequence, there are reified CycL terms PRED-NAME, TERM1, ..., TERMN -- which denote PRED, THING1, ..., THINGN, respectively -- such that the sentence (PRED-NAME TERM1 ... TERMN) built from those terms is an assertion in the KB.

If completeExtentAsserted is true of PRED, then the CycInferenceEngine, when asked a query of the form (PRED . VARS), can return a complete set of bindings for the variables in VARS simply via a lookup of assertions in the KB. By a "complete set of bindings" is meant a set of sequences of terms such that, for each sequence <THING1, ..., THINGN> in the extent of PRED, there is a corresponding sequence of terms <TERM1, ..., TERMN> returned wherein each TERMI denotes THINGI (for 1 <= I <= N).

For example, (completeExtentAsserted hourOfDayIndex_24Hour) holds. Thus, the sentence (hourOfDayIndex_24Hour TimeOfDay_1AM 1) is one of twenty-four similar ground-atomic sentences asserted in the KB. Conversely, (completeExtentAsserted argN) does not hold. Thus, while the Inference Engine could generate the set of all true argN based ground-atomic sentences (i.e. completeExtentEnumerable holds of argN), the members of this set are not all asserted in the KB.

See also completelyAssertedCollection, which applies to collections rather than predicates.
label: Complete Extent Asserted
completeExtentAsserted

comment: (resourceCapableOf AGENT SIT-TYPE ROLE) means that AGENT has the necessary resources available to it to play ROLE in elements of SIT-TYPE. Note that the notion of resource is different than skill (see skillCapableOf), technology (see technologicallyCapableOf), authority (see authorityCapableOf). Resources are external to the agent, so that anatomy is not a resource (see anatomicallyCapableOf). Money is one kind of resource and thus fiscallyCapableOf is implied by resourceCapableOf. Having the resources to play ROLE in SIT-TYPE entails that the appropriate (necessary or sufficient) things are present or are present in sufficient amounts.--BillJ, edited by Curtis

INS ...), where INS occurs in the Nth argument place, are appropriate sentences from which to generate expansion strings for the sub-string of UTTERANCE that denotes INS. More formally, (irExpansionPredForTypeInSitTypeWithRole TYPE SIT-TYPE ROLE N PRED) says that (forAll ?X (implies (isa ?X TYPE) (irExpansionSentencesForTermGivenVerbSem ?X SIT-TYPE ROLE SENTENCE))), where (trueSentence SENTENCE), (operatorFormulas PRED SENTENCE) and (argN ?X SENTENCE N) all hold.

comment:
This predicate is used to state that the value of a quantity slot increases for a fixed object throughout an event. (increasesThroughoutEvent SLOT THING EVENT) is true if and only if for every pair of sub-events SUB1 and SUB2 of EVENT there exist values VAL1 and VAL2 such that if 
(and
  (startsAfterEndingOf SUB1 SUB2)
  (holdsIn SUB1 (SLOT THING VAL1))
  (holdsIn SUB2 (SLOT THING VAL2)))
it follows that 
(greaterThanOrEqualTo VAL1 VAL2)
is true. See also decreasesThroughoutEvent and constantThroughoutEvent.

increasesThroughoutEvent

(See comment for succeedingIntervalType.) For example, (succeedingIntervalType Monday Tuesday) and (succeedingIntervalType Tuesday Wednesday) are true, and all of Monday, Tuesday and Wednesday are different instances of DayOfWeekType, and therefore (followingIntervalType_Cumulated Monday Wednesday DayOfWeekType 2) is true. Note that for each suitable arg3 to followingIntervalType_Cumulated, there is a maximal integer for its arg4. For example, if the arg3 is DayOfWeekType, the maximal integer for the arg4 is 7, and if the arg3 is MonthOfYearType, the maximal integer for the arg4 is 12, etc. Note also that this predicate is functional in its arg4 place.

comment: (importQuotaDuring REGION PRODUCT-TYPE THING AMOUNT) means that the ScalarInterval AMOUNT is a measure of the import quota of instances of the ProductType PRODUCT-TYPE for the GeographicalRegion REGION during the temporal extent of the TemporalThing THING. (Of course, the existence of import quotas is the exception rather than the rule.) THING will often be a calendar time period; but it may also be, for instance, a particular Event. In the case of automobile imports, for example, AMOUNT might be an Integer indicating the number of cars that may be imported. In the case of oil imports, AMOUNT might be a Volume (a number of barrels) indicating the total quantity of oil REGION is allowed to import. Alternatively, AMOUNT might be a Rate, characterizing the average rate of import, under the quota, of instances of PRODUCT-TYPE by REGION during the temporal extent of THING. Oil imports, for example, might be expressed in terms of so many million barrels per day.

comment:
A MetaRelation and specialization of functionCorrespondingPredicate that is used to state that a given function and a given predicate amount to essentially the same relationship and have the same argument order, modulo the given argument number of the predicate corresponding to the result of the function.

(functionCorrespondingPredicate_Canonical FUNC PRED N) means that FUNC maps a given argument-sequence ARGS (say of length M) to the value VAL if and only if PRED holds of the (M+1 length) sequence ARGS-N-VAL, where ARGS-N-VAL is just like ARGS except for having VAL as its Nth member and having ARGS's Nth to Mth members as its (N+1)th to (M+1)th members. Thus PRED will be a StrictlyFunctionalPredicate (q.v.), with its Nth argument-place being a "functional" one (see strictlyFunctionalInArgs).

For example, (functionCorrespondingPredicate_Canonical StreetCornerFn streetCornerOf 1) implies that (StreetCornerFn XING DIRECTION) = LOT just in case (streetCornerOf LOT XING DIRECTION) holds.

When reifying an instance of Function_Denotational it is generally considered good ontological engineering practice also to reify a (or to find an already-existing) corresponding Predicate, as this allows one to describe more explicitly the relationship between the members of the function's domain and the corresponding members of its range (see relationDomain and relationRange).

See also functionCorrespondsToShuffledPredicate, functionCorrespondsToShuffledPredicate_Symmetric, and functionCorrespondingPredicate_Generic.
label: Function Corresponding Predicate Canonical
functionCorrespondingPredicate-Canonical

comment: A TernaryPredicate that relates an Agent_Generic to a quoted instance of CycLPropositionalSentence to a Real0_1. (probabilityForAgent AGT PROP N) means that the (subjective) probability of PROP for AGT is N.
label: Probability For Agent
probabilityForAgent

comment: A ternary MetaRelation predicate for stating that a certain kind of complex, partly isa based relationship holds between the fourth argument to a given function and the corresponding value that is returned. (interArg4ResultIsa FUNC INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL DEPENDENT-ARG-COL) means that, when an instance of INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL appears as the fourth argument to FUNC, then -- regardless of what the other arguments to FUNC might be -- the value (if any) of that function for those arguments is an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. That is: if INST is an instance of INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL and (FUNC ARG1 ARG2 ARG3 INST ...) = VALUE, then VALUE is an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. Note that, unlike (e.g.) the InterArgTypePredicates, interArg4ResultIsa _cannot_ be used to put semantic well-formedness constraints on functions. See also the similar but more flexible quaternary interArgResultIsa.
label: Inter Arg 4 Result Isa
interArg4ResultIsa

comment: A ternary complex action predicate. (doDeclareVariable PROGRAMMER FILE VARIABLE) means that PROGRAMMER appends code declaring VARIABLE (an instance of SoftwareParameter) to the end of the source code file FILE.
label: Do Declare Variable
doDeclareVariable

comment: A ternary instance of InterArgIsaPredicate (q.v.). (interArgIsa3_4 RELN INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL DEPENDENT-ARG-COL) means that, when an instance of INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL appears as the third argument to RELN, a necessary condition for semantic well-formedness is that the fourth argument must be an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. That is, if INST is an instance of INDEPENDENT-ARG-COL, then (RELN ARG1 ARG2 INST ARG4 ... ARGN) is semantically well-formed only if ARG4 is an instance of DEPENDENT-ARG-COL. For an explanation of semantic well-formedness, see CycLExpression_Assertible and its direct specializations.
label: Inter Arg Isa 3 4
interArgIsa3-4

comment: If INTEGRATION is an IntegratingASetOfKnowledgeSources, INPUT-ODS-SET is the set of input object defining schemas to be integrated (see schemaIntegrationInputODSSet), and TYPE is one of the object field types associated with INTEGRATION (see schemaIntegrationObjectFieldTypeSet), then (schemaIntegrationTypeForInputODSSet INTEGRATION TYPE ODS-SET) means that each element of INPUT-ODS-SET is an object defining schema (see ObjectDefiningSchema) of type TYPE (see schemaIsa) that is associated with some element of INPUT-SET.
label: Schema Integration Type For Input ODS Set
schemaIntegrationTypeForInputODSSet
Uri Has Base And Fragment
uriHasBaseAndFragment
comment: A predicate corresponding to the function URIWithFragmentFn. (uriHasBaseAndFragment (URIWithFragmentFn BASE FRAGMENT) BASE FRAGMENT) will always be true for BASE and FRAGMENT meeting the relevant arg constraints.

(borderBetweenRegions BORDER REG1 REG2) means that BORDER is the entire intangible border shared by the adjacent geographical regions REG1 and REG2. Note that BORDER might be discontinuous (such as the border between France and Spain, interrupted by Andorra), or circular (such as the border between Italy and San Marino), or even have multiple disconnected and nested cyclic fragments (the border between Belgium and Netherlands, due to the Baarle-Nassau and Baarle-Hartog enclaves). To identify arbitrarily large or small segments of borders, see formsBorderPart. See also BorderBetweenFn, to which borderBetweenRegions is a (canonically) corresponding predicate.
label: Border Between Regions
borderBetweenRegions

comment: (synonymousExternalConcept THING SOURCE STRING) means that as it occurs in the external data source SOURCE, the string STRING denotes THING.
label: Synonymous External Concept
synonymousExternalConcept

comment: (kePredArgWeakSuggestionInverse PRED N BINPRED) means that if the relation expression (PRED . ARGS) is known, and ARGN appears as the Nth argument in (PRED . ARGS) it is weakly suggested that Cyc know there exists a THING such that (BINPRED THING ARGN).
label: Ke Pred Arg Weak Suggestion Inverse
kePredArgWeakSuggestionInverse

comment: (touchesWith AGENT OBJECT2 OBJECT3) means that AGENT touches OBJECT2 with OBJECT3. This implies (touches AGENT OBJECT3) and (touches OBJECT2 OBJECT3), but not (touches AGENT OBJECT2): AGENT may or not be touching OBJECT2 in the sense of touches. For example, if #$Zaiss touches POSSUM45 with the end of long STICK87, opposite to the end he is holding, then although (touchesWith #$Zaiss POSSUM45 STICK87), it is not the case the (touches #$Zaiss POSSUM45). Whereas if #$Zaiss touches POSSUM45 with his hand, or with a gloved hand, then it is true that (touches #$Zaiss POSSUM45) (see the comment of touches).
label: Touches With
touchesWith

comment: (defaultValueForParameter PROGRAM PARAMETER VALUE) means that in program PROGRAM, the parameter PARAMETER has a default value of VALUE. Assertions on this predicate are descriptive, not prescriptive. So, to assert (defaultValueForParameter CycLReformulator WFFEnforcementRFParameter RelationInMtWFFCheckInReformulation) does not set the default value for that parameter, but rather merely reports that the WFF-enforcement parameter of the reformulator is set by default to RelationInMtWFFCheckInReformulation.
label: Default Value For Parameter
defaultValueForParameter

comment: A ternary complex action predicate. (doDefineProgramFunctionFromAlgorithm PROGRAMMER FILE ALGORITHM) means that PROGRAMMER appends a declaration of a program function that implements ALGORITHM to the computer source code file FILE.
label: Do Define Program Function From Algorithm
doDefineProgramFunctionFromAlgorithm

comment:
(csqlOperatorToSQLOperator CSQL-OP SQL-OP DBMS-TYPE SYNTAX) tells the CSQL to SQL translator that in order to translate a CSQL literal with operator CSQL-OP into an SQL string literal with operator SQL-OP that is valid for evaluation by DBMS-TYPE, the translator should use the translation syntax SYNTAX. For example, the sentence 
(csqlOperatorToSQLOperator CSQLPlusFn "+" PostgreSQL SQLOperatorSyntax_Infix)
tells the translator that when translating a literal such as (CSQLPlusFn 1 2) into SQL which is to be evaulated by a PostgreSQL DBMS, it should infix the operator between its arguments, so that the resultant SQL literal would be "1 + 2".
label: Csql Operator To SQL Operator
csqlOperatorToSQLOperator

comment: (crit PART DEV SIT ROLE) This component (PART) is critical to a particular behavior (SIT and ROLE) of the device (DEV) of which it is a physical part.
label: Critical To Behavior
criticalToBehavior

comment: (formerName_Date THING DATE OLDNAME) means that before the date DATE, the thing THING was named OLDNAME. The name after that date changed or it took on an additional name. If the date of name change is unknown, see also formerName.
label: Former Name Date
formerName-Date

comment: (findAnalogs ?Num ?Src-Mt ?Src ?Tgt-Mt ?Tgt) causes ?Tgt to become successively bound to the ?Num best analogs (according to structure-mapping metrics) for the source concept ?Src as defined source domain microtheory ?Src-Mt in the target domain ?Tgt-Mt. That is, find the ?Tgt-Mt equivalent of ?Src as it is defined in ?Src-Mt. Example: (findAnalogs 4 #$DesertShieldMt Iraq #$Y1Phase2-AllStagesMt ?What) should cause ?What to be bound to Iran and 3 other values. See also findAnalog, structureMaps and structureDiffs.
label: Find Analogs
findAnalogs

comment: conflictOfInterest(X Y Z) means that agent X affects whether some proposition P will be true, X has a vested interest in both agents Y and Z, and Y and Z want different (conflicting) truth values for P.
label: Conflict Of Interest
conflictOfInterest

comment:
(intervalOfTypeLiesBetween_Inclusive INTERVAL TYPE EARLY LATE) means that the instance of TimeInterval INTERVAL is an interval of type TYPE that is subsumed by (c.f., temporallySubsumes) the interval started by (c.f., temporallyStartedBy) the earliest interval of TYPE that temporally intersects (c.f., temporallyIntersects) the instance of TemporalThing EARLY, and finished by (see temporallyFinishedBy) the latest interval of TYPE that temporally intersects the instance of TemporalThing LATE. For example, 
   (intervalOfTypeLiesBetween_Inclusive
           (MonthFn June (YearFn 1990)) CalendarMonth
           (DayFn 4 (MonthFn January (YearFn 1968))) Now)
means that the June 1990 is one of the instances of CalendarMonth that occurs during the interval formed from the first month that intersects (DayFn 4 (MonthFn January (YearFn 1968))) -- namely January 1968 -- and the last month that, as you read this, intersects the referent of the indexical Now.

Note that though in the above example, EARLY and LATE are both instances of TimeInterval, EARLY and LATE can be any instance of TemporalThing for which a temporally intersecting interval of TYPE can be found: 

   (intervalOfTypeLiesBetween_Inclusive
           (YearFn 1945) CalendarYear
           (EndFn #$WorldWarII)
           (OrganizationFoundingFn #$LebaneseHizballah))
means that the year 1945 is an instance of CalendarYear subsumed by the interval started by the year 1945 (the year in which WWII ended) and finished by the year 1982 (the year in which Hizballah was founded). Similarly, 
   (intervalOfTypeLiesBetween_Inclusive
           (YearFn 1945) CalendarYear #$WorldWarII
           (OrganizationFoundingFn #$LebaneseHizballah))
means that 1945 is a year that lies between the years 1939 and 1983. See also intervalOfTypeLiesBetween_Exclusive.
label: Interval Of Type Lies Between Inclusive
intervalOfTypeLiesBetween-Inclusive

comment:
(latestIntersectingIntervalOfType TEMPORAL-THING INTERVAL TYPE) means that the instance of TimeInterval INTERVAL is the latest interval of type TYPE that intersects (c.f., temporallyIntersects) the temporal extent of the instance of TemporalThing TEMPORAL-THING. For example, 
    (latestIntersectingIntervalOfType #$WorldWarII 
       (YearFn 1945) CalendarYear)
means that the year 1945 is the last calendar year that intersects WWII. See also earliestIntersectingIntervalOfType and latestSubsumedIntervalOfType.
label: Latest Intersecting Interval Of Type
latestIntersectingIntervalOfType

comment: Payments are made to ARG1 for events of type ARG2 during time ARG3 of total ARG4.
label: Payment In For Type
paymentInForType

comment: (termPhrases TERM CONSTRAINT STRING) means that STRING is a word or phrase that denotes TERM and that meets CONSTRAINT. CONSTRAINT is an instance of TermPhrasesConstraint (q.v.). For example, CONSTRAINT may be an instance of SpeechPartPredicate (such as singular or gerund); an instance of SpeechPart (such as Noun or Verb); or an instance of StringIndexingSlot (such as nameString). If CONSTRAINT is a predicate, assertions on its spec-preds will also be searched: thus, the query (termPhrases TERM nameString ?STRING) will also return strings asserted of TERM using preferredNameString. Similarly, if CONSTRAINT is a collection, assertions related to its specializations will be searched: thus, the query (termPhrases TERM ProperNoun ?STRING) will return ProperCountNouns and ProperMassNouns that refer to TERM. If CONSTRAINT is ProperNameString, assertions on predicates whose arg2Isa ProperNameString will be searched. If CONSTRAINT is CharacterString, no constraints will be imposed, and all lexifications of TERM are returned.
label: Term Phrases
termPhrases

comment: In instances of ARG1, entries on ARG2 must be in the user-rights relation ARG4 to entries on ARG3. For example, (userRightsConstraints BUYING SELLER objectOfPossessionTransfer FullUseRights).
label: User Rights Constraints
userRightsConstraints

comment: A predicate used to state the number of shares being offered for sale at the asked market price of a company's Stock (of a given class, e.g. common or preferred) at a given time. (stockSize_Ask NUM STOCK EXCHANGE MONEY) means that there are NUM shares of STOCK being offered for sale at the latter's current stockPrice_Ask (q.v.) at DATE on the exchange EXCHANGE. Cf. stockSize_Bid.
label: ask size
stockSize-Ask

comment: This predicate expresses the relationship between an adverb, a word sense, a subcategorization frame, and a CycL expression used to denote the adverb.
label: Adverb Sem Trans
adverbSemTrans

comment: (phraseNthDaughter MOTHER N DAUGHTER) means that DAUGHTER is the Nth daughter of MOTHER.
label: Phrase Nth Daughter
phraseNthDaughter
Event Set
eventSet
comment:
A UnaryPredicate that applies to a Set_Mathematical. (sampleSpace SET) means that, for the purposes of probabilistic reasoning, SET is the set of subsets of the sample space (see sampleSpace) that are being reasoned with. Intuitively, the elements of the event set are the "events" or "propositions" that are assigned probabilities.

Suppose, for example, that we want to reason about a single roll of a die. We would want to consider just six possible worlds, corresponding to the six possible outcomes. Thus our sample space might be (TheSet 1 2 3 4 5 6), with 1 representing the world in which 1 is rolled, etc. Our event set, then, might simply be the powerset of (TheSet 1 2 3 4 5 6). Thus we would assert: 

(eventSet (PowerSetFn (TheSet 1 2 3 4 5 6))).
The event set, F, is required to be an algebra over the sample space, W; that is, F must be a set of subsets of W that contains W itself and is closed under union and complementation.

(distanceAlongPath OBJ1 OBJ2 PATH DIST) means that the distance between OBJ1 and OBJ2, traveling along PATH, is DIST. If PATH is not Straight, then DIST will be larger the length of the shortest straight line between OBJ1 and OBJ2. See also distanceBetween which does not require reference to a pathway.
Mx4rwLSVCpwpEbGdrcN5Y29ycA: distances between points on a path
label: distance between points on a path
distanceAlongPath

comment:
(agentTypeSufficientForTruthWRTRole BINARY-ROLE-PRED AGENT-TYPE SENTENCE) holds just in case SENTENCE is a sentence that describes some state of affairs in which an agent plays some particular role, BINARY-ROLE-PRED, and that agent's being an instance of AGENT-TYPE is sufficient for the truth of SENTENCE. For instance, a particular movie theater may charge only five dollars if the ticket purchaser is a member of a particular film club. In that case, a sufficient condition on the truth of the statement that the purchase price of a ticket is five dollars is that the purchaser is a member of that film club. In CycL we might represent an example of this as 
(agentTypeSufficientForTruthWRTRole buyer (MemberFn AustinFilmClub)
   (relationAllInstance purchasePrice 
     (SubcollectionOfWithRelationToFn  EntertainmentPerformanceTicket
       publisherOfIBO #$AmcCourthousePlaza8-CinemaOrganization) 
     (Dollar_UnitedStates 5)))
We read the above in English as "the purchase price of tickets issued from Amc Courthouse Plaza8 Cinema is five dollars if the buyer is a member of the Austin film club" .
label: Agent Type Sufficient For Truth WRT Role
agentTypeSufficientForTruthWRTRole

comment: In a generated English phrase, the Cyc term arg1 corresponds best to the phrase arg4, when used as part of speech arg2 with restriction arg3.
label: Gen Phrase
genPhrase

comment: (contactToxicityFor STUFF ORGTYPE TOXLEVEL) means that under ordinary circumstances, stuff has the Toxicity TOXLEVEL for instances of ORGTYPE that come into skin contact with it.
label: skin toxicity for a type of organism
contactToxicityFor

comment:
(multiWordStringSenseExtensionBrokeredByPred WORD SPEECH-PART-1 DENOTATION SPEECH-PART-2 EXTENSION BINARY-PREDICATE LIST) means that the fact that 
   (multiWordStringSenseExtension WORD SPEECH-PART-1 DENOTATION SPEECH-PART-2 EXTENSION LIST)
is explained in part by the fact that 
   (BINARY-PREDICATE ARG1 ARG2)
for some ARG1 and ARG2 such that 
   (multiWordString LIST WORD SPEECH-PART-1 ARG1)
.

The reason why this sense extension is only partly explained by the above considerations reflects the fact that due to Cyc's incomplete knowledge, there will be many cases where BINARY-PREDICATE is not an instance of SenseExtendingPredicate, and so cannot reliably broker sense extensions from SPEECH-PART-1 to SPEECH-PART-2 for any word denoting one of its arg1s. Rather, there is a possibly unreified specialization SPEC-PRED of BINARY-PRED (see genlPreds) that is an instance of SenseExtendingPredicate, and the fact that (SPEC-PRED ARG1 ARG2) fully explains the sense extension in question.
label: Multi Word String Sense Extension Brokered By Pred
multiWordStringSenseExtensionBrokeredByPred

comment: (typeMaximizesTypeWRTType SIT-TYPE-1 SLOT SIT-TYPE-2) holds just in case being the performer or doer of instances of SIT-TYPE-1 will tend to maximize the second argument of SLOT with respect to SIT-TYPE-2.
label: Type Maximizes Type WRT Type
typeMaximizesTypeWRTType

comment:
A ternary predicate that relates a BinaryPredicate to a Collection to a Set_Mathematical. (slotInverseValueRangeWRTCollection PRED COL SET) means that SET is the set of all (and only those) things that are related to some instance of COL by PRED. That is, a thing OBJ is an element of SET if and only if there is at least one instance INST of COL such that (PRED OBJ INST) holds. For example, the inverse value-range of cityInState for State_UnitedStates is the set of US cities.

See also slotValueRangeWRTCollection.
label: Slot Inverse Value Range WRT Collection
slotInverseValueRangeWRTCollection

comment: A CanonicalizerDirectivePredicate (q.v.) used (in conjunction with a CanonicalizerDirective) to control the behavior of the CycCanonicalizer. (canonicalizerDirectiveForArg RELN N DIRECTIVE) means that the CycCanonicalizer obeys DIRECTIVE when canonicalizing the Nth argument of a CycLFormula whose main (or "0th place") operator denotes RELN. See the instances of CanonicalizerDirective for more information on how particular directives affect canonicalization. Also see canonicalizerDirectiveForArgAndRest and canonicalizerDirectiveForAllArgs.
label: Canonicalizer Directive For Arg
canonicalizerDirectiveForArg

comment: (cooperatesInInstancesOfEventTypeDuring AGT1 AGT2 EVENT-TYPE INTERVAL) holds just in case there is at least one instance of EVENT-TYPE, EVT, in which (cooperatingParticipants EVT AGT1) and (cooperatingParticipants EVT AGT2) holds and the date of EVT is subsumed by INTEVAL.
label: Cooperates In Instances Of Event Type During
cooperatesInInstancesOfEventTypeDuring

comment:
A KEFacilitationPredicate and RuleMacroPredicate. (keSuggestionPreds_InsSpec COL1 BINPRED COL2) means that for every known instance INS1 of COL1, it is suggested that there be some specialization SPEC2 of COL2 such that (BINPRED INS1 SPEC2) is known in the knowledge base.

For example,

(keSuggestionPreds_InsSpec PersonTypeByOccupation agentTypePerformsWorkOfType PurposefulAction)

means that for every known instance P-TYPE of PersonTypeByOccupation, it is suggested that there be some specialization ACT-TYPE of PurposefulAction such that (agentTypePerformsWorkOfType P-TYPE ACT-TYPE) is known in the knowledge base.

See also keSuggestionPredsInverse_InsSpec.
label: Ke Suggestion Preds Ins Spec
keSuggestionPreds-InsSpec

comment: An ActionPredicate relating instances of IntelligentAgent with instances of #$ProgramFaultAttribute, ComputerProgram_CW, and ComputationalSystem. (exploitFaultOfProgramOnSystem AGENT FAULT PROGRAM SYSTEM) means that AGENT exploits the FAULT of PROGRAM when PROGRAM is running on SYSTEM.
label: Exploit Fault Of Program On System With Instrument
exploitFaultOfProgramOnSystemWithInstrument

comment:
A TernaryPredicate that relates a Collection to a Collection to a QuantitySlot. (typesGreaterThanWRTScalar COL1 COL2 SLOT) means that, in general, instances of COL1 have a higher value for SLOT than do instances of COL2. More specifically, if each of the following hold: 
  (typesGreaterThanWRTScalar COL1 COL2 SLOT)
  (isa INST1 COL1)
  (isa INST2 COL2)
then the following holds: 
  (likelihood (largerThan INST1 INST2 SLOT) (HighToVeryHighAmountFn ProbabilityInterval)).
label: Types Greater Than WRT Scalar
typesGreaterThanWRTScalar

comment: (softwareOnComputerHasFault_ReportIndexed SOFT COMP FAULT REP) means that the software SOFT, as it is installed and configured on COMP, manifests the FAULT reported in the ComputerVulnerabilityReport_CW REP.
label: Software On Computer Has Fault Report Indexed
softwareOnComputerHasFault-ReportIndexed

comment: This predicate relates two things in terms of some BinaryPredicate that relates them to similar instances of a given collection of collections. (similarInValueOnRelation T1 T2 BINPRED) means that there are similar collections COL1 and COL2, such that (BINPRED T1 COL1) and (BINPRED T2 COL2). The minimum notion of similarity is that COL1 and COL2 be instances of the same "faceting" sort of collection. For instance, HighMountainousRegion and HillyRegion are both instances of the collection RegionTypeByHilliness. Furthermore, if the collection type to which they belong is ordered (see CollectionWithAnEventLikeOrder), then COL1 and COL2 should be "close" together in the ordering. For instance HillyRegion is closer to HighMountainousRegion than FlatRegion in the ordering on RegionTypeByHilliness. So, it is likely that a region, REG1, such that (terrainType REG1 HighMountainousRegion) stands in similarInValueOnRelation via terrainType to a region, REG2, such that (terrainType REG2 HillyRegion). But not likely that it stands in such a relation to an instance of FlatRegion. See also resemblesInValue.
label: Similar In Value On Relation
similarInValueOnRelation

comment: (givesSupportToAgentOfCategory GIVER RECEIVER CATEGORY) means that GIVER gives some positive amount of support, of category CATEGORY, to RECEIVER. For example, (givesSupportToAgent UnitedStatesOfAmerica Egypt MilitarySupportQuantity) means that the US gives some positive amount of military support to Egypt. This predicate is the 'type-level' version of givesSupportToAgent, and so whenever an assertion with givesSupportToAgentOfCategory as arg zero is true, so will be some possible assertion with givesSupportToAgent as arg zero not, in general, be 'redundant with' the assertion using the latter predicate, as the latter will generally be more specific. This predicate is suited to making assertions about inter-agent support relationships in the presence of limited information either about the amount of support given, or about the criteria, in context, for a given amount of support counting as 'high', 'low' 'medium', and so forth. This predicate is also suited to formulating rules for which particular degrees of support are irrelevant.
label: support
givesSupportToAgentOfCategory

comment: (enterLoginInformationForAccountAtComputer AGENT ACCT COMP) means that AGENT enters the usernameForAccount and passwordForAccount for ACCT at COMP. Note that COMP must be a nodeInAccountSystem for the AccountSystem of which ACCT is a UserAccount, and that AGENT must have physical access (hasPhysicalAccess) to COMP.
label: Enter Login Information For Account At Computer
enterLoginInformationForAccountAtComputer

comment: (structureCorrespondences ?Src ?Src-Mt ?Tgt ?Tgt-Mt ?Src-Corr ?Tgt-Corr) returns, via multiple successive bindings of the variables ?Src-Corr and ?Tgt-Corr, corresponding entities in the analogy between ?Src and ?Tgt.
label: Structure Correspondences
structureCorrespondences

comment: An assertion of the form (deathRateDuring PLACE ORG-TYPE REAL DATE) states that measurements made of the population during the Date DATE indicate that for every 1000 people in the population of the GeographicalRegion PLACE, REAL number of people died. For example, an assertion of the form (deathRateDuring Syria HomoSapiens 3.4 (YearFn 2005)) states that records indicate that during 2005, for every 1000 citizens of Syria, 3.4 people died. This represents a measurement and estimate.
label: Death Rate During
deathRateDuring
Agent Linked To Action Via Profile
agentLinkedToActionViaProfile

comment: (doesTypeWithFrequency AGENT TYPE FREQUENCY) says that AGENT plays the role of doneBy in instances of TYPE with FREQUENCY.
label: Does Type With Frequency
doesTypeWithFrequency

comment: (argSometimesIsa RELATION POSITIVE-INTERGER-N COLLECTION) means that semantic well-formedness requires that anything given as the Nth argument to RELN must be an instance of COL at sometime or other. More precisely, if (argSometimesIsa RELATION POSITIVE-INTERGER-N COLLECTION) then in order to assert: (RELATION ARG-N ... OTHER-ARGS)<MT TIME PAR>, it must be the case that there exists some time interval, t, such that (isa ARG-N COLLECTION)<MT t PAR>.
label: Arg Sometimes Isa
argSometimesIsa

comment: (removeProgram AGENT COMPUTER PROGRAM) means that AGENT removes PROGRAM from COMPUTER.
label: Remove Program
removeProgram

comment: This predicate is the predicateUnion of schemaIntegrationPredicateForInputExplicitRDSSet and schemaIntegrationPredicateForInputImplicitRDSSet.
label: Schema Integration Predicate For Input RDS Set
schemaIntegrationPredicateForInputRDSSet

comment: (exportToQuotaDuring REGION1 PRODUCT-TYPE REGION2 THING AMOUNT) means that the ScalarInterval AMOUNT is a measure of the export quota of instances of the ProductType PRODUCT-TYPE for the GeographicalRegion REGION1 to the GeographicalRegion REGION2 during the temporal extent of the TemporalThing THING. (Of course, the existence of export quotas is the exception rather than the rule.) THING will often be a calendar time period; but it may also be, for instance, a particular Event. In the case of oil exports, for example, AMOUNT might be a Volume (a number of barrels) indicating the total quantity of oil REGION1 is allowed to export to REGION2. Alternatively, AMOUNT might be a Rate, characterizing the average rate of export, under the quota, of instances of PRODUCT-TYPE by REGION1 to REGION2 during the temporal extent of THING. Oil exports, for example, might be expressed in terms of so many million barrels per day.
label: Export To Quota During
exportToQuotaDuring
Sksi Source Activated
sksiSourceActivated
comment: (sksiSourceActivated SKS) is true iff SKS has been turned 'activated' for querying. This is not sufficient alone to guarantee that Cyc can query SKS. In particular, it may the case that SKS has been activated but the removal module data structures for SKS have not been registered yet (see sksiSourceRegistered). Furthermore, it may be the case that Cyc cannot establish a connection to SKS (see sksiSourceAccessible). Finally, see also sksiSourceQueryable which checks all three conditions.
(onlyTypePlaysRoleInSituationType SITTYPE ACTORTYPE ROLE) means that in any instance of SITTYPE, whatever plays the role ROLE is expected to be an instance of ACTORTYPE.

comment: A quaternary predicate. (inheritRolePlayers_SitTypeToSubSitType SUPER ROLE1 SUB ROLE2) means that every instance of SUPER has an instance of SUB subSituations, and furthermore if (isa INST1 SUPER) and (ROLE1 INST1 ACTOR) and (subSituations INST1 INST2) then (ROLE2 INST2 ACTOR). For example, in BiologyMt, (inheritRolePlayers_SitTypeToSubSitType KillingByOrganism_Unique organismKilled Dying bodilyDoer) would mean that every killing of a single organism has a subevent in which the killed organism dies.
